1
00:01:24,285 --> 00:01:27,455
MAN 1: I owe everything
to George Bailey.

2
00:01:27,488 --> 00:01:29,723
Help him, dear Father.

3
00:01:29,757 --> 00:01:32,826
MAN 2: Joseph, Jesus and Mary,

4
00:01:32,860 --> 00:01:35,929
help my friend Mr. Bailey.

5
00:01:35,963 --> 00:01:39,400
WOMAN 1:
Help my son George tonight.

6
00:01:39,433 --> 00:01:41,402
MAN 3: He never thinks
about himself, God.

7
00:01:41,435 --> 00:01:43,171
That's why he's in trouble.

8
00:01:43,204 --> 00:01:44,572
MAN 4: George is a good guy.

9
00:01:45,539 --> 00:01:46,807
Give him a break, God.

10
00:01:47,608 --> 00:01:49,042
WOMAN 2: I love him,
dear Lord.

11
00:01:49,076 --> 00:01:51,379
Watch over him tonight.

12
00:01:51,412 --> 00:01:52,813
GIRL: Please, God.

13
00:01:52,846 --> 00:01:55,183
Something's
the matter with Daddy.

14
00:01:55,216 --> 00:01:58,051
GIRL 2: Please
bring Daddy back.

15
00:01:58,085 --> 00:01:59,687
(PEOPLE PRAYING)
Please
bring Daddy home.

16
00:01:59,720 --> 00:02:02,290
WOMAN 1:
Watch over him tonight.

17
00:02:02,323 --> 00:02:04,625
GIRL 2: Please
bring Daddy back.

18
00:02:08,529 --> 00:02:10,598
FRANKLIN:
Hello, Joseph. Trouble?

19
00:02:10,631 --> 00:02:13,301
JOSEPH: Looks like
we'll have to
send someone down.

20
00:02:13,334 --> 00:02:14,902
A lot of people
asking for help

21
00:02:14,935 --> 00:02:16,470
for a man named
George Bailey.

22
00:02:16,504 --> 00:02:18,071
George Bailey?

23
00:02:18,105 --> 00:02:20,641
Yes. Tonight's
his crucial night.
You're right.

24
00:02:20,674 --> 00:02:23,577
We'll have to send
someone down immediately.
Whose turn is it?

25
00:02:23,611 --> 00:02:26,146
That's why I came
to see you, sir.

26
00:02:26,180 --> 00:02:28,682
It's that clockmaker's
turn again.

27
00:02:28,716 --> 00:02:30,384
(CHUCKLING) Oh, Clarence.

28
00:02:30,418 --> 00:02:32,019
Hasn't got his
wings yet, has he?

29
00:02:32,052 --> 00:02:33,987
We've passed him
up right along.

30
00:02:34,021 --> 00:02:37,525
Because, you know, sir,
he's got the IQ of a rabbit.

31
00:02:37,558 --> 00:02:41,061
Yes,
but he's got the faith
of a child. Simple.

32
00:02:41,094 --> 00:02:43,130
Joseph,
send for Clarence.

33
00:02:46,567 --> 00:02:47,801
CLARENCE:
You sent for me, sir?

34
00:02:47,835 --> 00:02:49,169
Yes, Clarence.

35
00:02:49,203 --> 00:02:51,239
A man down on Earth
needs our help.

36
00:02:51,272 --> 00:02:52,773
Splendid. Is he sick?

37
00:02:52,806 --> 00:02:54,942
No, worse.
He's discouraged.

38
00:02:54,975 --> 00:02:57,611
At exactly 10:45 p.m.
Earth time,

39
00:02:57,645 --> 00:02:59,747
that man will be
thinking seriously

40
00:02:59,780 --> 00:03:01,782
of throwing away
God's greatest gift.

41
00:03:01,815 --> 00:03:03,651
Oh, dear, dear,
his life?

42
00:03:03,684 --> 00:03:05,486
Then I've only
an hour to dress.

43
00:03:05,519 --> 00:03:07,054
What are they
wearing now?

44
00:03:07,087 --> 00:03:10,023
You will spend that hour
getting acquainted
with George Bailey.

45
00:03:10,057 --> 00:03:13,093
Sir, if I should
accomplish this mission,

46
00:03:13,126 --> 00:03:16,630
I mean, uh,
might I perhaps
win my wings?

47
00:03:16,664 --> 00:03:19,166
I've been waiting
for over 200 years
now, sir,

48
00:03:19,199 --> 00:03:20,801
and people are
beginning to talk.

49
00:03:20,834 --> 00:03:22,370
What's that book
you've got there?

50
00:03:22,403 --> 00:03:24,605
Oh, The Adventures
of Tom Sawyer.

51
00:03:24,638 --> 00:03:27,074
Clarence, you do a good job
with George Bailey

52
00:03:27,107 --> 00:03:28,476
and you'll get
your wings.

53
00:03:28,509 --> 00:03:30,311
Oh, thank you, sir.
Thank you.

54
00:03:30,344 --> 00:03:33,146
Poor George.
Sit down.

55
00:03:33,180 --> 00:03:34,382
Sit down?
What are we...

56
00:03:34,415 --> 00:03:36,149
If you're going
to help a man,

57
00:03:36,183 --> 00:03:38,586
you want to know
something about him,
don't you?

58
00:03:38,619 --> 00:03:40,153
Well, naturally,
of course. I...

59
00:03:40,187 --> 00:03:41,522
Now, keep
your eyes open.

60
00:03:42,356 --> 00:03:43,524
See the town?

61
00:03:43,557 --> 00:03:46,294
CLARENCE: Where?
I--I don't see a thing.

62
00:03:46,327 --> 00:03:49,229
Oh, I forgot.
You haven't got
your wings yet.

63
00:03:49,263 --> 00:03:51,064
Now, look,
I'll help you out.

64
00:03:51,098 --> 00:03:52,900
Concentrate.

65
00:03:52,933 --> 00:03:54,735
Begin to see something?

66
00:03:54,768 --> 00:03:57,538
Why, yes.
This is amazing.

67
00:03:57,571 --> 00:04:00,173
If you ever get
your wings, you'll
see all by yourself.

68
00:04:00,207 --> 00:04:02,009
Oh, wonderful.

69
00:04:02,042 --> 00:04:04,812
(ALL CHEERING)
Yay! Yippee!

70
00:04:04,845 --> 00:04:06,880
Okay, boys, let's go.

71
00:04:06,914 --> 00:04:08,649
CLARENCE:
Hey, who's that?

72
00:04:08,682 --> 00:04:10,584
JOSEPH: That's your
problem. George Bailey.

73
00:04:10,618 --> 00:04:11,719
A boy?

74
00:04:11,752 --> 00:04:14,855
That's him
when he was 12
back in 1919.

75
00:04:14,888 --> 00:04:18,258
Something happens here
you'll have to
remember later on.

76
00:04:18,959 --> 00:04:20,728
BOY: Come on, Marty.

77
00:04:20,761 --> 00:04:22,630
Let's go, Marty!

78
00:04:23,431 --> 00:04:24,932
Attaboy, Marty.

79
00:04:25,833 --> 00:04:27,501
Hee-haw!

80
00:04:27,535 --> 00:04:30,203
(BOYS CHEERING)
Let's go, Sam. Hee-haw, Sammy!

81
00:04:30,237 --> 00:04:34,742
Here comes the scare-baby,
my kid brother Harry Bailey.

82
00:04:34,775 --> 00:04:36,510
I'm not scared.

83
00:04:37,611 --> 00:04:39,380
BOY: Come on, Harry.

84
00:04:39,413 --> 00:04:41,114
GEORGE: Let's go, Harry!

85
00:04:41,148 --> 00:04:43,751
Come on, Harry!
Come on, Harry!

86
00:04:43,784 --> 00:04:45,819
GEORGE: Come on, Harry!
BOY: Come on, Harry!

87
00:04:46,487 --> 00:04:47,955
Help, George, help!

88
00:04:47,988 --> 00:04:49,089
Help!

89
00:04:50,190 --> 00:04:52,793
Don't worry, Harry.
I'm coming!

90
00:04:52,826 --> 00:04:55,195
HARRY: Help!
Hang on, Harry!

91
00:04:55,228 --> 00:04:57,665
Help.
Make a chain--chain, gang.

92
00:04:57,698 --> 00:05:00,568
JOSEPH: George
saved his brother's
life that day,

93
00:05:00,601 --> 00:05:04,405
but he caught
a bad cold which
infected his left ear.

94
00:05:04,438 --> 00:05:06,674
Cost him his hearing
in that ear.

95
00:05:06,707 --> 00:05:09,042
It was weeks
before he was
able to go back

96
00:05:09,076 --> 00:05:12,446
to his after-school
job at old man Gower's
drugstore.

97
00:05:13,213 --> 00:05:14,382
Mr. Potter.

98
00:05:14,415 --> 00:05:16,750
CLARENCE:
Who's that, a king?

99
00:05:16,784 --> 00:05:18,752
FRANKLIN:
That's Henry F. Potter,

100
00:05:18,786 --> 00:05:22,656
the richest
and meanest man
in the county.

101
00:05:22,690 --> 00:05:23,791
(BOYS WHISTLING)

102
00:05:26,660 --> 00:05:29,363
BOYS: Hee-haw! Hee-haw!
BOYS: Hee-haw! Hee-haw!

103
00:05:29,397 --> 00:05:31,098
BOY: Go to work, slave.

104
00:05:32,132 --> 00:05:34,301
Don't worry,
we'll take care of it.

105
00:05:35,736 --> 00:05:37,738
Wish I had a million dollars.

106
00:05:38,372 --> 00:05:40,040
Hot dog!

107
00:05:40,073 --> 00:05:41,341
(WHISTLING)

108
00:05:43,477 --> 00:05:45,446
It's me, Mr. Gower.
George Bailey.

109
00:05:45,479 --> 00:05:46,514
You're late.

110
00:05:46,547 --> 00:05:47,848
Yes, sir.

111
00:05:56,089 --> 00:05:57,791
Hello, George.

112
00:05:57,825 --> 00:05:59,126
Hello, Mary.

113
00:05:59,660 --> 00:06:00,828
Hello, Violet.

114
00:06:00,861 --> 00:06:02,496
Two cents'
worth of shoelaces?

115
00:06:02,530 --> 00:06:03,931
She was here first.

116
00:06:03,964 --> 00:06:05,866
I'm still thinking.

117
00:06:05,899 --> 00:06:07,000
Shoelaces?

118
00:06:07,034 --> 00:06:08,636
Please, Georgie.

119
00:06:09,136 --> 00:06:10,337
I like him.

120
00:06:10,370 --> 00:06:12,172
You like every boy.

121
00:06:12,205 --> 00:06:14,041
What's wrong with that?

122
00:06:14,074 --> 00:06:15,576
Here you are.

123
00:06:16,410 --> 00:06:17,511
Help me down?

124
00:06:17,545 --> 00:06:18,979
Help you down?

125
00:06:23,116 --> 00:06:24,618
(CASH REGISTER DINGING)

126
00:06:26,153 --> 00:06:28,021
Made up your mind yet?

127
00:06:28,055 --> 00:06:29,923
I'll take chocolate.

128
00:06:29,957 --> 00:06:31,324
With coconuts?

129
00:06:31,358 --> 00:06:32,926
I don't like coconuts.

130
00:06:32,960 --> 00:06:34,928
You don't like coconuts?

131
00:06:34,962 --> 00:06:38,165
Say, brainless,
don't you know where
coconuts come from?

132
00:06:38,799 --> 00:06:40,233
Lookit here.

133
00:06:40,267 --> 00:06:43,737
From Tahiti,
the Fiji islands,
the Coral Sea.

134
00:06:43,771 --> 00:06:46,940
A new magazine.
I never saw it before.

135
00:06:46,974 --> 00:06:50,177
Of course you never.
Only us explorers can get it.

136
00:06:50,210 --> 00:06:51,912
I've been nominated
for membership

137
00:06:51,945 --> 00:06:54,682
in the National
Geographic Society.

138
00:06:55,616 --> 00:06:57,985
Is this the ear
you can't hear on?

139
00:06:58,018 --> 00:07:01,421
George Bailey, I'll love you
till the day I die.

140
00:07:01,455 --> 00:07:04,458
I'm going out
exploring someday. You watch.

141
00:07:04,492 --> 00:07:06,159
And I'm gonna have
a couple of harems

142
00:07:06,193 --> 00:07:07,795
and maybe three
or four wives.

143
00:07:07,828 --> 00:07:09,262
Wait and see.

144
00:07:09,296 --> 00:07:10,531
(WHISTLING)

145
00:07:11,999 --> 00:07:14,468
GOWER: George. George!

146
00:07:14,502 --> 00:07:15,603
Yes, sir?

147
00:07:15,636 --> 00:07:18,271
(SLURRING) You're not paid
to be a canary.

148
00:07:18,305 --> 00:07:19,607
No, sir.

149
00:07:46,967 --> 00:07:50,103
Mr. Gower, do you want
something? Anything?

150
00:07:50,137 --> 00:07:51,839
No.

151
00:07:51,872 --> 00:07:53,741
Anything I can do
back here?

152
00:07:53,774 --> 00:07:54,975
No.

153
00:07:55,008 --> 00:07:56,510
I'll get them, sir.

154
00:07:56,544 --> 00:07:59,780
Quick, take those capsules
over to Mrs. Blaine.

155
00:08:00,614 --> 00:08:01,849
She's waiting for them.

156
00:08:01,882 --> 00:08:03,216
Yes, sir.

157
00:08:25,773 --> 00:08:27,908
They have
the diphtheria there,
haven't they, sir?

158
00:08:27,941 --> 00:08:29,342
Yeah.

159
00:08:29,376 --> 00:08:31,111
Is it a charge, sir?

160
00:08:31,144 --> 00:08:32,546
Yes, George.

161
00:08:33,313 --> 00:08:35,583
Mr. Gower, I...
Oh, get going.

162
00:08:35,616 --> 00:08:36,884
Yes, sir.

163
00:09:02,109 --> 00:09:03,410
(BILLY EXCLAIMING)

164
00:09:03,443 --> 00:09:05,478
Avast there, Captain Cook.
Where you heading?

165
00:09:05,512 --> 00:09:06,880
I've got to see Pop,
Uncle Billy.

166
00:09:06,914 --> 00:09:08,616
Some other time, George.
It's important.

167
00:09:08,649 --> 00:09:11,484
There's a squall in there.
It's shaping up into a storm.

168
00:09:11,518 --> 00:09:13,687
TILLY: Uncle Billy, telephone.
Who is it?

169
00:09:13,721 --> 00:09:14,955
Bank examiner.

170
00:09:14,988 --> 00:09:16,556
Bank examiner?

171
00:09:16,590 --> 00:09:18,759
I should have
called him yesterday.

172
00:09:18,792 --> 00:09:20,093
Switch it inside.

173
00:09:22,262 --> 00:09:23,731
BAILEY: I'm not crying,
Mr. Potter.

174
00:09:23,764 --> 00:09:25,666
Well, you're begging.
That's a whole lot worse.

175
00:09:25,699 --> 00:09:27,534
All I'm asking
for is 30 days more.

176
00:09:27,567 --> 00:09:28,836
Pop.
Just a minute, Son.

177
00:09:28,869 --> 00:09:31,805
Just 30 short days.
I'll dig up that
$5,000 somehow.

178
00:09:31,839 --> 00:09:33,173
Shove me up,
shove me up.
Pop.

179
00:09:33,206 --> 00:09:35,075
Just a minute.
Have you put
any real pressure

180
00:09:35,108 --> 00:09:37,611
on these people of yours
to pay those mortgages?

181
00:09:37,645 --> 00:09:39,079
Times are bad,
Mr. Potter.

182
00:09:39,112 --> 00:09:40,981
A lot of these people
are out of work.
Well, then, foreclose.

183
00:09:41,014 --> 00:09:42,916
I can't do that.
These families
have children.

184
00:09:42,950 --> 00:09:44,551
GEORGE: Pop.
They're not my children.

185
00:09:44,584 --> 00:09:46,553
But they're
somebody's children,
Mr. Potter.

186
00:09:46,586 --> 00:09:49,189
Are you running a business
or a charity ward?

187
00:09:49,222 --> 00:09:51,391
Well, all right...
Not with my money.

188
00:09:51,424 --> 00:09:54,061
Mr. Potter,
what makes you such
a hard-skulled character?

189
00:09:54,094 --> 00:09:55,996
You have no family,
no children.

190
00:09:56,029 --> 00:09:57,931
You can't begin
to spend all the
money you've got.

191
00:09:57,965 --> 00:10:01,268
Oh, I suppose
I should give it
to miserable failures

192
00:10:01,301 --> 00:10:04,571
like you and that
idiot brother of yours
to spend for me.

193
00:10:04,604 --> 00:10:05,873
He's not a failure!

194
00:10:05,906 --> 00:10:07,741
You can't say
that about my father.
George, George.

195
00:10:07,775 --> 00:10:09,009
Quiet, George.

196
00:10:09,042 --> 00:10:10,477
You're not.
You're the biggest
man in town...

197
00:10:10,510 --> 00:10:12,680
Run along, run along.
...bigger than him,
bigger than everybody.

198
00:10:12,713 --> 00:10:14,047
Gives you an idea
of the Baileys.

199
00:10:14,081 --> 00:10:15,883
Don't let him say
that about you, Pop.

200
00:10:15,916 --> 00:10:17,617
All right, Son.
All right. Thanks.

201
00:10:17,651 --> 00:10:19,419
I'll talk to you tonight.

202
00:10:20,654 --> 00:10:22,022
(MEN CHATTERING)

203
00:10:26,493 --> 00:10:27,861
GOWER: What?

204
00:10:27,895 --> 00:10:31,665
(SLURRING)
Why, that medicine should have
been there an hour ago.

205
00:10:31,699 --> 00:10:34,234
It will be over
in five minutes, Mrs. Blaine.

206
00:10:38,171 --> 00:10:40,473
Where's Mrs. Blaine's
box of capsules?

207
00:10:40,507 --> 00:10:42,142
I... You...

208
00:10:42,943 --> 00:10:44,377
Didn't you hear
what I said?

209
00:10:44,411 --> 00:10:45,545
Yes, sir. I...

210
00:10:45,578 --> 00:10:47,580
What kind of tricks
are you playing anyway?

211
00:10:47,614 --> 00:10:48,882
(SLAPPING)

212
00:10:50,150 --> 00:10:52,886
Why--Why didn't you
deliver them right away?

213
00:10:52,920 --> 00:10:54,487
Don't you know
that boy's very sick?

214
00:10:54,521 --> 00:10:56,056
(SOBBING) You're hurting
my sore ear.

215
00:10:56,089 --> 00:10:57,457
You lazy loafer.

216
00:10:57,490 --> 00:10:59,727
Mr. Gower,
you don't know
what you're doing.

217
00:10:59,760 --> 00:11:01,695
You put something wrong
in those capsules.

218
00:11:01,729 --> 00:11:03,030
I know you're unhappy.

219
00:11:03,063 --> 00:11:04,798
You got the telegram,
and you're upset.

220
00:11:04,832 --> 00:11:06,734
You put something bad
in those capsules.

221
00:11:06,767 --> 00:11:09,102
It wasn't
your fault, Mr. Gower.

222
00:11:10,503 --> 00:11:12,005
Just look and see
what you did.

223
00:11:12,039 --> 00:11:14,274
The bottle you took
the powder from,
it's poison.

224
00:11:14,307 --> 00:11:16,176
I tell you, it's poison.

225
00:11:16,209 --> 00:11:17,945
I know you feel bad.

226
00:11:19,412 --> 00:11:20,948
(GEORGE SNIFFLING)

227
00:11:23,216 --> 00:11:25,085
Oh!
Don't hurt
my sore ear again!

228
00:11:25,118 --> 00:11:26,553
Oh, no, no.
Don't hurt
my sore ear again.

229
00:11:26,586 --> 00:11:29,222
(SOBBING)
Oh, George, George.

230
00:11:29,256 --> 00:11:32,125
Oh, Mr. Gower,
I won't ever tell anyone.

231
00:11:32,159 --> 00:11:33,593
I know how you're feeling.

232
00:11:33,626 --> 00:11:36,329
I won't ever tell a soul.
Hope to die, I won't.

233
00:11:36,363 --> 00:11:38,565
Oh, George. George.

234
00:11:38,598 --> 00:11:41,168
An overnight bag.
Genuine English cowhide.

235
00:11:41,201 --> 00:11:42,469
Combination lock.

236
00:11:42,502 --> 00:11:44,004
Fitted up with brushes,
combs...

237
00:11:44,037 --> 00:11:45,873
Nope, nope, nope, nope.

238
00:11:45,906 --> 00:11:48,408
Now, look, Joe. Now, look.

239
00:11:48,441 --> 00:11:51,111
I--I--I want a big one.

240
00:11:51,144 --> 00:11:52,545
CLARENCE:
What did you stop it for?

241
00:11:52,579 --> 00:11:55,783
FRANKLIN: I want you
to take a good look
at that face.

242
00:11:55,816 --> 00:11:56,884
Who is it?

243
00:11:56,917 --> 00:11:58,451
George Bailey.

244
00:11:58,485 --> 00:12:01,121
Oh, you mean
the kid that had his ears
slapped back by the druggist?

245
00:12:01,154 --> 00:12:02,455
That's the kid.

246
00:12:02,823 --> 00:12:04,424
Ah.

247
00:12:04,457 --> 00:12:06,593
It's a good face.
I like it.

248
00:12:06,626 --> 00:12:08,896
I like George Bailey.

249
00:12:08,929 --> 00:12:11,598
Tell me,
did he ever tell
anyone about the pills?

250
00:12:11,631 --> 00:12:13,033
Not a soul.

251
00:12:13,066 --> 00:12:14,601
Did he ever
marry the girl?

252
00:12:14,634 --> 00:12:15,936
Did he ever go exploring?

253
00:12:15,969 --> 00:12:18,338
Well, wait and see.

254
00:12:18,371 --> 00:12:20,607
Big, see? I--I don't want
one for one night.

255
00:12:20,640 --> 00:12:22,675
I want something
for 1,001 nights

256
00:12:22,709 --> 00:12:24,177
with plenty of room here
for labels

257
00:12:24,211 --> 00:12:27,247
from Italy and Baghdad,
Samarkand.

258
00:12:27,280 --> 00:12:28,481
Great big thing, about...

259
00:12:28,515 --> 00:12:30,550
I see. A flying carpet,
huh?
Yeah.

260
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:33,220
I don't suppose you'd like
this old secondhand job,
would you?

261
00:12:33,253 --> 00:12:34,521
Now you're talking.

262
00:12:34,554 --> 00:12:37,490
Gee whiz,
I could use that as a raft
in case the boat sunk.

263
00:12:37,524 --> 00:12:38,658
How much this cost?

264
00:12:38,691 --> 00:12:40,393
No charge.

265
00:12:40,427 --> 00:12:42,595
That's my trick ear, Joe.
It sounded like
you said "no charge."

266
00:12:42,629 --> 00:12:43,831
That's right.

267
00:12:44,965 --> 00:12:46,566
Well, what's my name
doing on it?

268
00:12:46,599 --> 00:12:48,235
A little present
from old man Gower.

269
00:12:48,268 --> 00:12:49,536
Came down
and picked it out himself.

270
00:12:49,569 --> 00:12:51,471
He did?
What do you know about that?

271
00:12:51,504 --> 00:12:53,173
My old boss.
Isn't that nice?

272
00:12:53,206 --> 00:12:54,541
What boat are you
sailing on?

273
00:12:54,574 --> 00:12:56,977
I'm working across
on a cattle boat.
A cattle boat?

274
00:12:57,010 --> 00:12:58,278
Okay, I like cows.

275
00:12:59,012 --> 00:13:00,547
(CHILDREN CLAMORING)

276
00:13:00,580 --> 00:13:02,582
Hello, Mr. Gower.
How are you?

277
00:13:02,615 --> 00:13:04,051
Thanks ever so much
for the baggage.

278
00:13:04,084 --> 00:13:05,785
It's just exactly
what I wanted.
Oh, forget it.

279
00:13:05,819 --> 00:13:07,120
Oh, it's wonderful
of you to think of me.

280
00:13:07,154 --> 00:13:08,922
Hope you enjoy it.
Oh, oh, oh, oh!

281
00:13:08,956 --> 00:13:10,824
I wish I had
a million dollars.

282
00:13:10,858 --> 00:13:12,759
Hot dog!

283
00:13:12,792 --> 00:13:15,328
Avast there, Captain Cook!
You got your sea legs yet?

284
00:13:15,362 --> 00:13:16,796
(LAUGHING)
Parlez-vous
francais, mister?

285
00:13:16,830 --> 00:13:19,166
Hey, send us some
of those picture postcards,
will you, George?

286
00:13:19,199 --> 00:13:21,001
Hey, George,
don't take
any plug nickels.

287
00:13:21,034 --> 00:13:22,735
Hey, George,
your suitcase is leaking.

288
00:13:22,769 --> 00:13:24,571
GEORGE: Hey, Ernie!

289
00:13:24,604 --> 00:13:26,206
Hi, Ernie. Hi, Bert.
Hiya, George.

290
00:13:26,239 --> 00:13:28,441
George.
Hey, hey, hey,
I'm a rich tourist today.

291
00:13:28,475 --> 00:13:29,742
How about driving
me home in style?

292
00:13:29,776 --> 00:13:31,744
Hop in,
Your Highness. Hop in.
Yes, sir.

293
00:13:31,778 --> 00:13:34,681
And for the carriage trade,
I put on my hat.

294
00:13:36,850 --> 00:13:38,551
Good afternoon,
Mr. Bailey.

295
00:13:38,585 --> 00:13:40,020
Hello, Violet.

296
00:13:40,053 --> 00:13:42,222
Hey, you look good.
That's some dress
you got on there.

297
00:13:42,255 --> 00:13:43,790
This old thing?

298
00:13:43,823 --> 00:13:46,459
Why, I only wear it
when I don't care how I look.

299
00:13:55,502 --> 00:13:56,870
(CAR HORN HONKING)

300
00:14:01,875 --> 00:14:03,810
How would you
like to take...
Yes.

301
00:14:05,678 --> 00:14:07,414
Want to come along, Bert?
We'll show you the town.

302
00:14:07,447 --> 00:14:08,781
No, thanks.

303
00:14:08,815 --> 00:14:11,851
I think
I'll go home and see
what the wife's doing.

304
00:14:13,753 --> 00:14:15,088
Family man.

305
00:14:15,122 --> 00:14:16,523
(GEORGE AND HARRY DANCING)

306
00:14:16,556 --> 00:14:20,527
George, Harry,
you're shaking
the house down. Stop it.

307
00:14:20,560 --> 00:14:21,728
Oh, let them alone.

308
00:14:21,761 --> 00:14:23,263
I wish I was up
there with them.

309
00:14:23,296 --> 00:14:25,432
But Harry will tear
his dinner suit.

310
00:14:25,465 --> 00:14:28,301
George!
That's why all children
should be girls.

311
00:14:28,335 --> 00:14:32,239
Well, if they were all girls
there wouldn't be any...
Oh, never mind.

312
00:14:32,272 --> 00:14:34,707
George, Harry,
come down to dinner
this minute.

313
00:14:34,741 --> 00:14:36,276
Everything's
getting cold, and you know

314
00:14:36,309 --> 00:14:37,810
how long we've been
waiting for you.

315
00:14:37,844 --> 00:14:39,346
GEORGE: Okay, Ma.
HARRY: Okay, Ma.

316
00:14:39,379 --> 00:14:40,847
(GEORGE AND HARRY SINGING)

317
00:14:40,880 --> 00:14:42,649
Ta-da!
Ta-da!

318
00:14:42,682 --> 00:14:44,617
(DOG BARKING)

319
00:14:44,651 --> 00:14:46,987
We got a present
for you, Pop.
There you are.

320
00:14:47,020 --> 00:14:48,021
Whoa.

321
00:14:48,855 --> 00:14:50,690
(LAUGHING)

322
00:14:50,723 --> 00:14:52,659
Oh, you two idiots.

323
00:14:52,692 --> 00:14:53,760
George, sit down
and have dinner.

324
00:14:53,793 --> 00:14:54,827
I've eaten.
Fine.

325
00:14:54,861 --> 00:14:56,029
Well, aren't you
gonna finish dressing

326
00:14:56,063 --> 00:14:57,931
for your graduating party?
Look at you!

327
00:14:57,965 --> 00:14:59,499
I don't care.
It's George's tux.

328
00:14:59,532 --> 00:15:01,234
Annie, my sweet,
have you got those pies?

329
00:15:01,268 --> 00:15:03,636
If you lay a hand on me,
I'll hit you with this broom!

330
00:15:03,670 --> 00:15:05,939
Annie, I'm in love with you.
There's a moon out tonight.

331
00:15:05,973 --> 00:15:07,140
(ANNIE SCREAMS)

332
00:15:07,174 --> 00:15:09,609
Boy, oh boy, oh boy!
My last meal

333
00:15:09,642 --> 00:15:10,944
in the old Bailey
boarding house.

334
00:15:10,978 --> 00:15:12,946
Oh, my lands,
my blood pressure.

335
00:15:12,980 --> 00:15:15,515
Pop, can I have the car?
I gotta take over a lot
of plates and things.

336
00:15:15,548 --> 00:15:16,516
What plates?

337
00:15:16,549 --> 00:15:17,784
Mom, I'm chairman
of the Eats Committee.

338
00:15:17,817 --> 00:15:19,352
We only need
a couple of dozen.

339
00:15:19,386 --> 00:15:22,355
Oh, no, you don't, Harry.
Now, not my best
Haviland, no.

340
00:15:22,389 --> 00:15:24,691
Oh, let him have
the plates, Mother.

341
00:15:24,724 --> 00:15:26,093
Hope you have
a good trip, George.

342
00:15:26,126 --> 00:15:27,527
Uncle Billy and I
are gonna miss you.

343
00:15:27,560 --> 00:15:29,496
I'm gonna miss you, too, Pop.

344
00:15:29,529 --> 00:15:30,797
What's the matter?
You look tired.

345
00:15:30,830 --> 00:15:33,266
Oh, I had another
tussle with
Potter today.

346
00:15:33,300 --> 00:15:35,135
I thought when we put him
on the board of directors,

347
00:15:35,168 --> 00:15:36,636
he'd ease up
on us a little bit.

348
00:15:36,669 --> 00:15:39,172
Oh, what's eating
that old money-grubbing
buzzard anyway?

349
00:15:39,206 --> 00:15:42,375
Oh, he's a sick man,
frustrated,
sick in his mind.

350
00:15:42,409 --> 00:15:44,444
Sick in his soul,
if he has one.

351
00:15:44,477 --> 00:15:47,280
He hates everybody
that has anything
that he can't have.

352
00:15:47,314 --> 00:15:48,881
He hates us
mostly, I guess.

353
00:15:48,915 --> 00:15:50,550
Gangway. Gangway.

354
00:15:50,583 --> 00:15:52,019
So long, Pop.
So long.

355
00:15:52,052 --> 00:15:53,920
You got a match?
Very funny, very funny.

356
00:15:53,953 --> 00:15:55,455
Put those things
in the car,

357
00:15:55,488 --> 00:15:57,090
and I'll get your tie
and studs ready for you.
Now, hurry up.

358
00:15:57,124 --> 00:15:58,825
Okay, Mom.
Now, don't drop
one of those.

359
00:15:58,858 --> 00:16:00,093
You coming later, George?

360
00:16:00,127 --> 00:16:01,461
What do you mean,
and be bored to death?

361
00:16:01,494 --> 00:16:03,130
Couldn't want a better death.
Lots of pretty girls,

362
00:16:03,163 --> 00:16:04,731
and we're gonna use
that new floor tonight, too.

363
00:16:04,764 --> 00:16:06,266
I hope it works.
No gin tonight, Son.

364
00:16:06,299 --> 00:16:07,767
HARRY:
Oh, Pop, just a little?

365
00:16:07,800 --> 00:16:09,969
No, Son. Not one drop.
Oh!

366
00:16:10,003 --> 00:16:12,305
Boys and girls and music.

367
00:16:12,339 --> 00:16:14,274
Why do they need gin?

368
00:16:14,307 --> 00:16:17,144
Did I act like that
when I graduated
from high school?

369
00:16:17,177 --> 00:16:19,246
Pretty much.

370
00:16:19,279 --> 00:16:21,814
You know, George, I wish
we could send Harry
to college with you.

371
00:16:21,848 --> 00:16:23,516
Your mother and I
talked it over
half the night.

372
00:16:23,550 --> 00:16:26,453
Mmm. We have that all
figured out.

373
00:16:26,486 --> 00:16:28,688
You see,
Harry will take my job
at the Building and Loan,

374
00:16:28,721 --> 00:16:31,858
work there for four years,
then he'll go.

375
00:16:31,891 --> 00:16:33,260
Pretty young
for that job.

376
00:16:33,293 --> 00:16:35,062
Well, no younger than I was.

377
00:16:35,095 --> 00:16:37,430
Well, you were
born older, George.

378
00:16:38,465 --> 00:16:40,033
How's that?

379
00:16:40,067 --> 00:16:41,801
I said you were
born older.

380
00:16:41,834 --> 00:16:44,871
I suppose you've decided
what you want to do
when you get out of college.

381
00:16:44,904 --> 00:16:46,706
Oh, well, you know
what I've always
talked about,

382
00:16:46,739 --> 00:16:50,210
build things,
design new buildings,
plan modern cities.

383
00:16:50,243 --> 00:16:51,611
All that stuff
I've been talking about.

384
00:16:51,644 --> 00:16:53,480
Still after
that first million
before you're 30?

385
00:16:53,513 --> 00:16:54,881
I'll settle
for half that in cash.

386
00:16:54,914 --> 00:16:56,449
(CHUCKLING)

387
00:16:56,483 --> 00:16:58,418
Of course,
it's just a hope.

388
00:16:59,386 --> 00:17:00,853
But, uh, you wouldn't
consider coming back

389
00:17:00,887 --> 00:17:02,655
to the Building
and Loan, would you?

390
00:17:04,857 --> 00:17:07,094
Well, I... I...

391
00:17:09,196 --> 00:17:10,997
Annie, why--why--why don't
you draw up a chair?

392
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:12,199
Then you'd be
more comfortable,

393
00:17:12,232 --> 00:17:13,966
and you could hear
everything
that's going on.

394
00:17:14,000 --> 00:17:16,503
I would if I thought
I'd hear anything
worth listening to.

395
00:17:16,536 --> 00:17:18,138
You would, eh?

396
00:17:18,171 --> 00:17:20,107
I know it's soon
to talk about it.

397
00:17:20,140 --> 00:17:23,576
No, now, Pop, I--I couldn't.

398
00:17:23,610 --> 00:17:25,878
I--I couldn't face
being cooped up
for the rest of my life

399
00:17:25,912 --> 00:17:27,714
in a shabby little office.

400
00:17:29,549 --> 00:17:32,719
Oh, I'm sorry, Pop.
I didn't mean that, but I...

401
00:17:32,752 --> 00:17:34,921
I-It's this business
of nickels and dimes

402
00:17:34,954 --> 00:17:37,424
and spending all your life
trying to figure out

403
00:17:37,457 --> 00:17:39,792
how to save three cents
on a length of pipe.
I'd go crazy.

404
00:17:39,826 --> 00:17:42,562
I--I want to do
something big
and something important.

405
00:17:42,595 --> 00:17:45,598
You know, George,
I feel that,
in a small way,

406
00:17:45,632 --> 00:17:47,600
we're doing
something important,

407
00:17:47,634 --> 00:17:49,902
satisfying
a fundamental urge.

408
00:17:49,936 --> 00:17:54,274
It's deep in the race
for a man to want his own roof
and walls and fireplace.

409
00:17:54,307 --> 00:17:58,044
And we're helping him
get those things
in our shabby little office.

410
00:17:58,077 --> 00:18:01,581
I know, Pop.
I--I know that.

411
00:18:01,614 --> 00:18:04,984
I--I wish I felt that, uh...

412
00:18:05,017 --> 00:18:08,755
I--I've been hoarding pennies
like a miser here
in order to...

413
00:18:08,788 --> 00:18:11,691
Most of my friends
have already
finished college.

414
00:18:11,724 --> 00:18:14,594
I--I just feel like if
I didn't get away, I'd bust.

415
00:18:14,627 --> 00:18:15,795
Mmm-hmm.

416
00:18:16,663 --> 00:18:19,866
Yes, yes,
you're right, Son.

417
00:18:19,899 --> 00:18:21,668
You see what I mean,
don't you, Pop?

418
00:18:21,701 --> 00:18:23,303
This town is no place
for any man

419
00:18:23,336 --> 00:18:25,672
unless he's willing
to crawl to Potter.

420
00:18:25,705 --> 00:18:28,975
Now, you've got talent, Son.
I've seen it.

421
00:18:29,008 --> 00:18:32,212
You get yourself
an education and
get out of here.

422
00:18:34,714 --> 00:18:36,583
Pop, you want a shock?

423
00:18:38,117 --> 00:18:40,220
I think you're a great guy.

424
00:18:43,790 --> 00:18:45,158
Why, did you
hear that, Annie?

425
00:18:45,192 --> 00:18:48,528
I heard it.
It's about time
one of you lunkheads said it.

426
00:18:50,463 --> 00:18:52,299
I'm gonna miss old Annie.

427
00:18:55,768 --> 00:18:59,005
Pop, I think I'll
get dressed and go over
to Harry's party.

428
00:18:59,038 --> 00:19:00,507
Have a good time, Son.

429
00:19:02,041 --> 00:19:03,476
(ORCHESTRA PLAYING MUSIC)

430
00:19:04,544 --> 00:19:05,678
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

431
00:19:05,712 --> 00:19:06,846
Excuse me.

432
00:19:07,414 --> 00:19:08,515
There you are.

433
00:19:08,548 --> 00:19:09,682
MAN: George, hello.

434
00:19:09,716 --> 00:19:10,983
You know
my kid brother George.

435
00:19:11,017 --> 00:19:12,985
I'm gonna put him
through college.
MAN 2: Hello, George.

436
00:19:13,420 --> 00:19:14,621
Hee-haw!

437
00:19:14,654 --> 00:19:15,855
Oh-oh, Sam Wainwright.

438
00:19:15,888 --> 00:19:17,490
How are you?
When did you get here?

439
00:19:17,524 --> 00:19:19,659
Oh, this afternoon.
I thought I'd give
the kids a treat.

440
00:19:19,692 --> 00:19:21,127
Old college graduate now.

441
00:19:21,160 --> 00:19:23,296
Yeah,
old "Joe College" Wainwright
they call me.

442
00:19:23,330 --> 00:19:26,699
Well, freshman, looks like
you're gonna make
it after all, huh?

443
00:19:26,733 --> 00:19:29,236
Harry, you're the guy
I want to see.
Hello, Sam.

444
00:19:29,269 --> 00:19:30,937
Coach has heard
all about you.
He has?

445
00:19:30,970 --> 00:19:32,839
Yeah,
he's followed every game,
and his mouth's watering.

446
00:19:32,872 --> 00:19:34,974
He wants me to find out
if you're gonna
come along with us.

447
00:19:35,007 --> 00:19:36,609
Well, I, uh, I got to
make some dough first.

448
00:19:36,643 --> 00:19:37,944
Well, you better
make it fast.

449
00:19:37,977 --> 00:19:39,246
We need great ends
like you.

450
00:19:39,279 --> 00:19:40,980
Not broken-down
old guys like this one.

451
00:19:41,013 --> 00:19:42,549
Hee-haw!

452
00:19:42,582 --> 00:19:44,651
George, welcome back.

453
00:19:44,684 --> 00:19:46,386
Hello, Mr. Partridge,
how are you?

454
00:19:46,419 --> 00:19:48,655
Putting a pool
under this floor
was a great idea.

455
00:19:48,688 --> 00:19:49,822
Saved us another building.

456
00:19:49,856 --> 00:19:51,991
Now, Harry, Sam,
have a lot of fun.

457
00:19:52,024 --> 00:19:55,362
There's lots of stuff here
to eat and drink.
Lots of pretty girls around.

458
00:19:55,395 --> 00:19:57,163
A third dance... A third...

459
00:19:57,196 --> 00:19:58,631
Hello, Violet.

460
00:19:58,665 --> 00:20:00,032
Hello. What am I bid?

461
00:20:00,066 --> 00:20:01,301
George.

462
00:20:01,334 --> 00:20:03,936
Marty! Well,
it's old home week.
Marty!

463
00:20:03,970 --> 00:20:05,372
Sam, Harry,
how are you?

464
00:20:05,405 --> 00:20:07,340
Do me a favor,
will you, George?
What's that?

465
00:20:07,374 --> 00:20:09,842
You remember
my kid sister Mary.
Oh, yeah. Yeah.

466
00:20:09,876 --> 00:20:12,211
(MIMICKING MARY)
"Mama wants you, Marty.
Mama wants you." Remember?

467
00:20:12,245 --> 00:20:13,646
Dance with her,
will you?

468
00:20:13,680 --> 00:20:16,849
Oh, me?
Well, I feel funny enough
already with all these kids.

469
00:20:16,883 --> 00:20:18,918
Oh, come on, be a sport.
Just dance with her
one time,

470
00:20:18,951 --> 00:20:21,388
and you'll give her
the thrill of her life.
Hey, Sis!

471
00:20:21,421 --> 00:20:24,791
Don't be long, Marty.
I'm not being
a wet nurse to a...

472
00:20:24,824 --> 00:20:26,859
TEEN: The next thing
I knew, some guy
came up and tripped me.

473
00:20:26,893 --> 00:20:28,861
That's the reason
why I came in fourth.

474
00:20:28,895 --> 00:20:31,664
If it hadn't been
for that, that race'd
have been a cinch.

475
00:20:31,698 --> 00:20:34,701
I tried to find out
who it was later,
but I couldn't find out.

476
00:20:34,734 --> 00:20:38,471
Nobody'd ever tell
you whoever it was,
because they'd be scared.

477
00:20:38,505 --> 00:20:39,806
'Cause they know
what kind of a guy I am.

478
00:20:39,839 --> 00:20:42,208
You remember George.
This is Mary.

479
00:20:42,241 --> 00:20:43,410
Well, I'll be seeing you.

480
00:20:43,443 --> 00:20:45,077
Well, well, well.

481
00:20:45,111 --> 00:20:47,680
Now to get back
to my story, see?

482
00:20:49,081 --> 00:20:50,783
(ORCHESTRA PLAYING MUSIC)

483
00:20:50,817 --> 00:20:52,184
Hey, this is my dance.

484
00:20:52,218 --> 00:20:54,086
Oh, why don't you
stop annoying people?

485
00:20:54,120 --> 00:20:56,255
Well, I'm sorry. Hey!

486
00:20:59,492 --> 00:21:00,760
Well, hello.

487
00:21:00,793 --> 00:21:02,495
Hello.

488
00:21:02,529 --> 00:21:04,731
You look at me as if
you didn't know me.

489
00:21:04,764 --> 00:21:06,032
Well, I don't.

490
00:21:06,065 --> 00:21:08,435
You've passed me
on the street
almost every day.

491
00:21:08,468 --> 00:21:09,602
Me?
Mmm-hmm.

492
00:21:09,636 --> 00:21:11,338
No. That was a little girl
named Mary Hatch.

493
00:21:11,371 --> 00:21:13,239
(WHISTLE BLOWING)
That wasn't you.

494
00:21:13,272 --> 00:21:15,041
Oh, yes! Oh, yes! Oh, yes!

495
00:21:15,074 --> 00:21:16,709
The big Charleston contest!

496
00:21:16,743 --> 00:21:18,845
(ALL CHEERING)

497
00:21:18,878 --> 00:21:21,748
The prize,
a genuine loving cup.

498
00:21:21,781 --> 00:21:24,617
Those not tapped by the judges
will remain on the floor.

499
00:21:24,651 --> 00:21:25,785
Let's go!

500
00:21:26,719 --> 00:21:29,055
(MUSIC PLAYING)

501
00:21:36,295 --> 00:21:37,597
I'm not very good at this.

502
00:21:37,630 --> 00:21:38,998
Neither am I.

503
00:21:39,031 --> 00:21:40,567
Okay. What can we lose?

504
00:21:52,779 --> 00:21:54,280
Hey, you're wonderful.

505
00:22:21,774 --> 00:22:24,276
What's the matter,
Othello? Jealous?

506
00:22:26,045 --> 00:22:29,416
Did you know
there's a swimming pool
under this floor?

507
00:22:29,449 --> 00:22:34,320
And did you know that
button behind you causes
this floor to open up?

508
00:22:34,353 --> 00:22:37,890
And did you further know
that George Bailey

509
00:22:37,924 --> 00:22:40,259
is dancing
right over that crack?

510
00:22:41,794 --> 00:22:43,430
And I've got the key.

511
00:22:54,340 --> 00:22:55,842
(PEOPLE GASPING)

512
00:22:59,479 --> 00:23:00,980
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

513
00:23:03,916 --> 00:23:05,151
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

514
00:23:06,185 --> 00:23:08,688
Stand back, everybody!
Stand back!

515
00:23:11,223 --> 00:23:13,192
(PEOPLE SCREAMING LOUDER)

516
00:23:13,225 --> 00:23:15,127
They're cheering us.
We must be good.

517
00:23:16,863 --> 00:23:18,297
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

518
00:23:22,502 --> 00:23:23,936
(PEOPLE EXCLAIMING)

519
00:23:27,173 --> 00:23:28,975
(INAUDIBLE)

520
00:23:29,809 --> 00:23:31,544
(PEOPLE CHEERING)

521
00:23:53,933 --> 00:23:55,234
Get out of there!

522
00:23:55,267 --> 00:23:56,803
What... Oh, well.

523
00:23:57,637 --> 00:23:58,838
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

524
00:23:58,871 --> 00:24:00,206
(WATER SPLASHING)

525
00:24:04,076 --> 00:24:06,378
BOTH: * Buffalo gals
can't you come out tonight?

526
00:24:06,412 --> 00:24:07,780
* Can't you come out tonight?

527
00:24:07,814 --> 00:24:09,248
* Can't you come out tonight?

528
00:24:09,281 --> 00:24:11,984
* Buffalo gals,
can't you come out tonight

529
00:24:12,018 --> 00:24:16,022
(BOTH SINGING OFF-KEY)
* And dance

530
00:24:16,055 --> 00:24:18,825
* By the light

531
00:24:18,858 --> 00:24:24,063
* Of the moon?

532
00:24:24,096 --> 00:24:26,799
Oh, hot dog.
Just like an organ.
Beautiful.

533
00:24:26,833 --> 00:24:29,068
I told Harry I thought
I'd be bored to death.

534
00:24:29,101 --> 00:24:31,403
You should have seen
the commotion
in that locker room.

535
00:24:31,437 --> 00:24:32,839
I had to knock down
three people

536
00:24:32,872 --> 00:24:34,240
to get this stuff
we're wearing here.

537
00:24:34,273 --> 00:24:36,208
Let me-- let me
hold that old wet dress
of yours.

538
00:24:36,242 --> 00:24:37,944
Do I look as funny
as you do?

539
00:24:37,977 --> 00:24:39,879
I guess I'm not
quite the football type.

540
00:24:39,912 --> 00:24:42,048
You--you look wonderful!

541
00:24:42,081 --> 00:24:43,449
You know,
if it wasn't me talking,

542
00:24:43,482 --> 00:24:45,618
I'd say you were
the prettiest girl in town.

543
00:24:46,653 --> 00:24:49,155
Well, why don't you say it?

544
00:24:49,188 --> 00:24:50,890
I don't know.
Maybe I will say it.

545
00:24:50,923 --> 00:24:52,559
How old are you anyway?

546
00:24:53,492 --> 00:24:54,727
Eighteen.

547
00:24:54,761 --> 00:24:58,831
Eighteen?
Why, it was only last year
you were seventeen.

548
00:24:58,865 --> 00:25:00,332
Too young or too old?

549
00:25:00,366 --> 00:25:03,903
Oh, no, no. Just right.
Your age fits you.

550
00:25:03,936 --> 00:25:06,706
Yes, sir,
you look a little older
without your clothes on.

551
00:25:06,739 --> 00:25:10,142
(STAMMERING)
I mean, without
a dress you look older.

552
00:25:10,176 --> 00:25:13,179
(STUTTERING)
I mean younger.
You look... You just...

553
00:25:13,212 --> 00:25:14,547
BOTH: Oh-oh.

554
00:25:14,581 --> 00:25:16,182
Oh, I'm on
the thing here.

555
00:25:16,215 --> 00:25:18,217
Sir, my train, please.

556
00:25:18,250 --> 00:25:21,053
A pox upon me
for a clumsy lout.

557
00:25:21,087 --> 00:25:25,157
Your, uh...
Your caboose, milady.

558
00:25:25,191 --> 00:25:26,726
You may kiss my hand.

559
00:25:26,759 --> 00:25:27,994
Mmm.

560
00:25:30,096 --> 00:25:31,564
Hey.

561
00:25:33,465 --> 00:25:35,434
Hey, Mary.

562
00:25:35,467 --> 00:25:38,771
* As I was
lumberin' down the street

563
00:25:38,805 --> 00:25:41,407
* Down the street,
down the street

564
00:25:41,440 --> 00:25:43,910
Okay, then. I'll
throw a rock at the
old Granville house.

565
00:25:43,943 --> 00:25:46,078
Oh, no, don't.
I--I love that old house.

566
00:25:46,112 --> 00:25:48,214
No, you see,
you make a wish and then try
and break some glass.

567
00:25:48,247 --> 00:25:50,149
And you got to be
a pretty good shot
nowadays, too.

568
00:25:50,182 --> 00:25:53,720
Oh, no, George, don't.
It's full of romance,
that old place.

569
00:25:53,753 --> 00:25:55,221
MARY: I'd like to live in it.

570
00:25:55,254 --> 00:25:57,156
GEORGE: In that place?
Uh-huh.

571
00:25:57,189 --> 00:25:58,725
I wouldn't live
in it as a ghost.
Now, watch.

572
00:25:58,758 --> 00:26:00,960
Right in the second floor,
there. See?

573
00:26:02,328 --> 00:26:04,096
(GLASS SHATTERING)

574
00:26:06,132 --> 00:26:07,333
What did you wish, George?

575
00:26:07,366 --> 00:26:09,936
Well, not just one wish,
a whole hatful.

576
00:26:09,969 --> 00:26:12,038
Mary, I know what
I'm gonna do tomorrow

577
00:26:12,071 --> 00:26:14,707
and the next day
and next year
and the year after that.

578
00:26:14,741 --> 00:26:17,644
I'm shaking the dust
of this crummy
little town off my feet,

579
00:26:17,677 --> 00:26:19,478
and I'm gonna see
the world!

580
00:26:19,511 --> 00:26:22,649
Italy, Greece,
the Parthenon, the Coliseum.

581
00:26:22,682 --> 00:26:25,384
Then I'm coming back here
and go to college
to see what they know.

582
00:26:25,417 --> 00:26:27,086
And then I'm
gonna build things.

583
00:26:27,119 --> 00:26:28,587
I'm gonna build airfields.

584
00:26:28,621 --> 00:26:31,057
I'm gonna build skyscrapers
100 stories high.

585
00:26:31,090 --> 00:26:33,826
I'm gonna build
bridges a mile long.

586
00:26:33,860 --> 00:26:35,227
What, are you gonna
throw a rock?

587
00:26:37,830 --> 00:26:39,365
(GLASS SHATTERING)

588
00:26:40,066 --> 00:26:41,768
Hey, that's pretty good.

589
00:26:42,468 --> 00:26:44,036
What did you wish, Mary?

590
00:26:45,137 --> 00:26:47,173
(BIRDS CHIRPING)

591
00:26:47,206 --> 00:26:49,475
* Buffalo gals
can't you come out tonight?

592
00:26:49,508 --> 00:26:50,810
BOTH: * Can't you
come out tonight?

593
00:26:50,843 --> 00:26:52,444
* Can't you
come out tonight?

594
00:26:52,478 --> 00:26:55,547
* Buffalo gals,
can't you come out tonight

595
00:26:55,581 --> 00:26:58,651
(BOTH SINGING OFF-KEY)
* And

596
00:26:58,685 --> 00:27:02,755
* Dance by
the light of the moon? *

597
00:27:02,789 --> 00:27:04,791
* What did you wish
when you threw that rock? *

598
00:27:04,824 --> 00:27:06,292
Oh, no.
Come on, tell me.

599
00:27:06,325 --> 00:27:08,127
If I told you,
it might not come true.

600
00:27:08,160 --> 00:27:10,096
What is it you want, Mary?

601
00:27:10,129 --> 00:27:12,965
What do you want?
You--You want the moon?

602
00:27:12,999 --> 00:27:16,335
Just say the word,
and I'll throw a lasso
around it and pull it down.

603
00:27:16,368 --> 00:27:18,170
Hey, that's
a pretty good idea.

604
00:27:18,938 --> 00:27:20,272
I'll give you the moon, Mary.

605
00:27:20,306 --> 00:27:21,741
I'll take it.

606
00:27:22,174 --> 00:27:23,676
Then what?

607
00:27:23,710 --> 00:27:25,477
Well, then you could
swallow it,

608
00:27:25,511 --> 00:27:27,613
and it would
all dissolve, see?

609
00:27:27,646 --> 00:27:31,117
And the moonbeams
would shoot out of
your fingers and your toes

610
00:27:31,150 --> 00:27:32,719
and the ends of your hair.

611
00:27:34,520 --> 00:27:35,922
Am I talking too much?

612
00:27:35,955 --> 00:27:38,190
Yes!

613
00:27:38,224 --> 00:27:40,592
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her
to death?

614
00:27:40,626 --> 00:27:41,928
How's that?

615
00:27:41,961 --> 00:27:44,831
Why don't you kiss her
instead of talking her
to death?

616
00:27:46,866 --> 00:27:48,500
You want me
to kiss her, huh?

617
00:27:48,534 --> 00:27:51,938
Oh, youth is wasted
on the wrong people.

618
00:27:52,972 --> 00:27:55,274
Hey. Hey, hold on,
hey, mister.

619
00:27:55,307 --> 00:27:56,608
Come on back out here!

620
00:27:56,642 --> 00:27:59,045
I'll show you some kissing
that'll put hair
back on your head.

621
00:27:59,078 --> 00:28:00,279
What are you...

622
00:28:08,020 --> 00:28:09,121
Mary?

623
00:28:16,729 --> 00:28:17,897
(WHISTLES)

624
00:28:20,266 --> 00:28:22,468
Okay, I give up.
Where are you?

625
00:28:22,501 --> 00:28:25,671
Over here
in the hydrangea bushes.

626
00:28:25,704 --> 00:28:27,106
(CHUCKLING)

627
00:28:27,139 --> 00:28:28,474
Here you are. Catch.

628
00:28:29,208 --> 00:28:31,778
Wait a minute.
What am I doing?

629
00:28:35,748 --> 00:28:38,317
This is a very
interesting situation.

630
00:28:38,350 --> 00:28:40,152
Please give me my robe.

631
00:28:40,186 --> 00:28:42,021
Hmm.

632
00:28:42,054 --> 00:28:44,824
A man doesn't
get in a situation
like this every day.

633
00:28:44,857 --> 00:28:46,959
I'd like to have my robe.

634
00:28:46,993 --> 00:28:48,527
Not in Bedford Falls,
anyway.

635
00:28:48,560 --> 00:28:50,096
Ouch! Oh!

636
00:28:50,129 --> 00:28:51,697
Gesundheit.

637
00:28:51,730 --> 00:28:53,599
George Bailey!
This requires
a little thought here.

638
00:28:53,632 --> 00:28:55,334
Give me my robe.

639
00:28:55,367 --> 00:28:57,837
I've read about
things like this,
but I've never...

640
00:28:57,870 --> 00:28:59,471
Shame on you!

641
00:28:59,505 --> 00:29:01,073
I'm gonna tell
your mother on you.

642
00:29:01,107 --> 00:29:03,776
My mother's way up
on the corner there.

643
00:29:03,810 --> 00:29:05,812
I'll call the police.

644
00:29:05,845 --> 00:29:08,680
They're way downtown.
They'd be on my side, too.

645
00:29:08,714 --> 00:29:11,250
Th-Then--Then I'm going
to scream!

646
00:29:11,283 --> 00:29:13,853
Maybe I could
sell tickets.

647
00:29:13,886 --> 00:29:17,356
Let's see.
No, the point is

648
00:29:17,389 --> 00:29:20,359
in order to get this robe...
I've got it.

649
00:29:20,392 --> 00:29:22,128
(CAR APPROACHING)
I'll make a deal
with you, Mary.

650
00:29:22,161 --> 00:29:23,996
George! George!

651
00:29:26,933 --> 00:29:29,301
George, come on home!
Quick!

652
00:29:29,335 --> 00:29:30,569
Your father's had a stroke.

653
00:29:30,602 --> 00:29:32,138
What?

654
00:29:32,171 --> 00:29:34,006
Mary, Mary, I'm sorry.
I've got to go.

655
00:29:34,040 --> 00:29:35,174
Come on, George,
let's hurry.

656
00:29:35,207 --> 00:29:36,408
GEORGE: Did you
get a doctor?
Yes.

657
00:29:36,442 --> 00:29:37,776
Campbell's there now.

658
00:29:48,687 --> 00:29:50,356
I think that's all
we'll need you for, George.

659
00:29:50,389 --> 00:29:51,590
I know you're anxious
to make a train.

660
00:29:51,623 --> 00:29:53,292
I have a taxi
waiting downstairs.

661
00:29:53,325 --> 00:29:56,195
I want the board to know
that George gave up
his trip to Europe

662
00:29:56,228 --> 00:29:59,265
to help
straighten things out here
these past few months.

663
00:29:59,298 --> 00:30:01,000
Good luck to you
at school, George.

664
00:30:01,033 --> 00:30:03,035
Good luck, George.
Goodbye, George.

665
00:30:03,069 --> 00:30:05,737
And now we come
to the real purpose
of this meeting,

666
00:30:05,771 --> 00:30:08,507
to appoint a successor
to our dear friend
Peter Bailey.

667
00:30:08,540 --> 00:30:10,742
Mr. Chairman,
I'd like to get
to my real purpose.

668
00:30:10,776 --> 00:30:13,045
Wait just a minute now.
Wait for what?

669
00:30:13,079 --> 00:30:16,482
I claim this institution
is not necessary
to this town.

670
00:30:16,515 --> 00:30:17,917
Therefore, Mr. Chairman,

671
00:30:17,950 --> 00:30:20,853
I make a motion
to dissolve this institution

672
00:30:20,887 --> 00:30:23,789
and turn its assets
and liabilities
over to the receiver.

673
00:30:23,822 --> 00:30:25,791
Potter, you dirty,
contemptible...
I'll wring his neck.

674
00:30:25,824 --> 00:30:27,059
George, did you hear
what that buzzard...

675
00:30:27,093 --> 00:30:29,929
Mr. Chairman.
It's too soon after
Peter Bailey's death

676
00:30:29,962 --> 00:30:32,331
to talk about chloroforming
the Building and Loan.

677
00:30:32,364 --> 00:30:34,833
(ALL CHATTERING)
Peter Bailey died
three months ago.

678
00:30:34,867 --> 00:30:36,735
I second
Mr. Potter's motion.

679
00:30:36,768 --> 00:30:38,237
Very well.
In that case,

680
00:30:38,270 --> 00:30:40,606
I'll ask the two
executive officers
to withdraw.

681
00:30:40,639 --> 00:30:42,174
But before you go,

682
00:30:42,208 --> 00:30:45,411
I'm sure
the whole board wishes
to express its deep sorrow

683
00:30:45,444 --> 00:30:47,679
at the passing
of Peter Bailey.
Thank you very much.

684
00:30:47,713 --> 00:30:49,381
It was his faith
and devotion

685
00:30:49,415 --> 00:30:51,350
that are responsible
for this organization.

686
00:30:51,383 --> 00:30:53,352
I'll go further
than that.

687
00:30:53,385 --> 00:30:57,856
I'll say that
to the public Peter Bailey
was the Building and Loan.

688
00:30:57,890 --> 00:31:00,159
That's fine, Potter,
coming from you,

689
00:31:00,192 --> 00:31:02,228
considering
that you probably
drove him to his grave.

690
00:31:02,261 --> 00:31:05,131
Peter Bailey
was not a businessman.

691
00:31:05,164 --> 00:31:06,665
That's what killed him.

692
00:31:06,698 --> 00:31:09,668
Oh, I don't mean
any disrespect to him.
God rest his soul.

693
00:31:09,701 --> 00:31:13,372
He was a man
of high ideals, so-called.

694
00:31:13,405 --> 00:31:18,044
But ideals
without common sense
can ruin this town.

695
00:31:18,077 --> 00:31:21,480
Now, you take this loan here
to Ernie Bishop,

696
00:31:21,513 --> 00:31:24,350
you know, that fellow
that sits around all day

697
00:31:24,383 --> 00:31:27,453
on his brains
in his taxi, you know.

698
00:31:27,486 --> 00:31:31,123
I happen to know
the bank turned down
this loan.

699
00:31:31,157 --> 00:31:32,891
But he comes here,

700
00:31:32,925 --> 00:31:38,430
and we're building him
a house worth $5,000.

701
00:31:38,464 --> 00:31:40,933
Why?
Well, I handled
that, Mr. Potter.

702
00:31:40,967 --> 00:31:42,501
You have all
the papers there.

703
00:31:42,534 --> 00:31:45,437
His salary, insurance.
I can personally
vouch for his character.

704
00:31:45,471 --> 00:31:46,905
A friend of yours?
Yes, sir.

705
00:31:46,939 --> 00:31:48,007
Uh-huh.

706
00:31:48,040 --> 00:31:51,643
You see, if you shoot pool
with some employee here,

707
00:31:51,677 --> 00:31:54,146
you can come
and borrow money.

708
00:31:54,180 --> 00:31:56,148
What does that get us?

709
00:31:56,182 --> 00:31:59,118
A discontented, lazy rabble

710
00:31:59,151 --> 00:32:01,087
instead of
a thrifty working class.

711
00:32:01,120 --> 00:32:06,525
And all because
a few starry-eyed dreamers
like Peter Bailey

712
00:32:06,558 --> 00:32:08,260
stir 'em up
and fill their heads

713
00:32:08,294 --> 00:32:10,596
with a lot
of impossible ideas.

714
00:32:10,629 --> 00:32:12,098
Now, I say...

715
00:32:12,131 --> 00:32:13,732
Just a minute.
Just--Just a minute.

716
00:32:13,765 --> 00:32:15,434
Now, hold on, Mr. Potter.

717
00:32:15,467 --> 00:32:18,770
Now, you're right when you say
my father was no businessman.
I know that.

718
00:32:18,804 --> 00:32:22,674
Why he ever started this cheap
penny-ante Building and Loan
I'll never know.

719
00:32:22,708 --> 00:32:23,842
But neither you
nor anybody else

720
00:32:23,875 --> 00:32:25,611
can say anything
against his character,

721
00:32:25,644 --> 00:32:27,413
because his whole life was...

722
00:32:27,446 --> 00:32:30,116
Why, in the 25 years since
he and Uncle Billy
started this thing,

723
00:32:30,149 --> 00:32:31,383
he never once
thought of himself.

724
00:32:31,417 --> 00:32:32,718
Isn't that right,
Uncle Billy?

725
00:32:32,751 --> 00:32:35,454
He didn't save enough money
to send Harry to school,
let alone me.

726
00:32:35,487 --> 00:32:38,290
But he did help a few people
get out of your slums,
Mr. Potter.

727
00:32:38,324 --> 00:32:39,758
And what's wrong
with that?

728
00:32:39,791 --> 00:32:42,461
Why, here,
you're all businessmen here.

729
00:32:42,494 --> 00:32:43,862
Don't it make them
better citizens,

730
00:32:43,895 --> 00:32:45,664
and doesn't it make them
better customers?

731
00:32:45,697 --> 00:32:47,733
You--You said that they...
What'd you say
just a minute ago?

732
00:32:47,766 --> 00:32:49,768
They--They had to wait
and save their money

733
00:32:49,801 --> 00:32:51,537
before they even thought
of a decent home.

734
00:32:51,570 --> 00:32:53,305
Wait? Wait for what?

735
00:32:53,339 --> 00:32:55,074
Until their children
grow up and leave them?

736
00:32:55,107 --> 00:32:57,343
Until they're so old
and broken-down that they...

737
00:32:57,376 --> 00:33:00,046
Do you know how long it takes
a working man to save $5,000?

738
00:33:00,079 --> 00:33:01,513
Just remember
this, Mr. Potter,

739
00:33:01,547 --> 00:33:03,515
that this rabble
you're talking about,

740
00:33:03,549 --> 00:33:05,284
they do most
of the working and paying

741
00:33:05,317 --> 00:33:07,519
and living and dying
in this community.

742
00:33:07,553 --> 00:33:10,056
Well, is it too much
to have them work and pay
and live and die

743
00:33:10,089 --> 00:33:11,923
in a couple of
decent rooms and a bath?

744
00:33:11,957 --> 00:33:14,693
Anyway, my father
didn't think so.

745
00:33:14,726 --> 00:33:17,063
People were human beings
to him, but to you,

746
00:33:17,096 --> 00:33:20,132
a warped, frustrated old man,
they're cattle.

747
00:33:20,166 --> 00:33:22,634
Well, in my book, he died
a much richer man
than you'll ever be.

748
00:33:22,668 --> 00:33:24,536
I'm not interested
in your book.

749
00:33:24,570 --> 00:33:27,173
I'm talking about
the Building and Loan.

750
00:33:27,206 --> 00:33:28,974
I know very well
what you're talking about.

751
00:33:29,007 --> 00:33:32,211
You're talking about something
you can't get your fingers on,
and it's galling you.

752
00:33:32,244 --> 00:33:34,613
That's what you're
talking about, I know.

753
00:33:34,646 --> 00:33:37,015
Well, I--I--I've said
too much. I...

754
00:33:37,049 --> 00:33:38,884
You're-- You're
the Board here.

755
00:33:38,917 --> 00:33:40,386
You do what you want
with this thing.

756
00:33:40,419 --> 00:33:41,687
There's just
one thing more, though.

757
00:33:41,720 --> 00:33:44,756
This town needs
this measly
one-horse institution

758
00:33:44,790 --> 00:33:48,627
if only to have someplace
where people can come
without crawling to Potter.

759
00:33:48,660 --> 00:33:49,828
Come on, Uncle Billy.

760
00:33:55,634 --> 00:33:59,238
Sentimental hogwash.
I want my motion.

761
00:33:59,271 --> 00:34:01,073
(ALL CLAMORING)

762
00:34:01,107 --> 00:34:03,709
Boy, oh boy,
that was telling him,
George, old boy.

763
00:34:03,742 --> 00:34:05,611
You shut his big mouth.
You should have heard him.

764
00:34:05,644 --> 00:34:07,113
What happened?
We heard
a lot of yelling.

765
00:34:07,146 --> 00:34:10,116
Well, we're being
voted out of business
after 25 years.

766
00:34:10,149 --> 00:34:11,717
Easy come, easy go.

767
00:34:11,750 --> 00:34:13,685
TILLY: Here it is.
"Help wanted. Female."

768
00:34:13,719 --> 00:34:15,754
You still want me
to hang around, George?

769
00:34:15,787 --> 00:34:17,089
Yeah, I'll be right down.

770
00:34:17,123 --> 00:34:18,357
Yeah, hey,
you'll miss your train.

771
00:34:18,390 --> 00:34:20,259
You're a week late
for school already. Go on.

772
00:34:20,292 --> 00:34:21,527
What's going on
in there?

773
00:34:21,560 --> 00:34:23,129
Oh, never mind.
Don't worry about that.

774
00:34:23,162 --> 00:34:24,563
They're putting us
out of business.

775
00:34:24,596 --> 00:34:27,133
So what?
I can get another job.
I'm only 55.

776
00:34:27,166 --> 00:34:28,334
56.

777
00:34:28,367 --> 00:34:30,502
Go on, go on. Hey, look,
you gave up your boat trip,

778
00:34:30,536 --> 00:34:32,171
now you don't want to
miss college, too, do you?

779
00:34:32,204 --> 00:34:34,706
George! George!
They voted Potter down.

780
00:34:34,740 --> 00:34:36,208
They want to
keep it going.

781
00:34:36,242 --> 00:34:37,509
(ALL CHEERING)

782
00:34:37,543 --> 00:34:39,145
You did it, George.
You did it.

783
00:34:39,178 --> 00:34:41,413
They got one condition,
only one condition.

784
00:34:41,447 --> 00:34:43,081
What's that?
And that's
the best part of it.

785
00:34:43,115 --> 00:34:46,552
They've appointed George here
as Executive Secretary
to take his father's place.

786
00:34:46,585 --> 00:34:47,786
Oh, no! But, Uncle Billy...

787
00:34:47,819 --> 00:34:49,488
You can keep him on.
That's all right.

788
00:34:49,521 --> 00:34:51,490
As Secretary,
you can hire anyone you like.

789
00:34:51,523 --> 00:34:53,959
Dr. Campbell, now
let's get this thing
straight. I'm leaving.

790
00:34:53,992 --> 00:34:55,894
I'm leaving right now.
I'm going to school.

791
00:34:55,927 --> 00:34:58,197
This is my last chance.
Uncle Billy here,
he's your man.

792
00:34:58,230 --> 00:35:01,066
But, George, they'll vote
with Potter otherwise.

793
00:35:03,169 --> 00:35:05,337
CLARENCE: I know, I know,
he didn't go.

794
00:35:05,371 --> 00:35:06,772
JOSEPH: That's right.

795
00:35:06,805 --> 00:35:09,641
Not only that, but he
gave his school money
to his brother, Harry,

796
00:35:09,675 --> 00:35:11,210
and sent him
to college.

797
00:35:11,243 --> 00:35:13,179
Harry became
a football star.

798
00:35:13,212 --> 00:35:15,381
Made second team
all-American.

799
00:35:15,414 --> 00:35:17,249
Yeah, but what
happened to George?

800
00:35:17,283 --> 00:35:20,419
JOSEPH: George got
four years older, waiting
for Harry to come back

801
00:35:20,452 --> 00:35:22,488
and take over
the Building and Loans.

802
00:35:22,521 --> 00:35:23,822
There are
plenty of jobs around

803
00:35:23,855 --> 00:35:26,024
for somebody that
likes to travel.
Look at this. Here.

804
00:35:26,057 --> 00:35:28,059
Venezuela oil fields.

805
00:35:28,093 --> 00:35:30,562
"Wanted, man
with construction
experience."

806
00:35:30,596 --> 00:35:32,731
Here's the Yukon,
right here.

807
00:35:32,764 --> 00:35:34,900
"Wanted, man
with engineering
experience."

808
00:35:34,933 --> 00:35:36,235
(TRAIN HORN BLOWING)

809
00:35:36,268 --> 00:35:38,136
There she blows.

810
00:35:38,170 --> 00:35:40,639
You know what
the three most exciting
sounds in the world are?

811
00:35:40,672 --> 00:35:43,175
Uh-huh. Breakfast
is served. Lunch
is served. Dinner...

812
00:35:43,209 --> 00:35:45,477
No, no, no, no!
Anchor chains,

813
00:35:45,511 --> 00:35:47,078
plane motors
and train whistles.

814
00:35:47,112 --> 00:35:48,214
Peanut?

815
00:35:48,247 --> 00:35:49,481
There's the
professor now.

816
00:35:49,515 --> 00:35:51,417
Old Professor
Phi Beta Kappa
all-American Baily.

817
00:35:51,450 --> 00:35:53,452
Why, old George
"Geographic Explorer" Bailey.

818
00:35:53,485 --> 00:35:55,387
What? No husky dogs?
No sled?

819
00:35:55,421 --> 00:35:56,688
Uncle Billy,
you haven't changed a bit.

820
00:35:56,722 --> 00:35:58,290
Nobody ever changes here,
you know that.

821
00:35:58,324 --> 00:36:00,058
Oh, am I glad
to see you.

822
00:36:00,091 --> 00:36:02,328
Say, where's Mother?
She's home, cooking
the fatted calf.

823
00:36:02,361 --> 00:36:04,263
Come on, let's go.
Oh, wait!
Wait, wait a minute.

824
00:36:04,296 --> 00:36:07,299
George, Uncle Billy,
I want you to meet Ruth.

825
00:36:07,333 --> 00:36:08,734
Hello.
How do you do?

826
00:36:08,767 --> 00:36:11,570
Ruth Dakin.
Ruth Dakin Bailey,
if you don't mind.

827
00:36:11,603 --> 00:36:13,772
Huh?
Well, I wired you
I had a surprise.

828
00:36:13,805 --> 00:36:15,907
Here she is.
Meet the wife.

829
00:36:15,941 --> 00:36:18,777
Well, what do
you know? A wife.

830
00:36:19,378 --> 00:36:21,079
Well, how do you do?

831
00:36:21,112 --> 00:36:22,781
Congratulations.
How do you do?

832
00:36:22,814 --> 00:36:24,650
What am I doing?
Congratulations!

833
00:36:24,683 --> 00:36:27,152
Doggone it,
Harry, you...
They're married!

834
00:36:27,185 --> 00:36:29,388
Why don't you
tell somebody?

835
00:36:29,421 --> 00:36:32,023
Come on, Mrs. Bailey,
I can't wait
to see everybody's reaction.

836
00:36:32,057 --> 00:36:33,525
You're really married?
Why, yes.

837
00:36:33,559 --> 00:36:35,327
What's a pretty girl
like you doing

838
00:36:35,361 --> 00:36:37,095
marrying this
two-headed brother of mine?

839
00:36:37,128 --> 00:36:38,797
Well, I'll tell you.
It's purely mercenary.

840
00:36:38,830 --> 00:36:40,165
My father
offered him a job.

841
00:36:40,198 --> 00:36:41,567
Oh, he got you
and the job?

842
00:36:41,600 --> 00:36:44,570
Well, Harry's cup
runneth over.

843
00:36:44,603 --> 00:36:47,573
Uh, George, about that job.
Ruth spoke out of turn.

844
00:36:47,606 --> 00:36:49,207
I never said
I'd take it.

845
00:36:49,241 --> 00:36:51,977
You've been
holding the bag here
for four years,

846
00:36:52,010 --> 00:36:53,745
and, well, I won't let
you down, George.

847
00:36:53,779 --> 00:36:54,913
I would like to...

848
00:36:54,946 --> 00:36:57,749
Oh, wait a minute.
I forgot the bags.
I'll be right back.

849
00:36:57,783 --> 00:36:59,117
BILLY: It was
a surprise to me.

850
00:36:59,150 --> 00:37:01,953
This is the
new Mrs. Bailey,
my nephew's wife.

851
00:37:01,987 --> 00:37:05,223
MAN: How are you?
BILLY: Old, old friend
of the Baileys.

852
00:37:05,257 --> 00:37:07,393
RUTH: Oh, really?
What are their names?

853
00:37:07,426 --> 00:37:08,860
Let's see...

854
00:37:08,894 --> 00:37:11,263
Oh, of course,
I've heard him
speak of you.

855
00:37:11,297 --> 00:37:13,665
BILLY: And I want to tell
you, we're gonna
give the biggest party

856
00:37:13,699 --> 00:37:15,301
(RUTH EXCLAIMING)
this town ever saw.

857
00:37:15,334 --> 00:37:16,868
(ALL CHATTERING)

858
00:37:18,270 --> 00:37:19,971
Here, have some popcorn.

859
00:37:21,373 --> 00:37:24,042
George, George, George.
That's all Harry
ever talks about.

860
00:37:24,075 --> 00:37:27,045
Uh, uh, uh, Ruth,
this, uh...

861
00:37:27,078 --> 00:37:28,280
What about this job?

862
00:37:28,314 --> 00:37:30,749
Oh, well, my father
owns a glass factory
in Buffalo.

863
00:37:30,782 --> 00:37:33,585
He wants to get
Harry started in
the research business.

864
00:37:33,619 --> 00:37:35,854
Well, is it a good job?
Oh, yes, very.

865
00:37:35,887 --> 00:37:38,189
Not much money,
but, uh, good future,
you know.

866
00:37:38,223 --> 00:37:39,291
Yeah.

867
00:37:39,325 --> 00:37:41,026
Harry's a genius at research.

868
00:37:41,059 --> 00:37:42,828
My father just fell
in love with him.

869
00:37:42,861 --> 00:37:45,364
And you did, too.
Uh-huh.

870
00:37:46,832 --> 00:37:48,700
(ALL CLAMORING)

871
00:37:59,110 --> 00:38:00,245
Hey, Joe.

872
00:38:00,278 --> 00:38:02,648
Oh boy, oh boy,
oh boy, oh boy.

873
00:38:02,681 --> 00:38:03,915
I feel so good.

874
00:38:03,949 --> 00:38:06,352
I could spit
in Potter's eye.

875
00:38:06,385 --> 00:38:08,554
I think I will.
I think I will.

876
00:38:09,321 --> 00:38:11,590
What did you say? Huh?

877
00:38:11,623 --> 00:38:13,992
Maybe I'd better go home.

878
00:38:14,025 --> 00:38:16,495
Where's my hat? Where's my...

879
00:38:16,528 --> 00:38:18,797
Oh, thank you, George.

880
00:38:18,830 --> 00:38:20,332
Which is mine?
The middle one.

881
00:38:20,366 --> 00:38:23,469
Oh, thank you, George.
Oh boy, oh boy. Now, look,

882
00:38:23,502 --> 00:38:26,905
if you'll point me
in the right direction...
Would you do that, George?

883
00:38:26,938 --> 00:38:28,139
Right down here.

884
00:38:28,173 --> 00:38:30,676
(SLURRING) Old Building
and Loan pal, huh?

885
00:38:30,709 --> 00:38:33,311
Now you just turn this way
and then right
straight down there.

886
00:38:33,345 --> 00:38:34,780
Oh, that way, huh?

887
00:38:34,813 --> 00:38:39,651
* My wild Irish rose

888
00:38:39,685 --> 00:38:42,287
(CRASHING)

889
00:38:42,320 --> 00:38:45,691
I'm all right.
I'm all right.

890
00:38:46,592 --> 00:38:48,293
(BILLY CONTINUES SINGING)

891
00:39:03,709 --> 00:39:05,544
(TRAIN HORN BLOWING)

892
00:39:08,647 --> 00:39:10,315
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

893
00:39:25,096 --> 00:39:26,465
(FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING)

894
00:39:27,933 --> 00:39:29,034
Hello, Ma.

895
00:39:31,202 --> 00:39:32,838
That's for nothing.

896
00:39:34,239 --> 00:39:35,373
How do you like her?

897
00:39:35,407 --> 00:39:36,842
She's swell, isn't she?

898
00:39:36,875 --> 00:39:39,711
Looks like she can keep
Harry on his toes.

899
00:39:39,745 --> 00:39:42,080
Keep him out
of Bedford Falls, anyway.

900
00:39:44,215 --> 00:39:46,618
Did you know that
Mary Hatch is back
from school?

901
00:39:46,652 --> 00:39:47,786
Mmm-hmm.

902
00:39:47,819 --> 00:39:49,488
Came back three days ago.

903
00:39:49,521 --> 00:39:51,089
Mmm.

904
00:39:51,122 --> 00:39:54,760
Nice girl, Mary.
Mmm-hmm.

905
00:39:54,793 --> 00:39:57,463
Kind that'll help you
find the answers, George.

906
00:39:57,496 --> 00:39:58,564
Mmm-hmm.

907
00:39:58,597 --> 00:40:00,365
Stop that grunting.

908
00:40:00,999 --> 00:40:02,167
Mmm?

909
00:40:02,200 --> 00:40:04,169
Can you give me
one good reason

910
00:40:04,202 --> 00:40:05,671
why you shouldn't
call on Mary?

911
00:40:05,704 --> 00:40:07,138
Sure. Sam Wainwright.

912
00:40:07,172 --> 00:40:09,207
Hee-haw?
Yes, Sam's crazy
about Mary.

913
00:40:09,240 --> 00:40:10,509
Well, she's not crazy
about him.

914
00:40:10,542 --> 00:40:13,111
Well, how do you know?
W-What, did she
discuss it with you?

915
00:40:13,144 --> 00:40:14,446
No.
Well, then how
do you know?

916
00:40:14,480 --> 00:40:16,247
Well, I've got eyes,
haven't I?

917
00:40:16,281 --> 00:40:19,751
Why, she lights up
like a firefly
whenever you're around.

918
00:40:19,785 --> 00:40:20,852
Oh!

919
00:40:20,886 --> 00:40:23,288
Besides, Sam Wainwright's
away in New York,

920
00:40:23,321 --> 00:40:25,223
and you're here
in Bedford Falls.

921
00:40:25,256 --> 00:40:27,693
And all's fair
in love and war.

922
00:40:27,726 --> 00:40:29,628
I don't know about war.

923
00:40:32,998 --> 00:40:35,233
Mother of mine,
I can see
right through you

924
00:40:35,266 --> 00:40:36,802
right to your
back-collar button.

925
00:40:36,835 --> 00:40:39,070
Trying to get
rid of me, huh?
Mmm-hmm.

926
00:40:41,406 --> 00:40:43,909
Well, here's your hat.
What's your hurry?

927
00:40:44,910 --> 00:40:47,779
All right, Mother,
old Building and Loan pal,

928
00:40:47,813 --> 00:40:49,214
I think I'll go out
and find a girl

929
00:40:49,247 --> 00:40:51,116
and do a little
passionate necking.

930
00:40:51,149 --> 00:40:52,551
Oh, George.

931
00:40:52,584 --> 00:40:55,621
Now, if you'll
just point me in
the right direction...

932
00:40:56,955 --> 00:40:58,289
This direction.

933
00:41:05,463 --> 00:41:07,165
Good night, Mrs. Bailey.

934
00:41:18,510 --> 00:41:21,279
Excuse me.
Now, wait a minute.

935
00:41:21,312 --> 00:41:23,515
I think I got a date.

936
00:41:23,549 --> 00:41:26,284
But, uh,
stick around, fellows,
just in case, huh?

937
00:41:27,619 --> 00:41:28,754
We'll wait for you, baby.

938
00:41:31,256 --> 00:41:32,758
Hello, Georgie Porgie!

939
00:41:32,791 --> 00:41:33,825
Hello Vi.

940
00:41:35,193 --> 00:41:37,729
What gives?
Nothing.

941
00:41:37,763 --> 00:41:38,997
Where are you going?

942
00:41:39,030 --> 00:41:42,100
Oh, I'll probably end up
down at the library.

943
00:41:42,133 --> 00:41:46,504
Georgie, don't you
ever get tired of just
reading about things?

944
00:41:47,639 --> 00:41:49,474
Yes.

945
00:41:49,507 --> 00:41:50,776
What are you
doing tonight?

946
00:41:50,809 --> 00:41:52,544
Not a thing.

947
00:41:52,578 --> 00:41:54,412
Are you game, Vi?
Let's make a night of it.

948
00:41:54,445 --> 00:41:56,782
I'd love it, Georgie.
What'll we do?

949
00:41:56,815 --> 00:41:58,684
Let's go out in the fields
and take off our shoes

950
00:41:58,717 --> 00:41:59,985
and walk through the grass.

951
00:42:00,018 --> 00:42:01,219
Huh?

952
00:42:01,252 --> 00:42:02,387
Then we can go
up to the falls.

953
00:42:02,420 --> 00:42:04,189
It's beautiful up there
in the moonlight,

954
00:42:04,222 --> 00:42:08,927
and there's a green pool
up there, and we--we can, uh,
swim in it.

955
00:42:08,960 --> 00:42:12,297
Then we can
climb Mount Bedford
and smell the pines

956
00:42:12,330 --> 00:42:14,032
and watch the sunrise
against the peaks,

957
00:42:14,065 --> 00:42:15,567
and we'll stay up there
the whole night,

958
00:42:15,601 --> 00:42:17,903
and everybody'll be
talking. There'll be
a terrific scandal.

959
00:42:17,936 --> 00:42:19,170
Georgie, have you
gone crazy?

960
00:42:19,204 --> 00:42:21,272
Why, walk in the grass
in my bare feet?

961
00:42:21,306 --> 00:42:22,708
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

962
00:42:22,741 --> 00:42:25,176
(GEORGE SHUSHING)
Why it's 10 miles
up to Mount Bedford.

963
00:42:25,210 --> 00:42:26,778
If you think...
O-O-O-Okay,

964
00:42:26,812 --> 00:42:29,581
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)
just forget
about the whole thing.

965
