He just took over the bank.

1206
00:54:28,165 --> 00:54:29,834
I may lose a fortune,

1207
00:54:29,867 --> 00:54:33,771
but I'm willing
to guarantee
your people, too.

1208
00:54:33,804 --> 00:54:36,341
Just tell them to bring
their shares over here,

1209
00:54:36,374 --> 00:54:39,009
and I will pay
50 cents on the dollar.

1210
00:54:39,043 --> 00:54:41,211
Oh, you never miss a trick,
do you, Potter?

1211
00:54:41,245 --> 00:54:42,580
Well, you're gonna
miss this one.

1212
00:54:42,613 --> 00:54:46,417
If you close
your doors before 6:00 p.m.,
you will never reopen.

1213
00:54:46,451 --> 00:54:47,452
(PHONE HANGING UP)

1214
00:54:55,025 --> 00:54:56,527
George,
was it a nice wedding?

1215
00:54:56,561 --> 00:54:58,563
Gosh, I wanted to be there.

1216
00:54:58,963 --> 00:55:00,030
Yeah.

1217
00:55:01,932 --> 00:55:03,834
You can take
this one off now.

1218
00:55:08,739 --> 00:55:10,140
(CROWD MURMURING)

1219
00:55:12,710 --> 00:55:16,313
Now, just remember
that this thing

1220
00:55:16,347 --> 00:55:18,282
isn't as black
as it appeared.

1221
00:55:18,315 --> 00:55:19,884
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

1222
00:55:27,792 --> 00:55:29,694
I have some news
for you, folks.

1223
00:55:29,727 --> 00:55:31,195
I was just talking
to old man Potter,

1224
00:55:31,228 --> 00:55:32,897
and he's guaranteed
cash payments at the bank.

1225
00:55:32,930 --> 00:55:34,532
The bank's gonna
reopen next week.

1226
00:55:34,565 --> 00:55:36,534
But, George,
I got my money here.

1227
00:55:36,567 --> 00:55:38,202
Did he guarantee
this place?

1228
00:55:38,235 --> 00:55:40,137
Well, no, Charlie.
I didn't even ask him.

1229
00:55:40,170 --> 00:55:41,305
We don't need
Potter over here.

1230
00:55:41,338 --> 00:55:43,441
MAN: Then,
I'll take mine now.

1231
00:55:43,474 --> 00:55:45,843
No, but you're...

1232
00:55:45,876 --> 00:55:48,012
You're-- You're thinking
of this place all wrong,

1233
00:55:48,045 --> 00:55:49,880
as if I had
the money back in a safe.

1234
00:55:49,914 --> 00:55:51,716
The money's not here.

1235
00:55:51,749 --> 00:55:53,050
Well, your money's
in Joe's house.

1236
00:55:53,083 --> 00:55:54,318
That's right next to yours.

1237
00:55:54,351 --> 00:55:56,654
And in the Kennedy house
and Mrs. Macklin's house

1238
00:55:56,687 --> 00:55:58,255
and 100 others.

1239
00:55:58,288 --> 00:56:00,224
Why, you're lending them
the money to build,

1240
00:56:00,257 --> 00:56:02,059
and then,
they're gonna pay it back
to you as best they can.

1241
00:56:02,092 --> 00:56:03,794
Now, what are you gonna do,
foreclose on them?

1242
00:56:03,828 --> 00:56:06,664
I got $242 in here,

1243
00:56:06,697 --> 00:56:10,701
and $242 isn't going
to break anybody.

1244
00:56:10,735 --> 00:56:13,538
Okay, Tom. All right.

1245
00:56:13,571 --> 00:56:16,206
Here you are.
You sign this. You'll get
your money in 60 days.

1246
00:56:16,240 --> 00:56:17,508
Sixty days?

1247
00:56:17,542 --> 00:56:19,577
Now, that's what you
agreed to when you
bought your shares.

1248
00:56:19,610 --> 00:56:21,779
Tom! Tom, did you
get your money?
No.

1249
00:56:21,812 --> 00:56:23,313
Well, I did.

1250
00:56:23,347 --> 00:56:25,616
Old man Potter'll pay
50 cents on the dollar
for every share you've got.

1251
00:56:25,650 --> 00:56:27,184
ALL: 50 cents on the dollar!

1252
00:56:27,217 --> 00:56:28,285
Yes, cash!

1253
00:56:28,318 --> 00:56:29,954
Well, what do
you say?

1254
00:56:29,987 --> 00:56:32,657
Now, Tom, you have to stick
to your original agreement.

1255
00:56:32,690 --> 00:56:34,091
Now, give us 60 days on this.

1256
00:56:34,124 --> 00:56:35,192
Okay, Randall.

1257
00:56:35,225 --> 00:56:36,226
Are you going to
go to Potter's?

1258
00:56:36,260 --> 00:56:38,429
Better to get
half than nothing.

1259
00:56:38,463 --> 00:56:40,898
(ALL CLAMORING)
Tom! Tom!

1260
00:56:40,931 --> 00:56:43,133
Randall!
Now, Randall, wait! Wait.

1261
00:56:43,167 --> 00:56:45,235
Now, listen.
Now, listen to me.

1262
00:56:45,269 --> 00:56:47,004
I--I beg of you
not to do this thing.

1263
00:56:47,037 --> 00:56:49,173
If Potter gets a hold
of this Building and Loan,

1264
00:56:49,206 --> 00:56:51,208
there'll never be
another decent house
built in this town.

1265
00:56:51,241 --> 00:56:52,977
He's already got
charge of the bank.

1266
00:56:53,010 --> 00:56:56,747
He's got the bus line.
He got the department stores.
And now he's after us. Why?

1267
00:56:56,781 --> 00:57:00,084
Well, it's very simple.
Because we're cutting in
on his business, that's why.

1268
00:57:00,117 --> 00:57:02,286
And because
he wants to keep you
living in his slums

1269
00:57:02,319 --> 00:57:04,254
and paying the kind
of rent he decides.

1270
00:57:04,288 --> 00:57:06,290
Joe, you had one
of those Potter houses,
didn't you?

1271
00:57:06,323 --> 00:57:07,625
Well, have you forgotten?

1272
00:57:07,658 --> 00:57:09,827
Have you forgotten
what he charged you
for that broken-down shack?

1273
00:57:09,860 --> 00:57:11,095
Here, Ed, you know.

1274
00:57:11,128 --> 00:57:13,030
You remember last year
when things
weren't going so well

1275
00:57:13,063 --> 00:57:14,298
and you couldn't
make your payments.

1276
00:57:14,331 --> 00:57:15,833
Well, you didn't lose
your house, did you?

1277
00:57:15,866 --> 00:57:17,668
You think Potter
would've let you keep it?

1278
00:57:17,702 --> 00:57:20,437
Can't-- Can't you understand
what's happening here?

1279
00:57:20,471 --> 00:57:22,106
Don't you see
what's happening?

1280
00:57:22,139 --> 00:57:24,909
Potter isn't selling.
Potter's buying, and why?

1281
00:57:24,942 --> 00:57:27,177
Because we're panicky
and he's not. That's why.

1282
00:57:27,211 --> 00:57:28,479
He's picking up
some bargain.

1283
00:57:28,513 --> 00:57:30,915
Now we--we can get through
this thing all right.

1284
00:57:30,948 --> 00:57:32,817
We've-- We've got to
stick together, though.

1285
00:57:32,850 --> 00:57:34,384
We've got to have
faith in each other.

1286
00:57:34,418 --> 00:57:37,688
But my husband hasn't worked
in over a year,
and I need money.

1287
00:57:37,722 --> 00:57:39,490
How am going to live
until the bank opens?

1288
00:57:39,524 --> 00:57:40,725
I got doctor bills to pay.

1289
00:57:40,758 --> 00:57:41,892
I need cash.

1290
00:57:41,926 --> 00:57:43,894
MAN: I can't feed
my kids on faith.

1291
00:57:43,928 --> 00:57:45,663
How much do you need?

1292
00:57:45,696 --> 00:57:49,166
Hey! I got $2,000.

1293
00:57:49,800 --> 00:57:50,935
Here's $2,000.

1294
00:57:50,968 --> 00:57:52,336
This'll tide us over
till the bank reopens.

1295
00:57:52,369 --> 00:57:53,704
All right, Tom,
how much do you need?

1296
00:57:53,738 --> 00:57:55,205
$242.

1297
00:57:55,239 --> 00:57:57,808
Oh, Tom,
just enough to tide you over
until the bank reopens.

1298
00:57:57,842 --> 00:58:00,110
I'll take $242.

1299
00:58:00,144 --> 00:58:01,812
(ALL CHATTERING)

1300
00:58:02,813 --> 00:58:04,649
There you are.
That'll close my account.

1301
00:58:04,682 --> 00:58:07,051
Your account's still here.
That's a loan.

1302
00:58:07,084 --> 00:58:08,786
Okay. All right, Ed?

1303
00:58:08,819 --> 00:58:10,487
I got $300 here, George.

1304
00:58:10,521 --> 00:58:14,158
Now, Ed, w-w-what'll it take
till the bank opens?
What do you need?

1305
00:58:14,191 --> 00:58:16,594
Well, I suppose $20.

1306
00:58:16,627 --> 00:58:18,062
$20. Now you're talking.

1307
00:58:18,095 --> 00:58:19,496
Thanks, Ed. That's fine.

1308
00:58:19,530 --> 00:58:21,198
All right,
now, Mrs. Thompson,
how much do you want?

1309
00:58:21,231 --> 00:58:22,432
MRS. THOMPSON: But it's
your own money, George.

1310
00:58:22,466 --> 00:58:24,334
Never mind about that.
How much do you want?

1311
00:58:24,368 --> 00:58:26,503
I can get along
with $20, all right.
$20, fine.

1312
00:58:26,537 --> 00:58:27,638
And I'll sign the paper.

1313
00:58:27,672 --> 00:58:28,873
You don't have
to sign anything.

1314
00:58:28,906 --> 00:58:30,941
I know you.
You pay it when you can.
That's okay.

1315
00:58:30,975 --> 00:58:32,476
All right, Mrs. Davis?

1316
00:58:32,509 --> 00:58:34,144
Could I have $17.50?

1317
00:58:36,046 --> 00:58:38,082
(ALL LAUGHING)
Bless your heart.
Of course you can have it.

1318
00:58:38,115 --> 00:58:39,650
You got 50 cents?

1319
00:58:39,684 --> 00:58:41,118
Seven...
We're gonna make it, George.

1320
00:58:41,151 --> 00:58:42,720
...six...
They'll never
close us up today!

1321
00:58:42,753 --> 00:58:47,357
...five, four, three, two,

1322
00:58:47,391 --> 00:58:49,526
one, bingo!

1323
00:58:49,560 --> 00:58:51,461
We made it!
Close the door, Eustace!
We made it.

1324
00:58:51,495 --> 00:58:52,797
Look, look,
we're still in business.

1325
00:58:52,830 --> 00:58:54,264
We've still got
two bucks left.

1326
00:58:54,298 --> 00:58:56,166
Look, let's have
some of that.
Let's celebrate!

1327
00:58:56,200 --> 00:58:57,668
Get--get
some glasses, Tilly.

1328
00:58:57,702 --> 00:58:59,570
Well, a couple of
financial wizards.

1329
00:58:59,604 --> 00:59:01,005
Call us Rockefellers.

1330
00:59:01,038 --> 00:59:03,608
Get a tray
for these two great big
important simoleons here.

1331
00:59:03,641 --> 00:59:05,242
We'll save them
for seed. A toast.

1332
00:59:05,275 --> 00:59:08,779
A toast.
A toast to Mama Dollar
and to Papa Dollar,

1333
00:59:08,813 --> 00:59:10,981
and if you want to keep
this old Building and Loan
in business,

1334
00:59:11,015 --> 00:59:12,549
you better have
a family real quick.

1335
00:59:12,583 --> 00:59:15,485
I wish they were rabbits.
I wish they were, too.

1336
00:59:15,519 --> 00:59:18,388
Okay, let's put them
in the safe and
see what happens.

1337
00:59:18,422 --> 00:59:20,691
(ALL SINGING)

1338
00:59:25,996 --> 00:59:27,197
Close the door.

1339
00:59:27,231 --> 00:59:29,199
Folks, folks,
wedding cigars.

1340
00:59:29,233 --> 00:59:32,703
Oh-oh, wedding.
Holy mackerel, I'm married.

1341
00:59:32,737 --> 00:59:35,439
Where's Mary? Mary! Poor...

1342
00:59:35,472 --> 00:59:37,675
Look, I got a
train to catch.
Well, the train's gone.

1343
00:59:37,708 --> 00:59:40,144
I wonder
if Ernie's still here
with his taxicab.

1344
00:59:40,177 --> 00:59:42,647
George, there's
a call for you.

1345
00:59:42,680 --> 00:59:44,148
Look, will you get my wife
on the phone?

1346
00:59:44,181 --> 00:59:45,515
She's probably
over at her mother's.

1347
00:59:45,549 --> 00:59:47,151
Mrs. Bailey is
on the phone.

1348
00:59:47,184 --> 00:59:49,253
I don't want Mrs. Bailey.
I want my wife.

1349
00:59:49,286 --> 00:59:51,321
Mrs. Bailey!
Oh, that's my wife.

1350
00:59:51,355 --> 00:59:53,190
Here, I'll take it
in here.

1351
00:59:53,223 --> 00:59:56,694
Mary. Hello.
Listen, dear, I'm sorry.

1352
00:59:56,727 --> 01:00:00,430
Huh? Come home?
What home?

1353
01:00:01,198 --> 01:00:03,100
320 Sycamore?
Well, what...

1354
01:00:03,133 --> 01:00:04,935
Whose home is that?

1355
01:00:05,770 --> 01:00:08,105
The Waldorf Hotel, huh?

1356
01:00:18,548 --> 01:00:20,317
Hey, this is
the company's posters,

1357
01:00:20,350 --> 01:00:21,652
and the company
won't like this.

1358
01:00:21,686 --> 01:00:23,721
How would you like
to get a ticket next week?

1359
01:00:23,754 --> 01:00:25,122
You got
any romance in you?

1360
01:00:25,155 --> 01:00:26,657
Sure, I had it,
but I got rid of it.

1361
01:00:26,691 --> 01:00:27,858
Liver pills.

1362
01:00:27,892 --> 01:00:30,394
Who wants to see liver pills
on their honeymoon?

1363
01:00:30,427 --> 01:00:32,897
What we want is
romantic places,
beautiful places,

1364
01:00:32,930 --> 01:00:34,965
places George
wants to go.

1365
01:00:34,999 --> 01:00:36,066
(MAN WHISTLES)

1366
01:00:36,100 --> 01:00:37,902
Hey, Bert. Here he comes.

1367
01:00:37,935 --> 01:00:39,236
Come on,
we got to get this up.
He's coming.

1368
01:00:39,269 --> 01:00:41,205
Who?
The groom, idiot.

1369
01:00:41,238 --> 01:00:43,173
This is their honeymoon.
Come on. Get that ladder.

1370
01:00:43,207 --> 01:00:44,742
What are they, ducks?

1371
01:00:47,544 --> 01:00:49,847
Get that ladder up here.
All right, all right.

1372
01:00:49,880 --> 01:00:51,315
Hurry up. Hurry up.
Hurry up.

1373
01:00:51,348 --> 01:00:52,717
I'm hurrying.

1374
01:01:01,759 --> 01:01:04,428
Hiya... Good evening, sir.

1375
01:01:06,596 --> 01:01:08,165
(GREETING IN FRENCH)

1376
01:01:10,000 --> 01:01:11,468
(GREETING IN FRENCH)

1377
01:01:12,136 --> 01:01:13,938
(SLOW MUSIC PLAYING)

1378
01:02:03,788 --> 01:02:04,789
(INAUDIBLE)

1379
01:02:29,814 --> 01:02:32,116
Welcome home, Mr. Bailey.

1380
01:02:36,821 --> 01:02:38,956
Well, I'll be...

1381
01:02:44,061 --> 01:02:46,763
Mary. Mary,
where did you...

1382
01:02:53,203 --> 01:02:58,675
* I love you truly

1383
01:02:58,708 --> 01:03:03,747
* Truly, dear

1384
01:03:03,780 --> 01:03:07,584
* Life with its shadows

1385
01:03:07,617 --> 01:03:09,586
Oh, Mary.

1386
01:03:09,619 --> 01:03:12,422
* Life with its tears

1387
01:03:12,456 --> 01:03:15,692
Remember the night we broke
some windows in this old
house?

1388
01:03:16,894 --> 01:03:18,929
This is what I wished for.

1389
01:03:22,933 --> 01:03:24,668
You're wonderful.

1390
01:03:27,771 --> 01:03:29,773
(WHISPERING)
You're wonderful.

1391
01:03:33,210 --> 01:03:39,649
* Truly, dear

1392
01:03:48,825 --> 01:03:51,528
Martini,
you rented a new house?

1393
01:03:51,561 --> 01:03:52,829
Rent?

1394
01:03:52,863 --> 01:03:54,098
(LAUGHING)

1395
01:03:54,131 --> 01:03:56,633
You hear
what he say, Mr. Bailey?
What's that?

1396
01:03:56,666 --> 01:03:58,568
I own the house.

1397
01:03:58,602 --> 01:04:02,006
Me, Giuseppe Martini,
I own my own house.

1398
01:04:02,039 --> 01:04:05,442
No more we live like a pigs
in this Potter's Field.

1399
01:04:05,475 --> 01:04:06,843
Mary, Mary!

1400
01:04:06,877 --> 01:04:08,212
Mary, come on,
bring the baby.

1401
01:04:08,245 --> 01:04:09,579
(ALL CHATTERING)

1402
01:04:09,613 --> 01:04:11,081
I feel like a queen.

1403
01:04:11,115 --> 01:04:12,316
I'll take
the kids in the car.

1404
01:04:12,349 --> 01:04:14,251
Oh, thank you,
Mr. Bailey. Thank you.

1405
01:04:14,284 --> 01:04:17,254
All right, kids, here.
Here, get in here.

1406
01:04:17,287 --> 01:04:19,456
Now, one at a time.
Get right up
on the seat there.

1407
01:04:20,925 --> 01:04:21,959
Sit down, there.

1408
01:04:21,992 --> 01:04:23,760
Here, now, get the dog, now.
That's it.

1409
01:04:25,862 --> 01:04:28,332
Goat, too.
Everybody!

1410
01:04:28,365 --> 01:04:29,833
All in!

1411
01:04:29,866 --> 01:04:31,902
(ALL EXCLAIMING)

1412
01:04:31,936 --> 01:04:33,837
MARTINI: Bye-bye! Bye-bye!

1413
01:04:36,873 --> 01:04:38,008
All in?

1414
01:04:42,246 --> 01:04:45,249
(O SOLE MIO PLAYING)

1415
01:04:45,682 --> 01:04:47,317
(GOAT BLEATING)

1416
01:04:56,626 --> 01:04:59,529
Mr. and Mrs. Martini,
welcome home.

1417
01:04:59,563 --> 01:05:02,132
Good old George,
he's always making a speech.

1418
01:05:03,167 --> 01:05:04,668
Hee-haw!

1419
01:05:04,701 --> 01:05:06,770
Sam Wainwright.

1420
01:05:06,803 --> 01:05:08,838
Oh, who cares.

1421
01:05:08,872 --> 01:05:12,742
Bread. That this house
may never know hunger.

1422
01:05:12,776 --> 01:05:16,513
Salt. That life
may always have flavor.

1423
01:05:16,546 --> 01:05:20,050
And wine.
That joy and prosperity
may reign forever.

1424
01:05:20,084 --> 01:05:21,685
Enter the Martini castle.

1425
01:05:21,718 --> 01:05:23,653
(ALL CHEERING)

1426
01:05:23,687 --> 01:05:26,190
Look, Mr. Potter,
it's no skin off my nose.

1427
01:05:26,223 --> 01:05:28,092
I'm just your little
rent collector.

1428
01:05:28,125 --> 01:05:30,995
But you can't laugh off
this Bailey Park anymore.

1429
01:05:31,028 --> 01:05:32,796
(INTERCOM BUZZING)
Look at it.

1430
01:05:32,829 --> 01:05:35,099
WOMAN ON INTERCOM:
Congressman Black is here
to see you, sir.

1431
01:05:35,132 --> 01:05:38,168
Oh, tell the Congressman
to wait. Go on.

1432
01:05:38,202 --> 01:05:41,038
Fifteen years ago,
a half a dozen houses
stuck here and there.

1433
01:05:41,071 --> 01:05:43,373
There's the old cemetery,
squirrels, buttercups,
daisies.

1434
01:05:43,407 --> 01:05:45,609
I used to hunt
rabbits there myself.

1435
01:05:46,476 --> 01:05:47,911
Look at it today.

1436
01:05:47,944 --> 01:05:50,914
Dozens of the prettiest
little homes you ever saw,

1437
01:05:50,947 --> 01:05:54,218
90 per cent owned by suckers
who used to pay rent to you.

1438
01:05:54,251 --> 01:05:57,621
Your Potter's Field,
my dear Mr. Employer,
is becoming just that.

1439
01:05:57,654 --> 01:06:01,158
And are the local yokels
making with those
David and Goliath wisecracks.

1440
01:06:01,191 --> 01:06:02,993
Oh, they are, are they?

1441
01:06:03,027 --> 01:06:05,996
Even though they know
the Baileys never
made a dime out of it.

1442
01:06:06,030 --> 01:06:08,565
You know very well why.
The Baileys were all chumps.

1443
01:06:08,598 --> 01:06:10,434
Every one of these homes

1444
01:06:10,467 --> 01:06:12,802
is worth twice
what it cost the Building
and Loan to build.

1445
01:06:12,836 --> 01:06:15,339
If I were you,
Mr. Potter...
You are not me.

1446
01:06:15,372 --> 01:06:18,875
As I say,
it's no skin off my nose,

1447
01:06:21,978 --> 01:06:23,980
but one of these days
this bright young man

1448
01:06:24,014 --> 01:06:26,650
is gonna be asking
George Bailey for a job.

1449
01:06:29,053 --> 01:06:32,222
The Bailey family has been
a boil on my neck long enough.

1450
01:06:32,256 --> 01:06:34,658
WOMAN ON INTERCOM: Yes, sir?
Come in here.

1451
01:06:34,691 --> 01:06:36,926
We just stopped in town
to take a look
at the new factory,

1452
01:06:36,960 --> 01:06:38,995
and then we're gonna
drive on down to Florida.
Oh.

1453
01:06:39,029 --> 01:06:40,730
Why don't you
have your friends join us?

1454
01:06:40,764 --> 01:06:44,501
Why, sure.
Hey, why don't you kids
drive down with us, huh?

1455
01:06:44,534 --> 01:06:47,371
Oh, I'm afraid
I couldn't get away, Sam.

1456
01:06:47,404 --> 01:06:49,506
Still got the nose
to the old grindstone, eh?

1457
01:06:49,539 --> 01:06:51,541
Jane, I offered
to let George in

1458
01:06:51,575 --> 01:06:53,177
on the ground floor
in plastics,

1459
01:06:53,210 --> 01:06:54,444
and he turned me
down cold.

1460
01:06:54,478 --> 01:06:56,012
Oh, now, don't rub it in.

1461
01:06:56,046 --> 01:06:57,314
I'm not rubbing it in.

1462
01:06:57,347 --> 01:06:59,015
Well, I guess we better
run along.

1463
01:06:59,049 --> 01:07:01,151
Awfully happy
to have met you, Mary.
Nice meeting you, too.

1464
01:07:01,185 --> 01:07:02,619
Goodbye. Glad to see you.
Goodbye, George.

1465
01:07:02,652 --> 01:07:04,154
So long, George.
See you in the funny papers.

1466
01:07:04,188 --> 01:07:06,323
So long, Mary.
Bye, Sam. Have fun.

1467
01:07:06,356 --> 01:07:08,425
Thanks for
dropping around.
Florida!

1468
01:07:08,458 --> 01:07:10,160
Hee-haw!
BOTH: Hee-haw.

1469
01:07:39,456 --> 01:07:41,291
Thank you, sir.

1470
01:07:41,325 --> 01:07:43,360
That's quite
a cigar, Mr. Potter.
You like it?

1471
01:07:43,393 --> 01:07:44,961
I'll send you a box.

1472
01:07:53,803 --> 01:07:55,071
Well, I, uh...

1473
01:07:56,640 --> 01:07:58,175
I suppose I'll find out
sooner or later,

1474
01:07:58,208 --> 01:08:00,310
but just what
exactly did you want
to see me about?

1475
01:08:00,344 --> 01:08:01,645
(LAUGHING)

1476
01:08:03,180 --> 01:08:07,251
George, now that's
just what I like
so much about you.

1477
01:08:07,284 --> 01:08:10,987
George, I am an old man,
and most people hate me.

1478
01:08:11,020 --> 01:08:14,057
But I don't like them, either,
so that makes it all even.

1479
01:08:14,090 --> 01:08:16,326
You know
just as well as I do

1480
01:08:16,360 --> 01:08:18,928
that I run
practically everything
in this town

1481
01:08:18,962 --> 01:08:21,998
but the Bailey
Building and Loan.

1482
01:08:22,031 --> 01:08:24,201
You know, also,
that for a number of years

1483
01:08:24,234 --> 01:08:26,170
I've been trying
to get control of it.

1484
01:08:26,203 --> 01:08:29,005
Or kill it.
But I haven't
been able to do it.

1485
01:08:29,038 --> 01:08:31,007
You have been stopping me.

1486
01:08:32,108 --> 01:08:35,312
In fact,
you have beaten me, George,

1487
01:08:35,345 --> 01:08:39,816
and as anyone in this county
can tell you,
that takes some doing.

1488
01:08:40,917 --> 01:08:43,687
Take during the Depression,
for instance.

1489
01:08:43,720 --> 01:08:46,856
You and I were the only ones
that kept our heads.

1490
01:08:46,890 --> 01:08:48,892
You saved
the Building and Loan.

1491
01:08:48,925 --> 01:08:50,894
I saved all the rest.

1492
01:08:50,927 --> 01:08:53,630
Yes. Well, most people say
you stole all the rest.

1493
01:08:53,663 --> 01:08:57,901
The envious ones say that,
George, the suckers.

1494
01:08:57,934 --> 01:09:02,339
Now, I have stated
my side very frankly.

1495
01:09:02,372 --> 01:09:04,508
Now let's look at your side.

1496
01:09:05,442 --> 01:09:09,413
Young man, 27-28,

1497
01:09:09,446 --> 01:09:12,449
married,
making, say, $40 a week.

1498
01:09:12,482 --> 01:09:14,451
$45.
$45.

1499
01:09:14,484 --> 01:09:15,952
$45.

1500
01:09:15,985 --> 01:09:18,322
Out of which,
after supporting
your mother

1501
01:09:18,355 --> 01:09:19,923
and paying your bills,

1502
01:09:19,956 --> 01:09:23,126
you're able to keep,
say, $10, if you skimp.

1503
01:09:23,159 --> 01:09:27,531
A child or two comes along,
and you won't even be able
to save the $10.

1504
01:09:27,564 --> 01:09:33,136
Now, if this young man of 28
was a common, ordinary yokel,

1505
01:09:33,169 --> 01:09:34,804
I'd say he was doing fine.

1506
01:09:34,838 --> 01:09:39,175
But George Bailey
is not a common,
ordinary yokel.

1507
01:09:39,209 --> 01:09:42,946
He is an intelligent, smart,
ambitious young man,

1508
01:09:42,979 --> 01:09:46,250
who hates his job,
who hates
the Building and Loan

1509
01:09:46,283 --> 01:09:48,618
almost as much as I do.

1510
01:09:48,652 --> 01:09:53,623
A young man who's been dying
to get out on his own
ever since he was born.

1511
01:09:53,657 --> 01:09:56,526
A young man...
The smartest one
of the crowd, mind you.

1512
01:09:56,560 --> 01:09:58,228
A young man
who has to sit by

1513
01:09:58,262 --> 01:10:01,765
and watch
his friends go places
because he's trapped.

1514
01:10:01,798 --> 01:10:05,502
Yes, sir, trapped
into frittering his life away,

1515
01:10:05,535 --> 01:10:08,137
playing nursemaid
to a lot of garlic eaters.

1516
01:10:09,606 --> 01:10:12,909
Do I paint a correct picture,
or do I exaggerate?

1517
01:10:15,379 --> 01:10:16,780
Now, what's
your point, Mr. Potter?

1518
01:10:16,813 --> 01:10:17,981
My point?

1519
01:10:18,014 --> 01:10:20,650
My point is I want
to hire you.
Hire me?

1520
01:10:20,684 --> 01:10:24,153
Yeah, I want you
to manage my affairs,
run my properties.

1521
01:10:24,187 --> 01:10:29,293
George, I'll start you out
at $20,000 a year.

1522
01:10:33,129 --> 01:10:36,132
$20,000 a year?

1523
01:10:36,165 --> 01:10:39,603
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1524
01:10:39,636 --> 01:10:42,372
buying your wife
a lot of fine clothes,

1525
01:10:42,406 --> 01:10:45,241
a couple of business trips
to New York a year,

1526
01:10:45,275 --> 01:10:47,176
maybe once in a while Europe.

1527
01:10:47,210 --> 01:10:48,578
You wouldn't mind that,
would you, George?

1528
01:10:48,612 --> 01:10:49,979
Would I?

1529
01:10:52,982 --> 01:10:55,352
Y-You're not
talking to somebody else
around here, are you?

1530
01:10:55,385 --> 01:10:57,921
You know, this--this is me.
You remember me?
George Bailey.

1531
01:10:57,954 --> 01:10:59,022
George Bailey.

1532
01:10:59,055 --> 01:11:03,393
Yeah, George Bailey,
whose ship has just come in.

1533
01:11:03,427 --> 01:11:06,663
Provided he has enough brains
to climb aboard.

1534
01:11:14,971 --> 01:11:16,406
Holy mackerel.

1535
01:11:19,476 --> 01:11:22,078
Well, how about
the Building and Loan?

1536
01:11:22,111 --> 01:11:25,615
Oh, confound it, man,
are you afraid of success?

1537
01:11:25,649 --> 01:11:28,151
I'm offering you
a three-years contract

1538
01:11:28,184 --> 01:11:30,620
at $20,000 a year,
starting today.

1539
01:11:30,654 --> 01:11:32,389
Is it a deal, or isn't it?

1540
01:11:34,023 --> 01:11:35,859
Well, Mr. Potter, I...

1541
01:11:35,892 --> 01:11:39,696
I--I know I ought to
jump at the chance
but I... I just, uh...

1542
01:11:40,797 --> 01:11:43,367
I--I wonder if it would
be possible for you

1543
01:11:43,400 --> 01:11:44,901
to give me 24 hours
to think it over?

1544
01:11:44,934 --> 01:11:46,670
Sure, sure, sure.

1545
01:11:46,703 --> 01:11:49,305
You go on home
and talk about it
to your wife.

1546
01:11:49,339 --> 01:11:50,940
I'd like to do that.
Yeah.

1547
01:11:50,974 --> 01:11:53,377
In the meantime,
I'll draw up the papers.

1548
01:11:53,410 --> 01:11:55,311
All right, sir.
Okay, George?

1549
01:11:56,913 --> 01:11:58,648
Okay, Mr. Potter.

1550
01:12:06,523 --> 01:12:11,661
No. No. No, no,
now wait a minute, here.
Wait a...

1551
01:12:11,695 --> 01:12:13,162
I don't need 24 hours.

1552
01:12:13,196 --> 01:12:14,598
I--I don't have
to talk to anybody.

1553
01:12:14,631 --> 01:12:18,435
I know right now,
and the answer is no.
No, doggone it!

1554
01:12:18,468 --> 01:12:20,970
You sit around here,
and you spin
your little webs,

1555
01:12:21,004 --> 01:12:23,540
and you think the whole world
revolves around you
and your money.

1556
01:12:23,573 --> 01:12:25,174
Well, it doesn't,
Mr. Potter.

1557
01:12:25,208 --> 01:12:28,445
In the-- In the whole vast
configuration of things,

1558
01:12:28,478 --> 01:12:31,314
I'd say you were nothing
but a scurvy little spider.

1559
01:12:31,347 --> 01:12:32,348
You...

1560
01:12:33,817 --> 01:12:35,952
And that goes
for you, too!

1561
01:12:40,023 --> 01:12:42,125
And it goes for you, too!

1562
01:12:49,098 --> 01:12:52,536
POTTER:
You wouldn't mind living
in the nicest house in town,

1563
01:12:52,569 --> 01:12:55,371
buying your wife
a lot of fine clothes,

1564
01:12:55,405 --> 01:12:58,975
going to New York
on a business trip
a couple of times a year,

1565
01:12:59,008 --> 01:13:02,178
maybe Europe
once in a while.

1566
01:13:02,211 --> 01:13:04,380
GEORGE: I know what
I'm gonna do tomorrow

1567
01:13:04,414 --> 01:13:07,684
and the next
day and next year
and the year after that.

1568
01:13:07,717 --> 01:13:10,920
I'm shaking the dust
of this crummy
little town off my feet,

1569
01:13:10,954 --> 01:13:12,822
and I'm gonna
see the world.

1570
01:13:12,856 --> 01:13:14,090
And then I'm
gonna build things.

1571
01:13:14,123 --> 01:13:15,659
I'm gonna build airfields.

1572
01:13:15,692 --> 01:13:18,327
I'm gonna build skyscrapers
100 stories high.

1573
01:13:18,361 --> 01:13:20,764
I'm gonna build
a bridge a mile long.

1574
01:13:22,031 --> 01:13:23,633
What is it you want, Mary?

1575
01:13:23,667 --> 01:13:25,735
What, you--you want the moon?

1576
01:13:25,769 --> 01:13:28,271
If you do, just say the word,
I'll throw a lasso around it

1577
01:13:28,304 --> 01:13:30,206
and pull her down for you.

1578
