fly Mother home
this afternoon.

1677
01:18:05,681 --> 01:18:06,816
In a plane?

1678
01:18:07,416 --> 01:18:09,185
What? Uncle Billy?

1679
01:18:09,218 --> 01:18:10,453
Has Uncle Billy
come in yet?

1680
01:18:10,486 --> 01:18:11,620
Oh, he stopped
at the bank first.

1681
01:18:11,654 --> 01:18:13,256
He's not here
right now, Harry.

1682
01:18:13,289 --> 01:18:15,725
But look, now, tell--
tell me about it.
George. George, George.

1683
01:18:15,759 --> 01:18:17,093
What?
That man is here again.

1684
01:18:17,126 --> 01:18:18,895
What man?
(STAMMERING)
Bank examiner.

1685
01:18:18,928 --> 01:18:20,196
Oh, oh.

1686
01:18:20,229 --> 01:18:22,598
Uh, Harry, talk to Eustace
for a minute, will you?

1687
01:18:22,631 --> 01:18:23,867
I'll be right back.

1688
01:18:23,900 --> 01:18:25,334
Well, Harry.

1689
01:18:25,368 --> 01:18:26,635
(CLEARING THROAT)
Oh, good morning, sir.

1690
01:18:26,669 --> 01:18:28,004
Carter, bank examiner.

1691
01:18:28,037 --> 01:18:30,239
Mr. Carter, Merry Christmas.
Merry Christmas.

1692
01:18:30,273 --> 01:18:32,075
We're all excited
around here.

1693
01:18:32,108 --> 01:18:34,077
My brother just got
the Congressional
Medal of Honor.

1694
01:18:34,110 --> 01:18:35,311
The President
just decorated him.

1695
01:18:35,344 --> 01:18:37,080
Well, I guess they do
those things.

1696
01:18:37,113 --> 01:18:38,882
Well, I trust you had
a good year.

1697
01:18:38,915 --> 01:18:40,216
Good year?

1698
01:18:40,249 --> 01:18:43,586
Uh, well, between you and me,
Mr. Carter, we're broke.

1699
01:18:43,619 --> 01:18:45,288
Yeah, very funny.

1700
01:18:46,355 --> 01:18:47,523
(CLEARING THROAT)

1701
01:18:47,556 --> 01:18:50,159
Well, uh, well, now,
come right in here,
Mr. Carter.

1702
01:18:50,193 --> 01:18:52,495
Although I shouldn't
wonder when you okay
reverse charges

1703
01:18:52,528 --> 01:18:54,330
on personal
long-distance calls.

1704
01:18:54,363 --> 01:18:55,932
George, shall
we hang up?

1705
01:18:55,965 --> 01:18:57,834
No, no. He wants to
talk to Uncle Billy.
You just hold on, there.

1706
01:18:57,867 --> 01:19:00,603
Now, if you'll cooperate,
I'd like to finish
with you by tonight.

1707
01:19:00,636 --> 01:19:03,539
I want to spend Christmas
in Elmira with my family.

1708
01:19:03,572 --> 01:19:05,008
I don't blame you at all,
Mr. Carter.

1709
01:19:05,041 --> 01:19:06,275
Just step right in here.
We'll fix you up.

1710
01:19:07,276 --> 01:19:10,146
December 24.

1711
01:19:16,085 --> 01:19:19,588
$8,000.

1712
01:19:19,622 --> 01:19:22,258
ALL: Merry Christmas,
Mr. Potter.
Merry Christmas.

1713
01:19:22,291 --> 01:19:25,761
Well, good morning,
Mr. Potter.
What's the news?

1714
01:19:25,795 --> 01:19:29,598
Oh, well, well, well,
"Harry Bailey wins
Congressional Medal."

1715
01:19:29,632 --> 01:19:31,767
That couldn't be
one of the Bailey boys.

1716
01:19:31,801 --> 01:19:35,438
You just can't keep
those Baileys down,
now can you, Mr. Potter?

1717
01:19:35,471 --> 01:19:37,941
How does slacker George
feel about that?

1718
01:19:37,974 --> 01:19:39,275
Very jealous.
Very jealous.

1719
01:19:39,308 --> 01:19:41,577
He only lost three
buttons off his vest.

1720
01:19:41,610 --> 01:19:43,712
Of course,
slacker George
would've gotten

1721
01:19:43,746 --> 01:19:45,748
two of these medals
if he had gone.

1722
01:19:45,781 --> 01:19:47,183
Bad ear.
Yes.

1723
01:19:47,216 --> 01:19:51,054
After all, Potter,
some people like George
had to stay at home.

1724
01:19:51,087 --> 01:19:54,891
Not every heel
was in Germany
and Japan.

1725
01:19:54,924 --> 01:19:56,159
(CHUCKLING)

1726
01:20:02,365 --> 01:20:04,333
Good morning,
Mr. Bailey.

1727
01:20:04,367 --> 01:20:05,935
Good morning, Horace.

1728
01:20:07,070 --> 01:20:08,571
I guess you forgot
something.

1729
01:20:08,604 --> 01:20:09,939
Huh?

1730
01:20:09,973 --> 01:20:11,875
You forgot something.
What?

1731
01:20:11,908 --> 01:20:13,376
Well, aren't you going
to make a deposit?

1732
01:20:13,409 --> 01:20:14,944
Oh, sure, sure I am.

1733
01:20:14,978 --> 01:20:17,213
Well, then, it's usually
customary to bring
the money with you.

1734
01:20:17,246 --> 01:20:18,581
Huh?

1735
01:20:18,614 --> 01:20:20,583
Oh, shucks,

1736
01:20:21,484 --> 01:20:23,652
I knew I had. I...

1737
01:20:24,487 --> 01:20:26,622
How about that
finger there?

1738
01:20:26,655 --> 01:20:27,756
Well, I...

1739
01:20:28,624 --> 01:20:29,825
Bailey.

1740
01:20:36,332 --> 01:20:38,734
Take me back there.
Hurry up.

1741
01:20:40,836 --> 01:20:43,072
Come on, look sharp.

1742
01:21:00,756 --> 01:21:02,291
Take me back.

1743
01:21:12,201 --> 01:21:13,802
Just make yourself
at home, Mr. Carter.

1744
01:21:13,836 --> 01:21:15,571
I got those books
for you here.

1745
01:21:15,604 --> 01:21:17,006
Oh, hello, Vi.

1746
01:21:17,040 --> 01:21:18,674
George,
can I see you
for a second?

1747
01:21:18,707 --> 01:21:21,877
Why, of course you can.
Go on in the office there.

1748
01:21:21,911 --> 01:21:23,980
Oh, Uncle Billy,
talk to Harry.
He's on the telephone.

1749
01:21:25,381 --> 01:21:26,749
TILLY: Hurry up,
Uncle Billy, hurry.

1750
01:21:26,782 --> 01:21:28,217
Long distance, Washington.

1751
01:21:28,251 --> 01:21:29,585
EUSTACE: Hey, here's Harry
on the phone.

1752
01:21:29,618 --> 01:21:31,054
You know, your nephew,
remember? Harry.

1753
01:21:31,087 --> 01:21:33,022
Here he is.
Hurry up.

1754
01:21:33,056 --> 01:21:37,293
(STAMMERING)
Hello? Hello. Yes, Harry,
yes, everything's fine.

1755
01:21:37,326 --> 01:21:39,562
I ought to have
my head examined.

1756
01:21:39,595 --> 01:21:42,498
$8,000.
It's got to be
somewhere.

1757
01:21:48,671 --> 01:21:49,905
Here you are.

1758
01:21:50,473 --> 01:21:52,175
Character?

1759
01:21:52,208 --> 01:21:53,542
If I had
any character, I'd...

1760
01:21:53,576 --> 01:21:55,411
It takes a lot of character
to leave your hometown

1761
01:21:55,444 --> 01:21:57,080
and start all over again.

1762
01:21:57,113 --> 01:21:58,614
No, George, don't.

1763
01:21:58,647 --> 01:22:00,716
Here now, you're broke,
aren't you?

1764
01:22:00,749 --> 01:22:02,418
I know, but...
What do you want to do,

1765
01:22:02,451 --> 01:22:04,253
hock your furs
and that hat?

1766
01:22:05,621 --> 01:22:07,156
You want to walk
to New York?

1767
01:22:07,190 --> 01:22:09,025
You know, they charge
for meals and rent up there,

1768
01:22:09,058 --> 01:22:10,526
just the same as they do
in Bedford Falls.

1769
01:22:10,559 --> 01:22:12,628
Yeah, sure.
No, that's a loan, now.

1770
01:22:12,661 --> 01:22:15,131
That's my business,
Building and Loan.

1771
01:22:15,164 --> 01:22:16,665
Besides, you'll get a job.

1772
01:22:16,699 --> 01:22:18,201
Good luck to you.

1773
01:22:18,234 --> 01:22:20,403
I'm glad I know you,
George Bailey.

1774
01:22:25,608 --> 01:22:27,010
Say hello to New York
for me.

1775
01:22:27,043 --> 01:22:28,411
Yeah, yeah, sure, I will.

1776
01:22:28,444 --> 01:22:30,346
Now, let's hear from you
once in a while.

1777
01:22:34,550 --> 01:22:36,085
Merry Christmas, Vi.

1778
01:22:36,119 --> 01:22:38,521
Merry Christmas, George.

1779
01:22:38,554 --> 01:22:41,057
Mr. Bailey.
Oh, Mr. Carter, I'm sorry.

1780
01:22:41,090 --> 01:22:42,625
I'll be right with you.
Uncle Billy in there?

1781
01:22:42,658 --> 01:22:44,227
TILLY: Yeah,
he's in his office.

1782
01:22:44,260 --> 01:22:46,629
Unc...
What's going on?

1783
01:22:46,662 --> 01:22:48,664
The bank
examiner's here.

1784
01:22:49,132 --> 01:22:50,366
He's here?

1785
01:22:50,399 --> 01:22:52,468
Oh, yeah, yeah. He wants
the accounts payable...

1786
01:22:52,501 --> 01:22:54,137
What's the matter
with you?

1787
01:22:54,170 --> 01:22:55,604
Come here.

1788
01:22:56,305 --> 01:22:57,573
(DOOR CLOSING)

1789
01:23:16,192 --> 01:23:17,393
Eustace.
Yeah?

1790
01:23:17,426 --> 01:23:18,627
Come here a minute.

1791
01:23:20,396 --> 01:23:22,831
Did you see Uncle Billy
with any cash last night?

1792
01:23:22,865 --> 01:23:25,334
He had it on his desk
counting it
before he closed up.

1793
01:23:26,402 --> 01:23:28,037
Now, look,
did you buy anything?

1794
01:23:28,071 --> 01:23:30,439
Nothing. Not even
a stick of gum.
All right, all right.

1795
01:23:30,473 --> 01:23:31,940
Now, we'll go over
every step you took

1796
01:23:31,974 --> 01:23:33,209
since you left
the house.

1797
01:23:33,242 --> 01:23:34,510
Right. This way.
Come on.

1798
01:23:39,182 --> 01:23:40,449
(HORN HONKING)

1799
01:23:44,187 --> 01:23:46,155
And did you put the envelope
in your pocket?

1800
01:23:46,189 --> 01:23:48,991
Yeah, maybe, maybe.

1801
01:23:49,024 --> 01:23:50,826
Maybe! Maybe!
I don't want any maybe.

1802
01:23:50,859 --> 01:23:52,261
We've got to find
that money!

1803
01:23:52,295 --> 01:23:53,862
I'm no good to you, George.
Uncle Billy, look,

1804
01:23:53,896 --> 01:23:56,465
do you realize
what's going to happen
if we don't find it?

1805
01:23:56,499 --> 01:23:57,600
Listen to me.

1806
01:23:57,633 --> 01:23:59,435
Do you have any
secret hiding place
here in the house?

1807
01:23:59,468 --> 01:24:00,569
Someplace
you would have...

1808
01:24:00,603 --> 01:24:01,770
Someplace you hide
the money?

1809
01:24:01,804 --> 01:24:03,372
I've gone over
the whole house,

1810
01:24:03,406 --> 01:24:07,376
even in rooms
that have been locked
since I lost Laura.

1811
01:24:07,410 --> 01:24:10,579
Listen to me, listen to me!
Think, think!

1812
01:24:10,613 --> 01:24:12,648
I can't think anymore,
George.

1813
01:24:12,681 --> 01:24:14,783
I can't think anymore.
It hurts.

1814
01:24:14,817 --> 01:24:17,753
Where's that money,
you silly, stupid old fool?

1815
01:24:17,786 --> 01:24:18,954
Where's that money?

1816
01:24:18,987 --> 01:24:20,623
Do you realize
what this means?

1817
01:24:20,656 --> 01:24:23,659
It means bankruptcy
and scandal and prison!

1818
01:24:24,760 --> 01:24:26,129
That's what it means.

1819
01:24:26,162 --> 01:24:27,496
One of us is going to jail.

1820
01:24:27,530 --> 01:24:29,098
Well, it's not going
to be me.

1821
01:24:38,574 --> 01:24:40,209
(SOBBING)

1822
01:24:43,479 --> 01:24:46,215
(PLAYING HARK!
THE HERALD ANGELS SING)

1823
01:24:52,221 --> 01:24:53,756
Hello, darling.
Hello, Daddy.

1824
01:24:53,789 --> 01:24:55,191
Hello, Daddy.
Hello, Daddy.

1825
01:24:55,224 --> 01:24:57,126
(SNEEZING)
How do you like it?

1826
01:24:57,160 --> 01:24:58,861
Bless you!
Bless you!

1827
01:25:00,596 --> 01:25:01,830
Did you bring
the wreath?

1828
01:25:01,864 --> 01:25:03,632
PETE: Yes, Daddy,
did you bring
the Christmas wreath?

1829
01:25:03,666 --> 01:25:04,833
What wreath?

1830
01:25:04,867 --> 01:25:07,370
Th-The Merry Christmas wreath
for the window.

1831
01:25:07,403 --> 01:25:08,771
No. I left it
at the office.

1832
01:25:08,804 --> 01:25:10,706
Is it snowing?
Yeah, it just started.

1833
01:25:10,739 --> 01:25:12,275
Where's your coat
and hat?

1834
01:25:12,308 --> 01:25:14,076
Left them at the office.

1835
01:25:14,109 --> 01:25:15,244
What's the matter?

1836
01:25:15,278 --> 01:25:17,313
Nothing's the matter.
Everything's all right.

1837
01:25:22,218 --> 01:25:23,619
(GROWLING)

1838
01:25:25,521 --> 01:25:27,223
Come on, Pete,
you're a big boy.

1839
01:25:27,256 --> 01:25:28,891
You can help me
get this star up.

1840
01:25:28,924 --> 01:25:32,495
Way up at the top.
There. That's it.

1841
01:25:32,528 --> 01:25:36,031
All right,
fill in that little bare spot
right there. Right there.

1842
01:25:36,064 --> 01:25:37,200
(GRUNTING)

1843
01:25:38,567 --> 01:25:40,636
MARY: Isn't it
wonderful about Harry?

1844
01:25:40,669 --> 01:25:42,104
We're famous, George.

1845
01:25:42,137 --> 01:25:46,008
Bet I had 50 calls today
about the parade,
the banquet.

1846
01:25:46,041 --> 01:25:48,143
Your mother's so excited.
She...

1847
01:25:49,678 --> 01:25:52,315
(JANIE CONTINUES
PLAYING PIANO)

1848
01:26:08,764 --> 01:26:11,300
Must she keep
playing that?

1849
01:26:11,334 --> 01:26:14,203
I have to practice it
for the party tonight,
Daddy.

1850
01:26:14,237 --> 01:26:17,440
Mama said we could
stay up till midnight
and sing Christmas carols.

1851
01:26:17,473 --> 01:26:19,342
Can you sing, Daddy?

1852
01:26:19,375 --> 01:26:20,943
MARY: Better hurry
and shave.

1853
01:26:20,976 --> 01:26:22,645
The families
will be here soon.

1854
01:26:22,678 --> 01:26:23,979
Families.

1855
01:26:24,012 --> 01:26:26,215
I--I don't want
the families over here.

1856
01:26:28,251 --> 01:26:31,354
Come on out
in the kitchen with me
while I finish dinner.

1857
01:26:31,387 --> 01:26:34,790
Excuse me.
Excuse me.

1858
01:26:34,823 --> 01:26:36,792
Have a hectic day?
Oh, yeah.

1859
01:26:36,825 --> 01:26:40,162
Another
big red-letter day
for the Baileys.

1860
01:26:40,195 --> 01:26:43,031
Daddy, the Browns next door
have a new car.
You should see it.

1861
01:26:43,065 --> 01:26:44,267
Well, what's the
matter with our car?

1862
01:26:44,300 --> 01:26:45,601
Isn't it good enough
for you?

1863
01:26:45,634 --> 01:26:46,802
Yes, Daddy.

1864
01:26:46,835 --> 01:26:49,272
Excuse me.
Excuse me.

1865
01:26:49,305 --> 01:26:50,639
Excuse you for what?

1866
01:26:50,673 --> 01:26:52,708
I burped.

1867
01:26:52,741 --> 01:26:54,277
(SIGHING)
All right, darling,
you're excused.

1868
01:26:54,310 --> 01:26:57,480
Now, go on upstairs
and see if little Zuzu
wants anything.

1869
01:26:57,513 --> 01:26:59,615
Zuzu? W-W-What's
the matter with Zuzu?

1870
01:26:59,648 --> 01:27:01,784
Oh, she's just got a cold.
She's in bed.

1871
01:27:01,817 --> 01:27:03,319
Caught it coming
home from school.

1872
01:27:03,352 --> 01:27:05,954
They gave her a flower
for a prize, and she didn't
want to crush it,

1873
01:27:05,988 --> 01:27:07,256
so she didn't
button up her coat.

1874
01:27:07,290 --> 01:27:09,258
What is it,
a sore throat or what?
It's just a cold.

1875
01:27:09,292 --> 01:27:10,826
The doctor says
it's nothing serious.
The doctor?

1876
01:27:10,859 --> 01:27:12,361
Was the doctor here?

1877
01:27:12,395 --> 01:27:13,996
Yes, I called him right away.
He says it's nothing
to worry about.

1878
01:27:14,029 --> 01:27:15,364
Is she running
a temperature?
What is it?

1879
01:27:15,398 --> 01:27:17,600
Just a teensy one, 99.6.
She'll be all right.

1880
01:27:17,633 --> 01:27:19,167
Of course,
it's this old house.

1881
01:27:19,201 --> 01:27:21,470
I don't know why
we don't all
have pneumonia.

1882
01:27:21,504 --> 01:27:22,938
Drafty old barn.

1883
01:27:22,971 --> 01:27:26,008
Might as well be living
in a refrigerator.

1884
01:27:26,041 --> 01:27:27,843
Why did we have
to live here
in the first place

1885
01:27:27,876 --> 01:27:30,746
and stay around this
measly, crummy old town?

1886
01:27:31,847 --> 01:27:33,115
George, what's wrong?

1887
01:27:33,148 --> 01:27:35,651
Wrong! Everything's wrong.
You call this
a happy family?

1888
01:27:35,684 --> 01:27:37,786
Why do we have to have
all these kids?

1889
01:27:37,820 --> 01:27:39,522
PETE: Dad, how do you
spell "frankincense"?

1890
01:27:39,555 --> 01:27:41,557
I don't know.
Ask your mother.

1891
01:27:41,590 --> 01:27:43,392
Where're you going?
I'm going up to see Zuzu.

1892
01:27:43,426 --> 01:27:45,294
He told me to write
a play for tomorrow.

1893
01:27:46,128 --> 01:27:47,930
(PIANO PLAYING CONTINUES)

1894
01:27:56,772 --> 01:28:00,676
F-r-a-n-k-i-n...

1895
01:28:00,709 --> 01:28:02,077
Hi, Daddy!

1896
01:28:03,178 --> 01:28:04,947
Well, what happened
to you?

1897
01:28:04,980 --> 01:28:06,749
I won a flower.

1898
01:28:06,782 --> 01:28:08,584
Wait now.
Where do you think
you're going?

1899
01:28:08,617 --> 01:28:10,285
I want to give
my flower a drink.

1900
01:28:10,319 --> 01:28:12,821
All right, all right.
Now, give Daddy the flower.

1901
01:28:12,855 --> 01:28:13,989
I'll give it a drink.

1902
01:28:14,022 --> 01:28:15,358
Now, here.

1903
01:28:16,859 --> 01:28:19,027
Look, Daddy!

1904
01:28:19,061 --> 01:28:20,529
Paste it!

1905
01:28:20,563 --> 01:28:23,098
Yeah, all right, all right.
Give it here.

1906
01:28:25,534 --> 01:28:28,103
Now, we'll paste
this together here.

1907
01:28:31,306 --> 01:28:34,643
There. There it is.
Good as new.

1908
01:28:34,677 --> 01:28:36,845
Now, give the flower
a drink.

1909
01:28:36,879 --> 01:28:38,347
Now, will you do
something for me?

1910
01:28:38,381 --> 01:28:39,682
(WHISPERING) What?

1911
01:28:39,715 --> 01:28:41,249
(WHISPERING) Will you try
and get some sleep?

1912
01:28:41,283 --> 01:28:42,718
I'm not sleepy.

1913
01:28:42,751 --> 01:28:44,186
I want to look
at my flower.

1914
01:28:44,219 --> 01:28:46,555
I know, I know,
but you just go to sleep

1915
01:28:46,589 --> 01:28:48,924
and then you can
dream about it,

1916
01:28:48,957 --> 01:28:51,159
and it'll be
a whole garden.

1917
01:28:51,193 --> 01:28:52,428
It will?

1918
01:28:52,461 --> 01:28:53,462
Uh-huh.

1919
01:28:59,668 --> 01:29:01,003
(TELEPHONE RINGING)

1920
01:29:01,036 --> 01:29:02,705
KIDS: Telephone!

1921
01:29:02,738 --> 01:29:04,172
I'll get it.

1922
01:29:06,375 --> 01:29:07,576
Hello?

1923
01:29:08,276 --> 01:29:10,546
Yes, this is Mrs. Bailey.

1924
01:29:10,579 --> 01:29:12,415
MARY: Oh, thank you,
Mrs. Welch.

1925
01:29:12,448 --> 01:29:13,749
I'm sure
she'll be all right.

1926
01:29:13,782 --> 01:29:15,217
The doctor said
that she ought to be
out of bed

1927
01:29:15,250 --> 01:29:16,519
in time to have
her Christmas dinner.

1928
01:29:16,552 --> 01:29:18,153
Is that Zuzu's teacher?
Yes.

1929
01:29:18,186 --> 01:29:19,588
Let me speak to her.

1930
01:29:19,622 --> 01:29:22,458
Hello. Hello, Mrs. Welch?

1931
01:29:22,491 --> 01:29:24,960
This is George Bailey.
I'm Zuzu's father.

1932
01:29:24,993 --> 01:29:26,762
Say, what kind of
a teacher are you,
anyway?

1933
01:29:26,795 --> 01:29:29,097
What do you mean
sending her home
like that, half naked?

1934
01:29:29,131 --> 01:29:30,265
Do you realize
she'll probably
end up

1935
01:29:30,298 --> 01:29:31,634
with pneumonia
on account of you?

1936
01:29:31,667 --> 01:29:33,869
George!
Is this the sort of thing
we pay taxes for

1937
01:29:33,902 --> 01:29:36,004
to have teachers...
to have teachers like you?

1938
01:29:36,038 --> 01:29:37,706
Stupid, silly,
careless people

1939
01:29:37,740 --> 01:29:39,374
who send our kids home
without any clothes on?

1940
01:29:39,408 --> 01:29:41,276
You know,
maybe my kids aren't
the best-dressed kids.

1941
01:29:41,309 --> 01:29:43,078
And maybe they don't have
any decent clothes...

1942
01:29:43,111 --> 01:29:45,614
That stupid...

1943
01:29:45,648 --> 01:29:48,584
H-H-Hello, Mrs. Welch.
I want to apologize...

1944
01:29:48,617 --> 01:29:50,753
Hello? Hello.

1945
01:29:52,521 --> 01:29:54,990
She's hung up!
I'll hang her up!

1946
01:29:55,023 --> 01:29:58,260
MAN ON PHONE: Hey, you!
I'll knock your block off!
What is that?

1947
01:29:58,293 --> 01:30:00,162
Hello! Who's this?

1948
01:30:00,195 --> 01:30:02,064
Oh, Mr. Welch?

1949
01:30:02,097 --> 01:30:03,566
Okay, that's fine,
Mr. Welch.

1950
01:30:03,599 --> 01:30:05,868
Give me a chance
to tell you what I really
think of your wife.

1951
01:30:05,901 --> 01:30:08,704
George, stop it.
Will you get out
and let me handle this?

1952
01:30:08,737 --> 01:30:11,273
Hello? Hello? What?

1953
01:30:13,075 --> 01:30:14,710
Oh, you will, huh?

1954
01:30:14,743 --> 01:30:17,746
Okay, Mr. Welch.
Any time you think
you're man enough, you...

1955
01:30:17,780 --> 01:30:19,314
Hello! Any...

1956
01:30:23,418 --> 01:30:24,653
Dad, how do you spell
"hallelujah"?

1957
01:30:24,687 --> 01:30:26,489
How should I know?
What do you think I am,
a dictionary?

1958
01:30:26,522 --> 01:30:27,890
Tommy, stop that!
Stop it!

1959
01:30:27,923 --> 01:30:29,792
Janie,
haven't you learned
that silly tune yet?

1960
01:30:29,825 --> 01:30:32,828
You play it over
and over again.
Now stop it! Stop it!

1961
01:31:00,623 --> 01:31:02,257
I'm sorry, Mary.

1962
01:31:05,528 --> 01:31:07,162
Janie, I'm sorry.

1963
01:31:08,096 --> 01:31:09,932
I didn't mean that. I...

1964
01:31:11,133 --> 01:31:12,668
You go on and practice.

1965
01:31:17,973 --> 01:31:20,175
Pete, I owe you
an apology, too.

1966
01:31:21,443 --> 01:31:22,811
I'm sorry.

1967
01:31:24,312 --> 01:31:25,781
What do you want to know?

1968
01:31:25,814 --> 01:31:27,182
Nothing, Daddy.

1969
01:31:34,122 --> 01:31:35,958
What's the matter
with everybody?

1970
01:31:35,991 --> 01:31:38,661
Janie, go on.
I told you to practice.
Now, go on, play!

1971
01:31:38,694 --> 01:31:40,028
Oh, Daddy!

1972
01:31:41,063 --> 01:31:42,330
(JANIE CRYING)

1973
01:31:45,500 --> 01:31:48,036
George, why must you
torture the children?
Why don't you...

1974
01:31:49,471 --> 01:31:50,706
Mary...

1975
01:32:01,216 --> 01:32:02,685
(DOOR CLOSING)

1976
01:32:05,020 --> 01:32:06,855
Bedford 247, please.

1977
01:32:06,889 --> 01:32:08,891
Is Daddy in trouble?
Yes, Pete.

1978
01:32:08,924 --> 01:32:10,492
Shall I pray for him?

1979
01:32:10,525 --> 01:32:12,194
Yes, Janie,
pray very hard.

1980
01:32:12,227 --> 01:32:14,096
Me, too?
You, too, Tommy.

1981
01:32:15,230 --> 01:32:17,566
Hello? Uncle Billy?

1982
01:32:17,600 --> 01:32:18,601
I'm in trouble, Mr. Potter.

1983
01:32:20,068 --> 01:32:21,336
I need help.

1984
01:32:22,337 --> 01:32:23,772
Through some
sort of an accident,

1985
01:32:23,806 --> 01:32:25,373
my company's short
in their accounts.

1986
01:32:25,407 --> 01:32:27,442
The bank examiner
got there today.

1987
01:32:27,475 --> 01:32:29,645
I've got to raise
$8,000 immediately.

1988
01:32:29,678 --> 01:32:32,180
Oh, that's what
the reporters wanted
to talk to you about?

1989
01:32:32,214 --> 01:32:33,548
The reporters?
Yes.

1990
01:32:33,582 --> 01:32:37,319
They called me up
from your Building and Loan.

1991
01:32:37,352 --> 01:32:40,689
Oh, there's a man over there
from the D.A.'s office, too.

1992
01:32:40,723 --> 01:32:42,124
He's looking for you.

1993
01:32:42,157 --> 01:32:43,859
Please help me,
Mr. Potter.

1994
01:32:43,892 --> 01:32:45,828
Help me,
won't you, please?

1995
01:32:45,861 --> 01:32:47,763
Can't you see
what it means
to my family?

1996
01:32:47,796 --> 01:32:50,599
I'll pay any sort of
a bonus on the loan,
any interest,

1997
01:32:50,633 --> 01:32:52,200
if you still want
the Building and Loan...

1998
01:32:52,234 --> 01:32:54,269
George,
could it possibly be

1999
01:32:54,302 --> 01:32:55,971
there's
a slight discrepancy
in the books?

2000
01:32:56,004 --> 01:32:57,439
No, sir. There's nothing
wrong with the books.

2001
01:32:57,472 --> 01:33:00,609
I've just misplaced $8,000.
I can't find it anywhere.

2002
01:33:00,643 --> 01:33:02,510
You misplaced $8,000?

2003
01:33:03,679 --> 01:33:05,080
Yes, sir.

2004
01:33:07,783 --> 01:33:09,551
Have you notified
the police?

2005
01:33:09,584 --> 01:33:11,386
No, sir.
I didn't want
the publicity.

2006
01:33:11,419 --> 01:33:13,355
Harry's
homecoming tomorrow...

2007
01:33:13,388 --> 01:33:15,523
(CHUCKLING)
They're going to
believe that one.

2008
01:33:15,557 --> 01:33:17,292
What've you been
doing, George?

2009
01:33:17,325 --> 01:33:19,695
Um, playing the market
with the company's money?

2010
01:33:19,728 --> 01:33:20,929
No, sir. No, sir,
I haven't.

2011
01:33:20,963 --> 01:33:22,965
Oh, is it a woman,
then?

2012
01:33:22,998 --> 01:33:24,299
You know,
it's all over town

2013
01:33:24,332 --> 01:33:26,568
that you've been giving
money to Violet Bick.

2014
01:33:26,601 --> 01:33:27,703
What?

2015
01:33:27,736 --> 01:33:29,371
Not that it makes
any difference to me,

2016
01:33:29,404 --> 01:33:30,806
but why did you
come to me?

2017
01:33:30,839 --> 01:33:33,308
Why don't you go
to Sam Wainwright
and ask him for the money?

2018
01:33:33,341 --> 01:33:35,010
I can't get a hold of him.
He's in Europe.

2019
01:33:35,043 --> 01:33:36,511
Well, what about all
your other friends?

2020
01:33:36,544 --> 01:33:38,914
They don't have that
kind of money, Mr. Potter.
You know that.

2021
01:33:38,947 --> 01:33:40,883
You're the only one
in town that can help me.

2022
01:33:40,916 --> 01:33:42,718
(CHUCKLING)

2023
01:33:42,751 --> 01:33:46,288
I've suddenly become
quite important.

2024
01:33:46,321 --> 01:33:49,057
What--what kind of security
would I have, George?

2025
01:33:49,091 --> 01:33:50,525
Have you got any stocks?

2026
01:33:51,259 --> 01:33:52,494
No, sir.

2027
01:33:52,527 --> 01:33:55,864
Bonds? Real estate?
Collateral of any kind?

2028
01:33:55,898 --> 01:33:59,968
I have some life insurance,
a $15,000 policy.

2029
01:34:00,002 --> 01:34:02,370
Yes. How much
is your equity in it?

2030
01:34:02,404 --> 01:34:04,006
Five hundred dollars.

2031
01:34:04,039 --> 01:34:06,208
Five hundred dollars?

2032
01:34:06,241 --> 01:34:08,877
And you ask me
to lend you $8,000?

2033
01:34:10,412 --> 01:34:13,849
Look at you.
You used to be so cocky.

2034
01:34:13,882 --> 01:34:17,485
You were going to go out
and conquer the world.

2035
01:34:17,519 --> 01:34:22,958
You once called me a warped,
frustrated old man.

2036
01:34:22,991 --> 01:34:26,795
What are you but a warped,
frustrated young man?

2037
01:34:26,829 --> 01:34:28,463
A miserable little clerk,

2038
01:34:28,496 --> 01:34:30,232
crawling in here
on your hands and knees

2039
01:34:30,265 --> 01:34:32,367
and begging for help.

2040
01:34:32,400 --> 01:34:34,302
No securities,
no stocks, no bonds.

2041
01:34:34,336 --> 01:34:38,040
Nothing but a miserable
little $500 equity

2042
01:34:38,073 --> 01:34:39,674
in a life insurance policy.

2043
01:34:39,708 --> 01:34:41,043
(CHUCKLING)

2044
01:34:41,076 --> 01:34:44,046
You're worth more
dead than alive.

2045
01:34:44,079 --> 01:34:47,015
Why don't you go
to the riffraff
you love so much

2046
01:34:47,049 --> 01:34:49,584
and ask them
to let you have $8,000?

2047
01:34:50,085 --> 01:34:51,353
You know why?

2048
01:34:51,386 --> 01:34:54,156
Because they'd run you
out of town on a rail.

2049
01:34:54,189 --> 01:34:57,492
But I tell you
what I'm going to do
for you, George.

2050
01:34:57,525 --> 01:35:00,763
Since the state examiner
is still here,

2051
01:35:00,796 --> 01:35:03,365
as a stockholder
of the Building and Loan,

2052
01:35:03,398 --> 01:35:06,634
I'm going to swear out
a warrant for your arrest.

2053
01:35:06,668 --> 01:35:10,739
Misappropriation of funds,
manipulation, malfeasance.

2054
01:35:12,307 --> 01:35:14,709
All right, George,
go ahead.

2055
01:35:14,743 --> 01:35:17,913
You can't hide
in a little town
like this.

2056
01:35:17,946 --> 01:35:20,015
Yeah, Bill?
This is Potter.

2057
01:35:33,495 --> 01:35:37,665
MARTINI: Ah! Merry Christmas!
Glad you come!

2058
01:35:37,699 --> 01:35:39,267
MAN: How about some of
that good spaghetti?

2059
01:35:39,301 --> 01:35:41,003
We got everything.

2060
01:35:42,404 --> 01:35:45,240
(ITALIAN MUSIC PLAYING)

2061
01:35:52,347 --> 01:35:53,615
Oh, God.

2062
01:35:56,819 --> 01:35:58,086
Oh, God.

2063
01:36:03,191 --> 01:36:05,060
Dear Father in Heaven,

2064
01:36:08,196 --> 01:36:10,132
I'm not a praying man,

2065
01:36:11,299 --> 01:36:14,236
but if you're up there
and you can hear me,

2066
01:36:15,871 --> 01:36:17,906
show me the way.

2067
01:36:17,940 --> 01:36:20,275
I'm at the end
of my rope. I...

2068
01:36:22,177 --> 01:36:24,179
Show me the way, O God.

2069
01:36:29,051 --> 01:36:30,752
Are you all right, George?

2070
01:36:30,785 --> 01:36:32,554
Want somebody
to take you home, huh?

2071
01:36:35,457 --> 01:36:37,926
Why you drink so much,
my friend?

2072
01:36:37,960 --> 01:36:39,727
Please go home, Mr. Bailey.

2073
01:36:39,761 --> 01:36:41,796
This is Christmas Eve.

2074
01:36:41,830 --> 01:36:44,867
Bailey?
Which Bailey?

2075
01:36:44,900 --> 01:36:46,734
This is
Mr. George Bailey.

2076
01:36:49,104 --> 01:36:51,106
(WOMEN SCREAMING)

2077
01:36:51,139 --> 01:36:54,142
MR. WELCH: The next time
you talk to my wife
like that, you'll get worse!

2078
01:36:54,176 --> 01:36:55,477
She cried for an hour!

2079
01:36:55,510 --> 01:36:57,312
It isn't enough
she slaves teaching

2080
01:36:57,345 --> 01:36:58,813
your stupid kids
how to read and write,

2081
01:36:58,847 --> 01:37:00,048
and you have
to bawl her out.

2082
01:37:00,082 --> 01:37:01,349
You get out of here,
Mr. Welch!

2083
01:37:01,383 --> 01:37:02,918
Now, wait,
I want to pay
for my drink.

2084
01:37:02,951 --> 01:37:04,652
Never mind the money!
You get out of here quick!

2085
01:37:04,686 --> 01:37:05,854
All right!

2086
01:37:05,888 --> 01:37:07,455
You hit my best friend!
Get out!

2087
01:37:12,995 --> 01:37:14,629
You all right, George?

2088
01:37:14,662 --> 01:37:15,998
Who was that?

2089
01:37:16,031 --> 01:37:19,234
He gone. No worry.
He name is Welch.

2090
01:37:19,267 --> 01:37:20,702
He no come into
my place no more.

2091
01:37:20,735 --> 01:37:22,137
Oh, Welch.

2092
01:37:22,170 --> 01:37:24,139
That's what I get
for praying.

2093
01:37:24,172 --> 01:37:26,274
The last time
he come in here.
You hear that, Nick?

2094
01:37:26,308 --> 01:37:29,111
Yes, you bet.
Where's my insurance policy?

2095
01:37:29,811 --> 01:37:31,046
Oh, here it is.

2096
01:37:31,079 --> 01:37:32,714
Oh, no, please,
don't go this way,
Mr. Bailey.

2097
01:37:32,747 --> 01:37:34,316
I'm all right.
No, no, you no feel
so good.

2098
01:37:34,349 --> 01:37:35,884
Sit down and rest.
I'm all right.

2099
01:37:35,918 --> 01:37:37,619
Please no go away,
please!

2100
01:37:39,721 --> 01:37:41,156
(TIRES SCREECHING)

2101
01:37:56,604 --> 01:37:58,240
What do you think
you're doing?

2102
01:38:01,009 --> 01:38:02,410
Now look what you did.

2103
01:38:02,444 --> 01:38:04,746
My great-grandfather
planted this tree!

2104
01:38:05,680 --> 01:38:08,383
Hey, you! Hey, you!

2105
01:38:08,416 --> 01:38:10,318
Come back here,
you drunken fool!

2106
01:38:10,352 --> 01:38:12,154
Get this car out of here!

2107
01:38:12,921 --> 01:38:14,856
(VEHICLE APPROACHING)

2108
01:38:18,260 --> 01:38:19,794
(HORN HONKING)

2109
01:38:19,827 --> 01:38:21,396
MAN: Hey,
what's the matter
with you?

2110
01:38:21,429 --> 01:38:23,165
Look where you're going.

2111
01:39:10,545 --> 01:39:11,679
CLARENCE: Help!

2112
01:39:13,248 --> 01:39:16,051
Help! Help!

2113
01:39:16,084 --> 01:39:17,352
(CLARENCE SCREAMING)

2114
01:39:19,587 --> 01:39:21,423
Help! Help!

2115
01:39:23,858 --> 01:39:25,493
Help!

2116
01:39:28,563 --> 01:39:31,966
Help! Help! Help! Help!

2117
01:39:34,769 --> 01:39:36,271
(CLARENCE SCREAMING)

2118
01:39:38,506 --> 01:39:41,209
Help! Help!

2119
01:39:57,659 --> 01:40:00,195
I didn't have time
to get some
stylish underwear.

2120
01:40:00,228 --> 01:40:02,330
Wife gave me this
on my last birthday.

2121
01:40:03,598 --> 01:40:05,367
I passed away in it.

2122
01:40:08,870 --> 01:40:11,773
Oh, Tom Sawyer's
drying out, too.

2123
01:40:14,976 --> 01:40:17,312
You should read the new book
Mark Twain's writing now.

2124
01:40:19,081 --> 01:40:20,948
How did you
happen to fall in?

2125
01:40:20,982 --> 01:40:22,517
I didn't fall in.

2126
01:40:22,550 --> 01:40:24,386
I jumped in
to save George.

2127
01:40:24,419 --> 01:40:27,555
You what? To save me?

2128
01:40:27,589 --> 01:40:29,091
Well, I did,
didn't I?

2129
01:40:29,124 --> 01:40:30,758
You didn't go
through with it,
did you?

2130
01:40:30,792 --> 01:40:32,960
Go through with what?
Suicide.

2131
01:40:32,994 --> 01:40:36,098
It's against the law to
commit suicide around here.

2132
01:40:36,131 --> 01:40:38,733
Yeah, it's against the law
where I come from, too.

2133
01:40:38,766 --> 01:40:40,635
Where do you come from?

2134
01:40:40,668 --> 01:40:41,803
Heaven.

2135
01:40:46,474 --> 01:40:47,875
I had to act quickly.

2136
01:40:47,909 --> 01:40:49,611
That's why I jumped in.

2137
01:40:49,644 --> 01:40:52,114
I knew if I were drowning,
you'd try to save me.

2138
01:40:52,147 --> 01:40:55,083
You see, you did,
and that's how I saved you.

2139
01:40:55,750 --> 01:40:57,452
Very funny.

2140
01:40:57,485 --> 01:40:59,521
Your lip's bleeding,
George.

2141
01:40:59,554 --> 01:41:01,889
Yeah, I got a bust
in the jaw

2142
01:41:01,923 --> 01:41:03,791
in answer to a prayer
a little bit ago.

2143
01:41:03,825 --> 01:41:05,727
Oh, no, no, no,
George,

2144
01:41:05,760 --> 01:41:07,629
I'm the answer
to your prayer.

2145
01:41:07,662 --> 01:41:09,631
That's why I was sent
down here.

2146
01:41:10,598 --> 01:41:12,033
How'd you know
my name?

2147
01:41:12,066 --> 01:41:13,868
Oh, I know
all about you.

2148
01:41:13,901 --> 01:41:15,670
I've watched you grow up
from a little boy.

2149
01:41:15,703 --> 01:41:17,205
What are you,
a mind reader
or something?

2150
01:41:17,239 --> 01:41:18,473
(CHUCKLING) No.

2151
01:41:18,506 --> 01:41:20,175
Well, who are you then?

2152
01:41:20,208 --> 01:41:22,444
Clarence Oddbody, AS2.

2153
01:41:23,178 --> 01:41:24,479
Oddbody?

2154
01:41:25,480 --> 01:41:27,815
(STAMMERING)
AS2? What's that, AS2?

2155
01:41:27,849 --> 01:41:29,217
Angel Second Class.

2156
01:41:40,162 --> 01:41:41,596
Cheerio, my good man.

2157
01:41:45,900 --> 01:41:47,235
Oh, brother.

2158
01:41:49,737 --> 01:41:51,005
Gee whiz.

2159
01:41:52,073 --> 01:41:54,309
I wonder what Martini
put in those drinks.

2160
01:41:56,911 --> 01:41:59,281
Hey, what's with you?

2161
01:41:59,314 --> 01:42:01,716
W-W-What did you say
just a minute ago?

2162
01:42:01,749 --> 01:42:03,385
Why'd you want
to save me?

2163
01:42:03,418 --> 01:42:05,187
That's what
I was sent down for.

2164
01:42:05,220 --> 01:42:07,389
I'm your guardian angel.

2165
01:42:07,422 --> 01:42:09,624
I wouldn't be
a bit surprised.

2166
01:42:09,657 --> 01:42:13,961
Ridiculous of you
to think of killing yourself
for money, $8,000.

2167
01:42:13,995 --> 01:42:15,563
Yeah, now,
just things like that...

2168
01:42:15,597 --> 01:42:17,199
How do you know that?

2169
01:42:17,232 --> 01:42:19,167
I told you.
I'm your guardian angel.

2170
01:42:19,201 --> 01:42:22,170
I know everything
about you.

2171
01:42:22,204 --> 01:42:25,473
Well, you look
about like the kind
of an angel I'd get.

2172
01:42:25,507 --> 01:42:27,242
Sort of a fallen angel,
aren't you?

2173
01:42:27,275 --> 01:42:28,443
What happened
to your wings?

2174
01:42:28,476 --> 01:42:29,811
I haven't won my wings yet.

2175
01:42:29,844 --> 01:42:31,813
That's why I'm
an Angel Second Class.

2176
01:42:36,884 --> 01:42:38,353
I don't know whether
I'd like it very much

2177
01:42:38,386 --> 01:42:40,388
being seen around
with an angel
without any wings.

2178
01:42:40,422 --> 01:42:42,857
Oh, I've got to earn them,

2179
01:42:42,890 --> 01:42:44,158
and you'll help me,
won't you?

2180
01:42:44,192 --> 01:42:45,793
Sure, sure.

2181
01:42:45,827 --> 01:42:46,961
How?

2182
01:42:46,994 --> 01:42:48,930
By letting me help you.

2183
01:42:48,963 --> 01:42:51,699
Yes. Only one way
you can help me.

2184
01:42:51,733 --> 01:42:53,935
You--you don't happen
to have 8,000 bucks
on you, do you?

2185
01:42:53,968 --> 01:42:56,371
Oh, no. No.
We don't use money
in heaven.

2186
01:42:56,404 --> 01:42:59,641
Oh, yeah, that's right,
I keep forgetting.

2187
01:42:59,674 --> 01:43:01,576
Comes in pretty handy
down here, bub.

2188
01:43:01,609 --> 01:43:03,211
Oh, tut, tut, tut.

2189
01:43:04,346 --> 01:43:06,080
I found it out
a little late.

2190
01:43:07,014 --> 01:43:08,983
I'm worth more
dead than alive.

2191
01:43:09,016 --> 01:43:10,852
Now, look, you mustn't
talk like that.

2192
01:43:10,885 --> 01:43:13,321
I won't get my wings
with that attitude.

2193
01:43:13,355 --> 01:43:15,790
You just don't know
all that you've done.

2194
01:43:15,823 --> 01:43:17,124
If it hadn't been
for you...

2195
01:43:17,158 --> 01:43:18,426
Yeah, if it hadn't
been for me,

2196
01:43:18,460 --> 01:43:19,861
everybody'd be
a lot better off.

2197
01:43:19,894 --> 01:43:22,096
My wife and my kids
and my friends.

2198
01:43:22,129 --> 01:43:23,398
I mean, look,
little fellow,

2199
01:43:23,431 --> 01:43:25,467
go off and haunt
somebody else, will you?

2200
01:43:25,500 --> 01:43:27,235
No, now,
you don't understand.

2201
01:43:27,269 --> 01:43:29,437
I've got my job...
Oh, shut up, will you?

2202
01:43:34,041 --> 01:43:36,744
Oh, this isn't gonna
be so easy.

2203
01:43:41,516 --> 01:43:44,151
Yeah, so you still think
killing yourself

2204
01:43:44,185 --> 01:43:46,354
would make everyone
feel happier, eh?

2205
01:43:47,922 --> 01:43:50,091
Well, I don't know.
I guess you're right.

2206
01:43:51,926 --> 01:43:53,094
I suppose it would
have been better

2207
01:43:53,127 --> 01:43:54,696
if I'd never been
born at all.

2208
01:43:54,729 --> 01:43:56,097
What'd you say?

2209
01:43:56,130 --> 01:43:58,466
I said I wish
I'd never been born.

2210
01:43:58,500 --> 01:44:01,436
Oh, you mustn't say
things like that.

2211
01:44:01,469 --> 01:44:04,706
You...
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

2212
01:44:04,739 --> 01:44:06,240
That's an idea.

2213
01:44:07,074 --> 01:44:08,476
What do you think?

2214
01:44:09,344 --> 01:44:10,778
Yeah, that'll do it.

2215
01:44:11,746 --> 01:44:13,080
All right.

2216
01:44:15,817 --> 01:44:17,719
You've got your wish.

2217
01:44:17,752 --> 01:44:19,554
You've never been born.

2218
01:44:19,587 --> 01:44:20,755
(WIND BLOWING)

2219
01:44:24,559 --> 01:44:26,894
You don't have
to make all that fuss
about it!

2220
01:44:28,630 --> 01:44:30,064
What did you say?

2221
01:44:30,097 --> 01:44:32,266
You've never been born.
You don't exist.

2222
01:44:32,300 --> 01:44:33,901
You haven't a care
in the world.

2223
01:44:33,935 --> 01:44:37,372
No worries, no obligations,
no $8,000 to get,

2224
01:44:37,405 --> 01:44:39,240
no Potter looking for you
with the Sheriff.

2225
01:44:39,273 --> 01:44:40,475
Say something else
in that ear.

2226
01:44:40,508 --> 01:44:42,744
Sure, you can hear
out of it.

2227
01:44:42,777 --> 01:44:44,979
Well, that's
the doggonedest thing.

2228
01:44:45,012 --> 01:44:47,615
I haven't heard anything
out of that ear
since I was a kid.

2229
01:44:47,649 --> 01:44:49,851
Must have been that jump
in that cold water.

2230
01:44:49,884 --> 01:44:52,119
Your lip stopped bleeding,
too, George.

2231
01:44:57,425 --> 01:44:59,293
What do you know
about that?

2232
01:45:00,127 --> 01:45:01,496
What's happening?

2233
01:45:02,564 --> 01:45:04,832
It stopped snowing
out here, didn't it?

2234
01:45:04,866 --> 01:45:07,435
Well, I...
What's happened here?

2235
01:45:07,469 --> 01:45:09,337
What I need is a couple
of good stiff drinks.

2236
01:45:09,371 --> 01:45:11,205
How about you, Angel?
You want a drink?

2237
01:45:11,238 --> 01:45:13,074
(LAUGHING)

2238
01:45:13,107 --> 01:45:15,477
Come on, soon as these
clothes of ours are dry...

2239
01:45:15,510 --> 01:45:17,579
The clothes are dry.

2240
01:45:17,612 --> 01:45:19,280
What do you know
about that?

2241
01:45:19,313 --> 01:45:20,748
Stove's hotter
than I thought.

2242
01:45:20,782 --> 01:45:22,183
Now, come on,
get your clothes on.

2243
01:45:22,216 --> 01:45:24,018
We'll stroll up
to my car and get...

2244
01:45:24,051 --> 01:45:27,221
Oh. Oh, I'm sorry.
I'll stroll. You fly.

2245
01:45:27,254 --> 01:45:28,923
I can't fly.
I haven't got
my wings.

2246
01:45:28,956 --> 01:45:30,658
You haven't got your wings.
Yeah, that's right.

2247
01:45:31,158 --> 01:45:32,660
(WIND WHISTLING)

2248
01:45:37,331 --> 01:45:38,633
What's the matter?

2249
01:45:38,666 --> 01:45:41,436
Well, this is where
I left my car,
and it isn't here.

2250
01:45:41,469 --> 01:45:42,770
You have no car.

2251
01:45:42,804 --> 01:45:44,972
Well, I had a car,
and it was right here.

2252
01:45:45,006 --> 01:45:47,375
I guess somebody
moved it.
Good evening.

2253
01:45:47,409 --> 01:45:50,945
Oh, say, hey,
w-where's my car?

2254
01:45:50,978 --> 01:45:52,980
I beg your pardon?
My car, my car.

2255
01:45:53,014 --> 01:45:55,450
GEORGE: I'm the fellow
that owns the car
that ran into your tree.

2256
01:45:55,483 --> 01:45:57,485
MAN: What tree?
What do you mean,
what tree?

2257
01:45:57,519 --> 01:45:59,721
This tree.
Here, I ran into it.

2258
01:45:59,754 --> 01:46:02,990
Cut a big gash
in the side of it there.

2259
01:46:07,261 --> 01:46:08,930
You must mean
two other trees.

2260
01:46:09,597 --> 01:46:10,898
You had me worried.

2261
01:46:10,932 --> 01:46:13,134
One of the oldest
trees in Pottersville.

2262
01:46:13,167 --> 01:46:14,368
Pottersville?

2263
01:46:14,402 --> 01:46:15,970
Why, you mean Bedford Falls.

2264
01:46:16,003 --> 01:46:17,805
I mean Pottersville.

2265
01:46:17,839 --> 01:46:19,807
Don't you think
I know where I live?

2266
01:46:19,841 --> 01:46:22,009
What's the matter
with you?

2267
01:46:22,043 --> 01:46:24,812
What's the matter with me?
Well, I guess I just...

2268
01:46:27,782 --> 01:46:31,986
Oh, I don't know.
Either I'm off my nut
or he is or you are.

2269
01:46:33,020 --> 01:46:34,556
It isn't me.

2270
01:46:34,589 --> 01:46:36,591
Well, maybe I left the car
up at Martini's.

2271
01:46:36,624 --> 01:46:38,926
Well, come on, Gabriel.
Clarence.

2272
01:46:38,960 --> 01:46:40,327
Clarence. Clarence.

2273
01:46:46,300 --> 01:46:47,469
That's all right.
Go on in.

2274
01:46:47,502 --> 01:46:49,370
Martini is
a friend of mine.

2275
01:46:50,505 --> 01:46:52,674
There's a place
to sit down. Sit down.

2276
01:46:59,481 --> 01:47:01,849
Oh, hello, Nick.
Hey, where's Martini?

2277
01:47:01,883 --> 01:47:03,150
Want a martini?

2278
01:47:03,184 --> 01:47:05,152
No, no, Martini.
Your boss.
Where is he?

2279
01:47:05,186 --> 01:47:06,454
Hey, look,
I'm the boss.

2280
01:47:06,488 --> 01:47:07,722
You want a drink
or don't you?

2281
01:47:07,755 --> 01:47:10,024
Okay, all right.
Double bourbon,
will you, and quick, huh?

2282
01:47:10,057 --> 01:47:11,292
Okay.

2283
01:47:14,462 --> 01:47:15,930
What's yours?

2284
01:47:15,963 --> 01:47:17,431
I was just thinking.

2285
01:47:18,700 --> 01:47:21,102
(CHUCKLING)
It's been so long
since I...

2286
01:47:21,135 --> 01:47:23,137
Look, mister,
I'm standing here

2287
01:47:23,170 --> 01:47:24,839
waiting for you
to make up your mind.

2288
01:47:24,872 --> 01:47:26,541
That's a good man.

2289
01:47:26,574 --> 01:47:28,743
I was just thinking

2290
01:47:29,611 --> 01:47:33,114
of a flaming rum punch.

2291
01:47:33,147 --> 01:47:35,717
No, it's not cold
enough for that,
not nearly cold enough.

2292
01:47:35,750 --> 01:47:38,753
Wait a minute.
Wait a minute.
I got it.

2293
01:47:38,786 --> 01:47:42,456
Mulled wine,
heavy on the cinnamon
and light on the cloves.

2294
01:47:42,490 --> 01:47:44,458
Off with you, me lad,
and be lively!

2295
01:47:44,492 --> 01:47:47,729
Hey, look, mister,
we serve hard drinks
in here

2296
01:47:47,762 --> 01:47:49,430
for men who want
to get drunk fast.

2297
01:47:49,463 --> 01:47:51,566
And we don't need
any characters around

2298
01:47:51,599 --> 01:47:53,067
to give the joint
atmosphere.

2299
01:47:53,100 --> 01:47:54,335
NICK: Is that clear,

2300
01:47:54,368 --> 01:47:56,771
or do I have to slip you
my left for a convincer?

2301
01:47:56,804 --> 01:47:58,239
What's he talking about?

2302
01:47:58,272 --> 01:48:00,241
Nick, Nick,

2303
01:48:00,274 --> 01:48:03,310
just give him
the same as mine.
He's okay.

2304
01:48:03,645 --> 01:48:04,946
Okay.

2305
01:48:06,213 --> 01:48:07,582
What's the matter
with him?

2306
01:48:07,615 --> 01:48:09,784
I never saw Nick
act like that before.

2307
01:48:09,817 --> 01:48:12,386
You'll see
a lot of strange things
from now on.

2308
01:48:13,087 --> 01:48:14,856
Oh, yeah.

2309
01:48:16,057 --> 01:48:19,093
Hey, little fellow,

2310
01:48:20,194 --> 01:48:21,563
you worry me, you know.

2311
01:48:21,596 --> 01:48:23,865
You--you got someplace
to sleep?

2312
01:48:23,898 --> 01:48:26,367
No.
You don't, huh?

2313
01:48:26,400 --> 01:48:28,069
Well, you--you got
any money?

2314
01:48:28,102 --> 01:48:30,104
No.

2315
01:48:30,137 --> 01:48:31,706
No wonder you jumped
in the river.

2316
01:48:31,739 --> 01:48:35,810
I jumped in the river
to save you
so I could get my wings.

2317
01:48:35,843 --> 01:48:37,144
(CASH REGISTER RINGS)
Oh-oh.

2318
01:48:39,313 --> 01:48:41,482
Somebody's just made it.
Made what?

2319
01:48:41,515 --> 01:48:43,585
Every time you hear
a bell ring, it means

2320
01:48:43,618 --> 01:48:45,953
that some angel's
just got his wings.

2321
01:48:51,358 --> 01:48:52,359
Look, uh,

2322
01:48:54,095 --> 01:48:56,898
I think maybe
you better not mention

2323
01:48:56,931 --> 01:48:58,432
getting your wings
around here.

2324
01:48:58,465 --> 01:49:00,534
Why? Don't they believe
in angels?

2325
01:49:01,268 --> 01:49:02,503
I...

2326
01:49:03,437 --> 01:49:05,272
Yeah, they believe
in them.

2327
01:49:05,306 --> 01:49:07,875
Oh, why should
they be surprised
when they see one?

2328
01:49:10,411 --> 01:49:14,115
Oh, he never
grew up. He's...

2329
01:49:14,148 --> 01:49:16,117
How old are you
anyway, Clarence?

2330
01:49:16,150 --> 01:49:19,621
Two hundred
and ninety-three, uh,

2331
01:49:20,287 --> 01:49:22,123
next May.

2332
01:49:22,156 --> 01:49:24,826
That does it.
Out, you two pixies!

2333
01:49:24,859 --> 01:49:26,894
Go through the door
or out the window.

2334
01:49:26,928 --> 01:49:28,495
Look, Nick,
what's wrong?

2335
01:49:28,529 --> 01:49:31,098
Now, that's another thing.
Where do you come off
calling me Nick?

2336
01:49:31,132 --> 01:49:32,667
GEORGE: Well, Nick,
that's your name.

2337
01:49:32,700 --> 01:49:34,235
NICK: What's that
got to do with it?

2338
01:49:34,268 --> 01:49:36,971
I don't know you
from Adam's off ox.

2339
01:49:37,004 --> 01:49:39,540
Hey. Hey, you rummy, there.
Come here, come here.

2340
01:49:43,310 --> 01:49:46,480
Didn't I tell you
never to come panhandling
around here, huh?

2341
01:49:48,515 --> 01:49:49,851
(ALL LAUGH)

2342
01:49:54,055 --> 01:49:55,422
Mr. Gower.

2343
01:49:56,590 --> 01:49:57,925
Mr. Gower.

2344
01:49:59,627 --> 01:50:01,629
What... What did...

2345
01:50:01,663 --> 01:50:04,098
Mr. Gower, look,
this is George Bailey.

2346
01:50:05,499 --> 01:50:06,734
Don't you know me?

2347
01:50:06,768 --> 01:50:07,935
No.

2348
01:50:09,203 --> 01:50:10,471
No.

2349
01:50:10,504 --> 01:50:11,906
NICK: Throw him out.
Throw him out.

2350
01:50:11,939 --> 01:50:15,076
Mr. Gower! Hey, what is...

2351
01:50:15,109 --> 01:50:17,544
Hey, Nick. Nick.
Isn't that Mr. Gower,
the druggist?

2352
01:50:17,578 --> 01:50:19,747
You know,
that's another reason
for me not to like you.

2353
01:50:19,781 --> 01:50:23,284
That rum head
spent 20 years in jail
for poisoning a kid.

2354
01:50:23,317 --> 01:50:25,753
If you know him,
you must be
a jailbird yourself.

2355
01:50:25,787 --> 01:50:28,389
Uh, would you show
these gentlemen
to the door?

2356
01:50:28,422 --> 01:50:30,457
Sure. This way,
gentlemen.

2357
01:50:32,760 --> 01:50:34,161
(PEOPLE LAUGHING)

2358
01:50:35,863 --> 01:50:37,164
Stay out.

2359
01:50:38,399 --> 01:50:41,035
Get me! I'm giving out wings!

2360
01:50:41,068 --> 01:50:42,469
(ALL LAUGHING)

2361
01:50:43,671 --> 01:50:46,140
You see, George,
you were not there
to stop Gower

2362
01:50:46,173 --> 01:50:47,975
from putting that poison
into the capsules.

2363
01:50:48,009 --> 01:50:49,143
What do you mean,
I wasn't there?

2364
01:50:49,176 --> 01:50:50,945
I remember distinctly...

2365
01:50:53,815 --> 01:50:56,483
Hey, what's going on
around here?

2366
01:50:56,517 --> 01:50:58,986
What... What...

2367
01:50:59,020 --> 01:51:01,155
Why, this ought to
be Martini's place.

2368
01:51:07,661 --> 01:51:09,496
Look, who are you?

2369
01:51:09,530 --> 01:51:12,133
I told you, George.
I'm your guardian angel.

2370
01:51:12,166 --> 01:51:14,068
Yeah, yeah, I know.
You told me that.

2371
01:51:20,041 --> 01:51:23,244
What else are you?
What, are you--you
a hypnotist?

2372
01:51:23,277 --> 01:51:24,645
No. Of course not.

2373
01:51:24,678 --> 01:51:27,248
Well, then,
why am I seeing all these
strange things here?

2374
01:51:27,281 --> 01:51:29,516
Don't you understand,
George?

2375
01:51:29,550 --> 01:51:31,719
It's because
you were not born.

2376
01:51:31,753 --> 01:51:33,554
Well, if I wasn't born,
who am I?

2377
01:51:33,587 --> 01:51:36,157
You're nobody.
You have no identity.

2378
01:51:36,190 --> 01:51:38,793
What do you mean,
no identity?
My name's George Bailey.

2379
01:51:38,826 --> 01:51:40,895
There is no George Bailey.

2380
01:51:42,096 --> 01:51:46,834
You have no papers, no cards,
no driver's license,

2381
01:51:46,868 --> 01:51:49,603
no 4-F card,
no insurance policy.

2382
01:51:50,637 --> 01:51:52,273
They're not there, either.

2383
01:51:53,640 --> 01:51:54,842
What?

2384
01:51:54,876 --> 01:51:56,177
Zuzu's petals.

2385
01:52:01,715 --> 01:52:04,551
You've been given
a great gift, George,

2386
01:52:04,585 --> 01:52:07,755
a chance to see
what the world
would be like without you.

2387
01:52:10,424 --> 01:52:13,060
Now, wait a minute here.
Wait a minute here.

2388
01:52:15,062 --> 01:52:18,399
This is some sort of
a funny dream I'm having.

2389
01:52:18,432 --> 01:52:20,301
So long, mister.
I--I'm going home.

2390
01:52:20,334 --> 01:52:21,535
Home? What home?

2391
01:52:21,568 --> 01:52:23,170
Oh, shut up! Cut it out!

2392
01:52:23,805 --> 01:52:25,739
(STUTTERING) You're crazy!

2393
01:52:25,773 --> 01:52:28,209
That's what I think.
You're-- you're screwy.

2394
01:52:28,242 --> 01:52:29,643
You're driving me
crazy, too.

2395
01:52:29,676 --> 01:52:30,945
I'm seeing things here.

2396
01:52:30,978 --> 01:52:32,914
I'm going home
and see my wife
and family.

2397
01:52:32,947 --> 01:52:35,149
You understand that?
And I'm going home
alone.

2398
01:52:38,552 --> 01:52:40,454
How am I doing,
Joseph?

2399
01:52:41,155 --> 01:52:42,689
Thanks.

2400
01:52:42,723 --> 01:52:44,458
No, I didn't have a drink.

2401
01:52:47,494 --> 01:52:50,297
(JAZZ PLAYING)

2402
01:52:50,932 --> 01:52:53,300
(POLICE SIREN WAILING)

2403
01:53:01,575 --> 01:53:03,244
(CROWDS CHEERING)

2404
01:53:24,866 --> 01:53:27,168
(PEOPLE SHOUTING)

2405
01:53:35,977 --> 01:53:38,645
Hey, hey,
where did the Building
and Loan move to?

2406
01:53:38,679 --> 01:53:40,647
Building and what?
The Bailey
Building and Loan.

2407
01:53:40,681 --> 01:53:43,450
It was up there.
They went out of
business years ago.

2408
01:53:43,484 --> 01:53:44,919
That sailor's a liar!

2409
01:53:44,952 --> 01:53:47,288
I know every big
shot in this town!

2410
01:53:47,321 --> 01:53:49,924
I know Potter,
and I'll have
you kicked off the beat.

2411
01:53:49,957 --> 01:53:51,425
Hey, Violet!

2412
01:53:52,626 --> 01:53:55,262
Hey, hey! Listen.
That's Violet Bick.

2413
01:53:55,296 --> 01:53:57,464
I know.
I know that girl!

2414
01:53:57,498 --> 01:53:59,300
Take a walk. Beat it.

2415
01:54:01,368 --> 01:54:02,904
GEORGE: Hey, Ernie!
Ernie.

2416
01:54:05,306 --> 01:54:07,408
Ernie, take me home.
I'm going off my nut.

2417
01:54:07,441 --> 01:54:09,110
Where do you live?
Now, doggone it, Ernie,

2418
01:54:09,143 --> 01:54:10,444
don't you start
pulling that stuff.

2419
01:54:10,477 --> 01:54:13,047
You know where I live.
320 Sycamore.
Now hurry up.

2420
01:54:13,080 --> 01:54:14,982
All right. 320 Sycamore?

2421
01:54:15,016 --> 01:54:16,717
Yeah, yeah, hurry up.
Zuzu's sick.

2422
01:54:16,750 --> 01:54:19,020
Come on.
All right. All right.

2423
01:54:19,053 --> 01:54:21,155
Come on, Ernie,
now straighten me
out here.

2424
01:54:21,188 --> 01:54:23,991
Look,
I've got some bad liquor
or something. Listen to me.

2425
01:54:24,025 --> 01:54:27,261
Now, you are Ernie Bishop,
and you live in Bailey Park
with your wife and kid?

2426
01:54:27,294 --> 01:54:29,496
That's right, isn't it?
You seen my wife?

2427
01:54:29,530 --> 01:54:32,833
Seen your wife?
I've been to your house
100 times.

2428
01:54:32,866 --> 01:54:35,769
Look, bud, what's the idea?
I live in a shack
in Potter's Field,

2429
01:54:35,802 --> 01:54:37,871
my wife ran away
three years ago
and took the kid,

2430
01:54:37,905 --> 01:54:40,507
and I ain't never seen you
before in my life, see?

2431
01:54:40,541 --> 01:54:42,809
Okay, well, just step on it.
Just get me home!

2432
01:55:01,062 --> 01:55:03,064
Is this the place?
Of course it's the place.

2433
01:55:03,097 --> 01:55:05,832
Well, this house
ain't been lived in
for 20 years.

2434
01:55:12,473 --> 01:55:14,108
What's up, Ernie?
I don't know.

2435
01:55:14,141 --> 01:55:16,643
But we better keep
our eye on this guy.
He's bats.

2436
01:55:35,196 --> 01:55:37,398
Mary. Mary!

2437
01:55:40,434 --> 01:55:43,637
Tommy! Pete! Janie! Zuzu!
Where are you?

2438
01:55:43,670 --> 01:55:46,373
They're not here, George.
You have no children.

2439
01:55:46,407 --> 01:55:47,808
Where are they?
What have you done
with them?

2440
01:55:47,841 --> 01:55:50,111
BERT: All right,
put up your hands.
No fast moves.

2441
01:55:50,144 --> 01:55:51,712
Come on out here,
both of you.

2442
01:55:51,745 --> 01:55:53,214
Bert! Thank heaven
you're here.

2443
01:55:53,247 --> 01:55:56,083
Back this.
Bert, what's happened
to this house?

2444
01:55:56,117 --> 01:55:57,584
Where--where's Mary?
Where's my kids?

2445
01:55:57,618 --> 01:55:59,220
Watch him, Bert.
Come on, come on.

2446
01:55:59,253 --> 01:56:01,355
GEORGE: Bert, Ernie.
What's the matter
with you two guys?

2447
01:56:01,388 --> 01:56:02,990
You--you--you were here
on my wedding night.

2448
01:56:03,024 --> 01:56:04,658
You, both of you,
stood out there
on the porch

2449
01:56:04,691 --> 01:56:06,060
and sung to us,
don't you remember?

2450
01:56:06,093 --> 01:56:08,529
Think I'd better be going.
Look, now, why don't you
be a good kid,

2451
01:56:08,562 --> 01:56:09,930
and we'll take you in
to a doctor?

2452
01:56:09,963 --> 01:56:11,698
Everything's gonna
be all right.
Bert, no, listen to me.

2453
01:56:11,732 --> 01:56:13,634
Ernie,
will you take me over
to my mother's house?

2454
01:56:13,667 --> 01:56:16,203
Bert, listen.
It's that fellow here.
He says he's an angel.

2455
01:56:16,237 --> 01:56:17,638
He's trying
to hypnotize me.

2456
01:56:17,671 --> 01:56:19,506
I hate to do
this to you, bud, but...

2457
01:56:19,540 --> 01:56:20,974
(SCREAMING)

2458
01:56:21,008 --> 01:56:23,744
CLARENCE: Run, George!
Run, George! Run!
BERT: Ow!

2459
01:56:25,512 --> 01:56:26,880
Joseph! Help!

2460
01:56:26,913 --> 01:56:28,382
Oh, shut up.
Help!

2461
01:56:28,415 --> 01:56:31,218
Oh, Joseph! Joseph!

2462
01:56:36,990 --> 01:56:38,659
Where'd he go?
Where'd he go?

2463
01:56:38,692 --> 01:56:40,294
I had him right here.

2464
01:56:43,130 --> 01:56:45,099
I need a drink.

2465
01:56:45,132 --> 01:56:47,068
Well, which way did he go?
Help me find him.

2466
01:56:51,105 --> 01:56:52,573
(DOORBELL BUZZING)

2467
01:56:57,711 --> 01:56:59,080
Well?

2468
01:57:02,049 --> 01:57:03,250
Mother.

2469
01:57:05,319 --> 01:57:07,020
Mother? What do you want?

2470
01:57:08,455 --> 01:57:11,392
Mother, this is George.

2471
01:57:11,425 --> 01:57:13,260
I thought sure
you'd remember me.

2472
01:57:13,294 --> 01:57:14,828
George who?

2473
01:57:14,861 --> 01:57:16,697
If you're looking
for a room,
there's no vacancy.

2474
01:57:16,730 --> 01:57:18,432
Mother, listen.
Please help me.

2475
01:57:18,465 --> 01:57:20,167
Something terrible's
happened to me.

2476
01:57:20,201 --> 01:57:22,636
I don't know what it is.
Something's
happened to everybody.

2477
01:57:22,669 --> 01:57:25,672
Please let me come in,
and keep me here
until I get over it.

2478
01:57:25,706 --> 01:57:28,209
Get over what?
I don't take in
strangers

2479
01:57:28,242 --> 01:57:30,043
unless they're sent here
by somebody I know.

2480
01:57:30,077 --> 01:57:33,814
W-Well, I know everybody
you know.

2481
01:57:33,847 --> 01:57:36,049
Your brother-in-law,
Uncle Billy.

2482
01:57:36,083 --> 01:57:37,918
You know him?
Well, sure I do.

2483
01:57:37,951 --> 01:57:40,254
When did you see him last?
Today over at his house.

2484
01:57:40,287 --> 01:57:42,556
It's a lie. He's been
in the insane asylum

2485
01:57:42,589 --> 01:57:44,258
ever since he lost
his business.

2486
01:57:44,291 --> 01:57:46,227
And if you ask me,
that's where
you belong.

2487
01:57:59,173 --> 01:58:01,242
Strange, isn't it?

2488
01:58:01,275 --> 01:58:04,511
Each man's life
touches so many
other lives.

2489
01:58:04,545 --> 01:58:05,846
CLARENCE:
And when he isn't around,

2490
01:58:05,879 --> 01:58:07,581
he leaves an awful hole,
doesn't he?

2491
01:58:07,614 --> 01:58:08,849
I've heard of
things like this.

2492
01:58:08,882 --> 01:58:10,617
You got me in
some kind of
a spell or something.

2493
01:58:10,651 --> 01:58:12,919
Well, I'm gonna
get out of it.
I'll get out of it.

2494
01:58:12,953 --> 01:58:15,055
I know how, too. I...

2495
01:58:15,088 --> 01:58:16,390
The last man I talked to,

2496
01:58:16,423 --> 01:58:18,425
before all this stuff
started happening
to me, was Martini.

2497
01:58:18,459 --> 01:58:19,726
You know where he lives?

2498
01:58:19,760 --> 01:58:22,196
Well, sure,
I know where he lives.
He lives in Bailey Park.

2499
01:58:26,633 --> 01:58:28,902
Are you sure
this is Bailey Park?

2500
01:58:28,935 --> 01:58:31,805
No, I'm not sure
of anything anymore.

2501
01:58:31,838 --> 01:58:34,141
All I know is
this should be
Bailey Park.

2502
01:58:35,342 --> 01:58:37,110
But where are
the houses?

2503
01:58:37,144 --> 01:58:38,945
You weren't here
to build them.

2504
01:58:43,684 --> 01:58:46,720
Your brother Harry Bailey
broke through the ice

2505
01:58:46,753 --> 01:58:48,689
and was drowned
at the age of nine.

2506
01:58:48,722 --> 01:58:50,857
That's a lie.
Harry Bailey
went to war.

2507
01:58:50,891 --> 01:58:52,393
He got the Congressional
Medal of Honor.

2508
01:58:52,426 --> 01:58:54,495
He saved
the lives of every man
on that transport.

2509
01:58:54,528 --> 01:58:56,697
Every man
on that transport died.

2510
01:58:56,730 --> 01:58:57,964
Harry wasn't there
to save them,

2511
01:58:57,998 --> 01:59:00,267
because you weren't there
to save Harry.

2512
01:59:11,978 --> 01:59:13,547
You see, George?

2513
01:59:13,580 --> 01:59:15,882
You really had
a wonderful life.

2514
01:59:15,916 --> 01:59:20,754
Don't you see
what a mistake it would be
to throw it away?

2515
01:59:20,787 --> 01:59:22,723
Clarence.
Yes, George?

2516
01:59:23,657 --> 01:59:24,958
Where's Mary?

2517
01:59:24,991 --> 01:59:26,960
(STAMMERING)
Oh, well, I can't...

2518
01:59:26,993 --> 01:59:29,463
I don't know
how you know these things,
but tell me, where is she?

2519
01:59:29,496 --> 01:59:31,532
If you know where she is,
tell me where my wife is.

2520
01:59:31,565 --> 01:59:32,899
I'm not supposed to tell.

2521
01:59:32,933 --> 01:59:34,668
Please, Clarence,
tell me where she is.

2522
01:59:34,701 --> 01:59:37,003
You're not gonna
like it, George.
Where is she?

2523
01:59:37,037 --> 01:59:39,473
She's an old maid.
She never married.

2524
01:59:39,506 --> 01:59:41,107
Where is Mary?
Where is she?

2525
01:59:41,141 --> 01:59:44,811
Where is she?
She's just about to
close up the library!

2526
01:59:48,682 --> 01:59:52,085
(GROANING) There must be
some easier way for me
to get my wings.

2527
02:00:03,664 --> 02:00:05,065
GEORGE: Mary!

2528
02:00:10,404 --> 02:00:11,505
Mary!

2529
02:00:13,940 --> 02:00:15,075
Mary!

2530
02:00:16,443 --> 02:00:18,211
Mary! Mary!

2531
02:00:18,245 --> 02:00:20,881
Mary, it's George.
Don't you know me?
What's happened to us?

2532
02:00:20,914 --> 02:00:22,316
I don't know you.
Let me go!

2533
02:00:22,349 --> 02:00:23,917
Mary, please!
Oh, don't do this to me.

2534
02:00:23,950 --> 02:00:25,452
Please, Mary, help me.

2535
02:00:25,486 --> 02:00:27,120
Where's our kids?
I need you, Mary.

2536
02:00:27,153 --> 02:00:28,289
(SCREAMING)

2537
02:00:28,322 --> 02:00:29,556
Help me, Mary!

2538
02:00:30,491 --> 02:00:32,225
Mary! Let me go!

2539
02:00:32,259 --> 02:00:33,994
MARY: Help!
It's a wild man!

2540
02:00:35,228 --> 02:00:37,964
The wild man is chasing me.
Somebody stop him!

2541
02:00:37,998 --> 02:00:41,134
Tom! Ed! Charlie!

2542
02:00:41,167 --> 02:00:42,603
That's my wife!

2543
02:00:42,636 --> 02:00:44,538
(SCREAMING)

2544
02:00:45,272 --> 02:00:46,740
Mary!
MAN 1: No, you don't.

2545
02:00:46,773 --> 02:00:47,974
MAN 2: Somebody
call the police.

2546
02:00:48,008 --> 02:00:49,676
MAN 3: Somebody hit him
on the head with a bottle.

2547
02:00:49,710 --> 02:00:51,244
You need
a straightjacket.

2548
02:00:51,278 --> 02:00:52,646
(SIREN WAILING)

2549
02:00:52,679 --> 02:00:54,448
Clarence!

2550
02:00:54,481 --> 02:00:56,016
MAN: Get out of here!

2551
02:00:56,049 --> 02:00:57,318
Clarence!

2552
02:00:59,019 --> 02:01:00,153
GEORGE: Clarence!

2553
02:01:00,186 --> 02:01:01,355
Right, that's you!

2554
02:01:04,858 --> 02:01:06,226
Stand back!

2555
02:01:06,893 --> 02:01:08,495
(GUN FIRING)

2556
02:01:09,696 --> 02:01:10,997
Clarence!

2557
02:01:16,637 --> 02:01:18,872
(SIREN WAILING)

2558
02:01:20,240 --> 02:01:21,542
Clarence!

2559
02:01:26,480 --> 02:01:28,715
Clarence! Clarence!

2560
02:01:30,417 --> 02:01:31,885
Help me, Clarence!

2561
02:01:33,253 --> 02:01:35,456
Get me back!

2562
02:01:35,489 --> 02:01:37,758
Get me back. I don't care
what happens to me.

2563
02:01:38,759 --> 02:01:41,161
Get me back
to my wife and kids.

2564
02:01:41,194 --> 02:01:43,830
Help me, Clarence,
please.

2565
02:01:43,864 --> 02:01:48,402
Please. I want to live again.
I want to live again.

2566
02:01:50,236 --> 02:01:51,838
I want to live again.

2567
02:01:51,872 --> 02:01:54,074
(WIND STOPS HOWLING)
Please, God,
let me live again.

2568
02:01:55,842 --> 02:01:57,143
(SOBBING)

2569
02:02:03,283 --> 02:02:04,718
Hey, George!

2570
02:02:06,186 --> 02:02:07,388
George!

2571
02:02:08,288 --> 02:02:10,424
You all right.
Hey, what's the matter?

2572
02:02:10,457 --> 02:02:12,893
Now get out of here, Bert,
or I'll hit you again!
Get out of here!

2573
02:02:12,926 --> 02:02:14,695
What the sam hill
are you yelling for,
George?

2574
02:02:14,728 --> 02:02:16,229
You...

2575
02:02:17,564 --> 02:02:20,767
George?
Bert, do you know me?

2576
02:02:20,801 --> 02:02:22,869
Know you? You kidding?

2577
02:02:22,903 --> 02:02:25,038
I've been
looking all over town
trying to find you.

2578
02:02:25,071 --> 02:02:26,907
I saw your car
piled into that tree
down there,

2579
02:02:26,940 --> 02:02:28,208
and I thought maybe you...

2580
02:02:28,241 --> 02:02:30,477
Hey, your mouth's bleeding.
Are you sure
you're all right?

2581
02:02:30,511 --> 02:02:31,812
What did...

2582
02:02:34,247 --> 02:02:35,949
(LAUGHS)

2583
02:02:35,982 --> 02:02:37,851
My mouth's bleeding, Bert!

2584
02:02:37,884 --> 02:02:39,319
My mouth's...

2585
02:02:39,352 --> 02:02:42,456
Zuzu's petals. Zuzu...
There they are!

2586
02:02:42,489 --> 02:02:45,459
(SHOUTING) Bert! What
do you know about that?

2587
02:02:45,492 --> 02:02:47,260
Merry Christmas!

2588
02:02:47,861 --> 02:02:49,563
Well, Merry Christmas.

2589
02:02:49,596 --> 02:02:52,699
Mary! Mary!

2590
02:02:54,300 --> 02:02:56,102
(CHEERING)

2591
02:03:00,140 --> 02:03:01,475
(CHEERING)

2592
02:03:01,508 --> 02:03:03,610
Hello, Bedford Falls!

2593
02:03:06,480 --> 02:03:07,914
Merry Christmas!

2594
02:03:07,948 --> 02:03:09,716
MAN: Merry Christmas,
George!
WOMAN: Merry Christmas!

2595
02:03:09,750 --> 02:03:11,652
MAN 2: Merry Christmas,
George.

2596
02:03:11,685 --> 02:03:14,655
GEORGE: Merry Christmas,
movie house!

2597
02:03:14,688 --> 02:03:16,990
Merry Christmas,
emporium!

2598
02:03:18,191 --> 02:03:21,895
Merry Christmas,
you wonderful
old Building and Loan!

2599
02:03:26,166 --> 02:03:29,736
Hey, Merry Christmas,
Mr. Potter!

2600
02:03:29,770 --> 02:03:32,539
Happy New Year
to you in jail!

2601
02:03:32,573 --> 02:03:34,575
Go on home.
They're waiting for you.

2602
02:03:36,309 --> 02:03:39,312
GEORGE: Mary! Mary!

2603
02:03:41,014 --> 02:03:42,983
Mary!

2604
02:03:43,016 --> 02:03:45,919
Well, hello,
Mr. Bank Examiner!
How are you?

2605
02:03:45,952 --> 02:03:48,288
Mr. Bailey,
there's a deficit.
I know, $8,000.

2606
02:03:48,321 --> 02:03:49,556
George, I've got
a little paper here.

2607
02:03:49,590 --> 02:03:51,024
I'll bet it's a warrant
for my arrest.

2608
02:03:51,057 --> 02:03:52,759
Isn't it wonderful?
I'm going to jail!

2609
02:03:52,793 --> 02:03:55,261
Merry Christmas!
Reporters?
Where's Mary?

2610
02:03:55,295 --> 02:03:58,164
Mary!
Oh, look at this wonderful,
old drafty house.

2611
02:03:58,198 --> 02:04:00,467
Mary! Mary!

2612
02:04:01,802 --> 02:04:02,903
Mary.

2613
02:04:03,637 --> 02:04:05,271
Have you seen my wife?

2614
02:04:05,305 --> 02:04:08,341
CHILDREN:
Merry Christmas, Daddy.

2615
02:04:08,374 --> 02:04:10,343
Kids! Pete!

2616
02:04:12,979 --> 02:04:14,147
(LAUGHING)

2617
02:04:15,081 --> 02:04:16,349
Kids! Janie!

2618
02:04:16,382 --> 02:04:17,884
Janie! Tommy!

2619
02:04:19,986 --> 02:04:23,123
Let me look at you.
Oh, I could eat you up.

2620
02:04:23,156 --> 02:04:24,725
GEORGE:
Where's your mother?

2621
02:04:24,758 --> 02:04:26,627
PETE: She went looking
for you.
JANIE: With Uncle Billy.

2622
02:04:26,660 --> 02:04:28,529
Daddy!
Zuzu!

2623
02:04:28,562 --> 02:04:31,097
Zuzu, my little gingersnap.
How do you feel?

2624
02:04:31,131 --> 02:04:33,099
Fine!
Not a smidge
of temperature.

2625
02:04:33,133 --> 02:04:35,101
(LAUGHS) Not a smidge of...

2626
02:04:35,135 --> 02:04:37,771
GEORGE: Hallelujah!
Hello.

2627
02:04:37,804 --> 02:04:39,506
MARY: George!
George, darling!

2628
02:04:39,540 --> 02:04:40,974
Mary! Mary!

2629
02:04:41,007 --> 02:04:43,309
George, darling.
Where have you been?

2630
02:04:43,343 --> 02:04:45,478
Oh, George, George, George.

2631
02:04:45,512 --> 02:04:46,713
Mary.

2632
02:04:46,747 --> 02:04:48,214
Oh, let me touch you.

2633
02:04:48,248 --> 02:04:50,116
Let me touch you.
Are you real?

2634
02:04:51,484 --> 02:04:53,554
George, George.

2635
02:04:53,587 --> 02:04:55,556
You have no idea
what's happened to me.

2636
02:04:55,589 --> 02:04:57,390
You've no idea
what happened...

2637
02:04:58,458 --> 02:05:00,661
Well, come on, George.
Come on downstairs, quick.

2638
02:05:00,694 --> 02:05:02,062
They're on their way.
All right.

2639
02:05:02,095 --> 02:05:03,429
Come on.

2640
02:05:03,463 --> 02:05:04,665
(LAUGHS)

2641
02:05:05,732 --> 02:05:07,233
Come on
in here now.

2642
02:05:08,702 --> 02:05:10,403
Now, you stand
right over here
by the tree.

2643
02:05:10,436 --> 02:05:12,706
Right there,
and don't move.
Don't move.

2644
02:05:12,739 --> 02:05:14,675
What's happening?
Who's gonna come?

2645
02:05:14,708 --> 02:05:16,109
Oh, I hear them
coming now.

2646
02:05:16,142 --> 02:05:18,745
George, it's a miracle.
It's a miracle.

2647
02:05:18,779 --> 02:05:20,914
JANIE: What's happening?
What's happening?

2648
02:05:20,947 --> 02:05:22,716
PETE: Who's gonna
come, Daddy?
ZUZU: Who, Daddy?

2649
02:05:22,749 --> 02:05:24,618
GEORGE: I don't know.
Come in, Uncle Billy.

2650
02:05:24,651 --> 02:05:26,720
Everybody, in here.

2651
02:05:26,753 --> 02:05:28,622
George. George.

2652
02:05:29,455 --> 02:05:31,357
Here's everything
right here.

2653
02:05:31,391 --> 02:05:32,959
(ALL CHATTERING)

2654
02:05:32,993 --> 02:05:34,995
Isn't it wonderful?
So many friends.

2655
02:05:35,028 --> 02:05:36,663
Mary did it, George!
Mary did it!

2656
02:05:36,697 --> 02:05:38,331
She told some people
you were in trouble,

2657
02:05:38,364 --> 02:05:40,366
and they
scattered all over town
collecting money.

2658
02:05:40,400 --> 02:05:41,702
Didn't ask any questions.

2659
02:05:41,735 --> 02:05:43,336
Just said,
"George in trouble?
Then count me in."

2660
02:05:43,369 --> 02:05:45,138
What is this...
You never saw
anything like it.

2661
02:05:45,171 --> 02:05:47,340
...another run
on the bank?

2662
02:05:47,373 --> 02:05:49,643
Here you are, George.
Merry Christmas.

2663
02:05:49,676 --> 02:05:51,978
ERNIE: Now, don't crowd.
Don't push.
There we are.

2664
02:05:52,012 --> 02:05:53,647
The line forms
on the right.

2665
02:05:54,514 --> 02:05:56,016
MAN: More coming, George.

2666
02:05:56,049 --> 02:05:58,585
Merry Christmas,
and God bless you.

2667
02:05:59,820 --> 02:06:01,788
Merry Christmas.

2668
02:06:01,822 --> 02:06:04,224
Oh, Mr. Martini!
Merry Christmas.

2669
02:06:04,257 --> 02:06:06,760
ERNIE: Martini!
Step right up here.

2670
02:06:07,493 --> 02:06:09,596
I busted the jukebox, too.

2671
02:06:09,630 --> 02:06:10,997
(ALL LAUGHING)

2672
02:06:13,099 --> 02:06:14,635
Oh, Mr. Gower!

2673
02:06:16,870 --> 02:06:19,606
I made the rounds
of my charge accounts.

2674
02:06:27,447 --> 02:06:29,950
I'm not gonna go, George.
I changed my mind.

2675
02:06:30,851 --> 02:06:32,285
Violet Bick.

2676
02:06:33,053 --> 02:06:34,755
Oh, Annie! Annie!

2677
02:06:35,956 --> 02:06:38,291
I've been saving
this money
for a divorce,

2678
02:06:38,324 --> 02:06:40,326
if ever I get a husband.

2679
02:06:41,628 --> 02:06:42,796
ANNIE: Merry Christmas.

2680
02:06:44,998 --> 02:06:48,401
There you are, George.
I got the faculty
all up and out of bed.

2681
02:06:48,434 --> 02:06:50,270
Here's something
for you to play with.

2682
02:06:52,238 --> 02:06:53,840
I wouldn't have
a roof over my head

2683
02:06:53,874 --> 02:06:55,441
if it wasn't
for you, George.

2684
02:06:55,475 --> 02:06:57,277
ERNIE: Just a minute.
Just a minute.

2685
02:06:57,310 --> 02:06:59,145
Quiet, everybody.
Quiet, quiet.

2686
02:06:59,179 --> 02:07:01,047
Now, get this,
it's from London.

2687
02:07:01,081 --> 02:07:02,248
Oh!

2688
02:07:02,282 --> 02:07:04,951
"Mr. Gower cabled
you need cash. Stop.

2689
02:07:04,985 --> 02:07:09,322
"My office instructed
to advance you
up to $25,000. Stop.

2690
02:07:09,355 --> 02:07:12,358
"Hee-haw and Merry Christmas.
Sam Wainwright."

2691
02:07:12,392 --> 02:07:14,194
(ALL CHEERING)

2692
02:07:22,602 --> 02:07:25,538
And Mr. Martini.
How about some wine?

2693
02:07:25,571 --> 02:07:27,540
